window.WEEK_INFO={"1": "Week 1: Demand & Supply — Elasticities, Taxes, Price Controls, Trade & Externalities", "2": "Week 2: Firms & Factor Markets — Monopoly, Oligopoly, Network Goods, Labor", "3": "Week 3: Decision Making — Incentives, Asymmetric Information, Consumer Choice", "5": "Week 5: Economic Growth — GDP Measurement & the Solow Growth Model", "6": "Week 6: Business Fluctuations — AD/AS, Shocks, Unemployment & Inflation", "7": "Week 7: Macroeconomic Policy — Central Banks, Monetary Policy & International Finance"};
window.CONCEPTS=[{"id": "c5_price_elasticity_demand", "ch": 5, "week": 1, "name": "Price Elasticity of Demand", "star": true, "scene": "ある財の価格が $40 から $50 に上がったとき、需要量が 100 kg から 95 kg に減った。「価格が25%上がったら需要量が5%減る」と捉えるのが **price elasticity of demand**(需要の価格弾力性)の考え方。", "compare": {"a": "Elastic Demand", "b": "Inelastic Demand", "table": [{"dim": "Elasticity", "a": "|E| > 1", "b": "|E| < 1"}, {"dim": "Responsiveness", "a": "Quantity responds a lot", "b": "Quantity responds little"}, {"dim": "Price and total revenue", "a": "Move in opposite directions", "b": "Move together"}, {"dim": "Example good", "a": "Computer chips", "b": "Food"}]}, "punchline": "Price elasticity of demand is the responsiveness of quantity demanded to a change in price.", "defEN": "**Price elasticity of demand (Epd)** is the responsiveness of quantity demanded to a change in price. It is the **percentage change in quantity demanded divided by the percentage change in price**: Epd = %change-Qd / %change-P. Equivalently, Epd = (dQd/Qd) / (dP/P) = (dQd/dP) x (P/Qd). When **|E| > 1** demand is **elastic**, when **|E| < 1** demand is **inelastic**, and when **|E| = 1** demand is **unit elastic**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**price elasticity of demand**(需要の価格弾力性)は『価格が1%変わったら需要量が何%変わるか』です。\n\n--- 計算 ---\n**Epd** = %ΔQd / %ΔP\n\n--- 判定 ---\n• |E|>1 → **elastic**(弾力的)\n• |E|<1 → **inelastic**(非弾力的)\n• |E|=1 → **unit elastic**(単位弾力的)\n\nスライドの例: 価格が $40→$50(+25%)で需要量が 100→95 kg(−5%)。", "example": "Price increases from $40 to $50 (+25%) and quantity demanded falls from 100 kg to 95 kg (-5%), so Epd = -5% / 25% = -0.2 (inelastic).", "whyNeeded": "価格設定や税の帰着(**tax incidence**)、総収入(**total revenue**)の変化を予測するのに不可欠。試験では計算と **elastic / inelastic** の判定が頻出。", "mistakes": ["**elastic** と **inelastic** を逆にする誤り。|E|>1 が elastic。", "弾力性を傾き(**slope**)と同じだと考える誤り。スライド明記: Elasticity is not the same as slope。"], "memorize": "Elastic = |E|>1 (responsive); Inelastic = |E|<1 (rigid)"}, {"id": "c5_elasticity_vs_slope", "ch": 5, "week": 1, "name": "Elasticity Is Not Slope", "star": true, "scene": "1本の直線需要曲線上では、点 A・B・C の **slope**(傾き)はどこでも同じなのに、**elasticity** は点ごとに違う。上の方ほど弾力的。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Along a straight-line demand curve the slope is constant, but elasticity varies from point to point.", "defEN": "**Elasticity is not the same as slope.** On a single straight-line (linear) demand curve the **slope** is the same at every point, yet the **price elasticity of demand** differs at each point: |EA| > |EB| > |EC| as you move down the curve. A **flatter** curve through a common point is **more elastic** at a given quantity. Because two linear demand curves run through a common point, at any given quantity the steeper-to-flatter relationship determines which is more elastic, not the slope alone.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**slope**(傾き)と **elasticity**(弾力性)は別物です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 直線の需要曲線では slope は一定だが elasticity は点で変わる(スライド: |EA|>|EB|>|EC|)。\n• 共通点を通る2本の直線では、同じ数量で **flatter = more elastic**。\n\n演習Q2の正解は『slope ≠ elasticity だが、共通点を通るので任意の数量で曲線 A は B より elastic』。", "example": "On one straight-line demand curve, slope at A = slope at B = slope at C, but |EA| > |EB| > |EC|; the flatter curve is more elastic at a given quantity.", "whyNeeded": "図問題で『slope が elasticity に等しい』という誤答選択肢を排除するために必須。演習 Ch5 Q2(答え c)で直接問われた。", "mistakes": ["『Elasticity of demand equals the slope of the curve』と答える誤り(演習の誤答 a/b)。", "急な曲線ほど弾力的と思い込む誤り。実際は **flatter = more elastic**。"], "memorize": "Flatter = more elastic; slope constant, elasticity varies"}, {"id": "c5_determinants_demand_elasticity", "ch": 5, "week": 1, "name": "Determinants of Price Elasticity of Demand", "star": true, "scene": "なぜ塩は値上げしても買う量が変わらず、ある特定ブランドのジュースは少し値上げしただけで他社に流れるのか。**substitutes**(代替財)の数や時間などで決まる。", "compare": {"a": "Less Elastic", "b": "More Elastic", "table": [{"dim": "Substitutes", "a": "Fewer substitutes", "b": "More substitutes"}, {"dim": "Time horizon", "a": "Short run (less time)", "b": "Long run (more time)"}, {"dim": "Product definition", "a": "Categories of product", "b": "Specific brands"}, {"dim": "Type of good", "a": "Necessities", "b": "Luxuries"}, {"dim": "Budget share", "a": "Small part of budget", "b": "Large part of budget"}]}, "punchline": "Demand is more elastic with more substitutes, more time, specific brands, luxuries, and large budget shares.", "defEN": "The **determinants of price elasticity of demand** make demand **more elastic** when there are **more substitutes**, in the **long run** (more time to adjust), for **specific brands** rather than product categories, for **luxuries** rather than necessities, and when the good is a **large part of the budget**. Demand is **less elastic** in the opposite cases: fewer substitutes, short run, broad product categories, necessities, and small budget shares.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、需要が **elastic**(値段に敏感)になる条件をまとめたものです。\n\n--- More elastic になる条件 ---\n• 代替財が多い(**more substitutes**)\n• 長期(**long run**)\n• 特定ブランド(**specific brands**)\n• 贅沢品(**luxuries**)\n• 予算に占める割合が大きい(**large part of budget**)\n\n逆はすべて less elastic。", "example": "Demand for a specific brand of cola (many substitutes) is more elastic, while demand for the category food (a necessity) is inelastic.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch5 Q3(答え b)のように『どの財が最も inelastic / elastic か』を判定する問題で使う。", "mistakes": ["**necessities** を more elastic と勘違いする誤り。必需品は inelastic。", "短期(**short run**)を more elastic と取り違える誤り。長期ほど elastic。"], "memorize": "SLLLB elastic: Substitutes, Long run, Luxuries, brand-specific, Large budget share"}, {"id": "c5_elasticity_total_revenue", "ch": 5, "week": 1, "name": "Elasticity and Total Revenue", "star": true, "scene": "値下げセールで売上(総収入)が増えるか減るかは、需要が **elastic** か **inelastic** かで決まる。麻薬禁止が密売人の収入を上げてしまう理由もこれ。", "compare": {"a": "Elastic Demand (|E|>1)", "b": "Inelastic Demand (|E|<1)", "table": [{"dim": "When price rises", "a": "Total revenue falls", "b": "Total revenue rises"}, {"dim": "When price falls", "a": "Total revenue rises", "b": "Total revenue falls"}, {"dim": "Price and revenue", "a": "Move in opposite directions", "b": "Move together"}]}, "punchline": "Whether a price change raises or lowers total revenue depends on elasticity.", "defEN": "**Total revenue (TR) = Price x Quantity.** Price elasticity of demand tells you how revenue responds to a price change. **Case 1 (elastic, |E|>1):** price and revenue move in **opposite directions**, so a discount raises revenue. **Case 2 (inelastic, |E|<1):** price and revenue move **together**, so a price increase raises revenue. **Case 3 (unit elastic, |E|=1):** price changes but **revenue stays the same**. This explains why, with inelastic demand, prohibition (the War on Drugs) raises sellers' revenue.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**total revenue**(総収入=価格×数量)が価格変更でどう動くかは elasticity 次第です。\n\n--- ルール ---\n• **elastic**(|E|>1): 価格と収入は逆方向 → 値下げで収入↑\n• **inelastic**(|E|<1): 価格と収入は同方向 → 値上げで収入↑\n• **unit elastic**(|E|=1): 収入は変わらない\n\n応用: 需要が inelastic だと、禁止(**War on Drugs**)はかえって売り手の収入を増やす。", "example": "Food demand is inelastic, so when farm productivity rises and prices fall, farm revenues decline; computer chip demand is elastic, so falling chip prices raise chip revenues.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch5 Q5(価格 $4→$6 での総収入変化を面積 F−(E+B) で表す)で直接問われる頻出論点。", "mistakes": ["inelastic 財の値下げで収入が増えると考える誤り。inelastic では値上げで収入↑。", "**unit elastic** で収入が変わると思う誤り。実際は不変。"], "memorize": "Inelastic: P and TR move together. Elastic: P and TR move apart."}, {"id": "c5_other_elasticities", "ch": 5, "week": 1, "name": "Income and Cross-Price Elasticity of Demand", "star": false, "scene": "所得が増えたら需要量はどれだけ増えるか(**income elasticity**)、ある財の価格が変わったら別の財の需要量がどう動くか(**cross-price elasticity**)を測る。", "compare": {"a": "Income Elasticity (E_Id)", "b": "Cross-Price Elasticity (E_xyd)", "table": [{"dim": "Cause variable", "a": "Change in income (I)", "b": "Change in price of good y (Py)"}, {"dim": "Effect variable", "a": "Quantity demanded of the good", "b": "Quantity demanded of good x"}, {"dim": "Formula", "a": "(dQd/Qd) / (dI/I)", "b": "(dQxd/Qxd) / (dPy/Py)"}]}, "punchline": "Elasticity in general is % change in effect divided by % change in cause.", "defEN": "In general, **Elasticity = (% change in Effect) / (% change in Cause)**. The **income elasticity of demand (E_Id)** measures responsiveness of quantity demanded to a change in **income**: E_Id = (dQd/Qd) / (dI/I). The **cross-price elasticity of demand (E_xyd)** measures responsiveness of quantity demanded of good x to a change in the **price of good y**: E_xyd = (dQxd/Qxd) / (dPy/Py).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、弾力性は『効果の%変化 ÷ 原因の%変化』という一般形です。\n\n--- 種類 ---\n• **income elasticity (E_Id)**: 原因=所得 I の変化\n  E_Id = (ΔQd/Qd) / (ΔI/I)\n• **cross-price elasticity (E_xyd)**: 原因=別の財 y の価格 Py の変化\n  E_xyd = (ΔQxd/Qxd) / (ΔPy/Py)", "example": "If income rises 10% and quantity demanded rises 20%, income elasticity = 20% / 10% = 2.", "whyNeeded": "弾力性が価格だけでなく所得・他財価格にも一般化できることを示す。一般公式 %ΔEffect / %ΔCause を覚える基礎。", "mistakes": ["**cross-price elasticity** で自分の価格を使ってしまう誤り。原因は別財 y の価格。", "一般公式の分母(Cause)と分子(Effect)を取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "Elasticity = %Effect / %Cause (income uses I, cross uses Py)"}, {"id": "c5_price_elasticity_supply", "ch": 5, "week": 1, "name": "Price Elasticity of Supply", "star": true, "scene": "価格が20%上がったとき供給量が4%しか増えないなら供給は **inelastic**。爪楊枝は増産が容易で elastic、石油や金は単位コストが急増し inelastic。", "compare": {"a": "Less Elastic Supply", "b": "More Elastic Supply", "table": [{"dim": "Cost of more production", "a": "Needs much higher unit costs (oil, gold)", "b": "Little increase in unit costs (toothpick)"}, {"dim": "Share of input market", "a": "Large share of market for inputs", "b": "Small share of market for inputs"}, {"dim": "Scope of supply", "a": "Global supply", "b": "Local supply"}, {"dim": "Time horizon", "a": "Short run", "b": "Long run"}]}, "punchline": "Price elasticity of supply is the responsiveness of quantity supplied to a change in price.", "defEN": "**Price elasticity of supply (Eps)** is the responsiveness of quantity supplied to a change in price: Eps = (dQs/Qs) / (dP/P). Supply is **less elastic** when increased production requires **much higher unit costs** (oil, gold), when the good uses a **large share of the input market**, for **global** supply, and in the **short run**. Supply is **more elastic** when production can increase **without much higher unit costs** (toothpicks), uses a **small share of inputs**, is **local**, and in the **long run**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**price elasticity of supply**(供給の価格弾力性)は『価格が1%変わったら供給量が何%変わるか』です。\n\n--- 計算 ---\n**Eps** = (ΔQs/Qs) / (ΔP/P)\n\n--- More elastic の条件 ---\n• 増産でも単位コストが上がらない(toothpick)\n• 投入市場のシェアが小さい\n• 地域供給(local)\n• 長期(long run)\n\n週テスト Q1: 価格+20%で供給量+4% → Eps = 4/20 = 0.2(inelastic)。", "example": "If price rises 20% and quantity supplied rises 4%, Eps = 4% / 20% = 0.2 (inelastic).", "whyNeeded": "税の帰着や Gun Buyback プログラム分析の前提。週テスト Q1(答え c, 0.2)で直接計算が問われた。", "mistakes": ["供給弾力性の分子と分母を逆にし 20/4 = 5 と誤る(週テスト Q1 誤答 a)。正しくは 4/20 = 0.2。", "石油・金を more elastic と思う誤り。単位コストが急増するため less elastic。"], "memorize": "Eps = %ΔQs / %ΔP; toothpick elastic, oil inelastic"}, {"id": "c6_commodity_taxes", "ch": 6, "week": 1, "name": "Commodity Taxes", "star": true, "scene": "燃料・タバコ・酒にかかる税。政府が売り手に課しても買い手に課しても結果は同じ。誰が払った『ことになっている』かは関係ない。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A commodity tax has the same effect whether it is levied on buyers or sellers.", "defEN": "**Commodity taxes** are taxes on goods, such as those on fuel, cigarettes, and liquor. The government can tax sellers or buyers for every unit sold or bought. A key result: **a tax has exactly the same effects whether it is 'paid' by sellers or by buyers.** Who **ultimately** pays a tax is determined by the **relative elasticities of supply and demand**, not by who legally remits it.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**commodity taxes**(物品税)は燃料・タバコ・酒などの財にかかる税です。\n\n--- 重要な結論 ---\n• 売り手に課すか買い手に課すかで**効果は同じ**。\n• 最終的に誰が負担するか(**tax incidence**)は、**relative elasticities of supply and demand**(供給と需要の相対的弾力性)で決まる。\n\n税は買い手の払う価格と売り手の受け取る価格の間に **tax wedge** を打ち込む。", "example": "A $1 tax on gasoline has the same market effect whether it is collected from sellers or from buyers.", "whyNeeded": "税の図問題の出発点。『売り手課税と買い手課税は同じ』という結論は MC で頻出。", "mistakes": ["法的に課された側が実際の負担者だと考える誤り。負担は弾力性で決まる。", "**commodity tax** を所得税のような直接税と混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Tax on buyers = tax on sellers (same effect); incidence set by elasticities"}, {"id": "c6_tax_incidence", "ch": 6, "week": 1, "name": "Tax Incidence", "star": true, "scene": "同じ税でも、需要が inelastic な側(逃げられない側)が多く負担する。『Elastic = escape(逃げられる)』が合言葉。", "compare": {"a": "More Elastic Side", "b": "Less Elastic Side", "table": [{"dim": "Tax burden", "a": "Bears less of the tax (escapes)", "b": "Bears more of the tax"}, {"dim": "Subsidy benefit", "a": "Receives less of the benefit", "b": "Receives more of the benefit"}, {"dim": "Slogan", "a": "Elastic = escape", "b": "Inelastic = stuck"}]}, "punchline": "The more elastic side of the market escapes more of the tax.", "defEN": "**Tax incidence** is who ultimately bears the burden of a tax. It is determined by the **relative elasticities of supply and demand**. The slogan is **'Elastic = escape':** more of the tax burden falls on the **less elastic** side of the market. The side of the market (buyers or sellers) with the **more elastic** curve will **escape more of the tax**, and the side that bears more tax burden will also receive more of a subsidy's benefit.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**tax incidence**(税の帰着)は『実際に誰が税を負担するか』です。\n\n--- ルール ---\n• 決め手は **relative elasticities of supply and demand**。\n• 合言葉: **Elastic = escape**(弾力的な側ほど逃げる)。\n• 負担が重いのは **less elastic**(非弾力的)な側。\n• 多く負担した側は subsidy では多く恩恵を受ける。", "example": "If demand is more inelastic than supply, buyers bear most of a commodity tax because they cannot easily escape by reducing purchases.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch6 Q6(『買い手の税負担が最大になる需要・供給の組合せ』答え a: D0 and S0)など図問題で必須。", "mistakes": ["弾力的な側が多く負担すると考える誤り。逆で、less elastic な側が多く負担。", "**tax incidence** を法的納税者(legal liability)と混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Elastic = escape; the inelastic side pays more"}, {"id": "c6_tax_wedge", "ch": 6, "week": 1, "name": "Tax Wedge", "star": true, "scene": "$1 の税は、買い手が払う価格と売り手が受け取る価格の間に縦に『くさび(wedge)』を打ち込む。その縦の差がちょうど税額。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A tax drives a wedge equal to the tax between the buyer's price and the seller's price.", "defEN": "A tax drives a **tax wedge** between the price paid by buyers and the price received by sellers: **Tax = Price paid by buyers - Price received by sellers.** The wedge is a shortcut for tax analysis: you find the quantity where the vertical gap between the demand and supply curves equals the tax, then read off the buyer's price (on demand) and seller's price (on supply).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**tax wedge**(税のくさび)は買い手価格と売り手価格の縦の差で、それが税額です。\n\n--- 公式 ---\n**Tax = Price paid by buyers − Price received by sellers**\n\n--- 使い方 ---\n需要曲線と供給曲線の縦の差が税額になる数量を探し、買い手価格・売り手価格を読み取る。演習 Ch6 Q3/Q5 はこのくさびの大きさ(=税額)を図から読む問題。", "example": "If a tax makes buyers pay $3.50 while sellers receive $2.50, the tax wedge = $3.50 - $2.50 = $1.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch6 Q3(税額 $3)・Q5(税額 $4)・Q4(買い手価格 $3.50)など図から税額や価格を読む問題で直接使う。", "mistakes": ["wedge を片側の価格変化だけで測る誤り。wedge は買い手価格−売り手価格の差全体。", "税額と税収(**tax revenue** = 税額×数量)を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Wedge = Buyer's price - Seller's price = the tax"}, {"id": "c6_tax_revenue_dwl", "ch": 6, "week": 1, "name": "Tax Revenue and Deadweight Loss", "star": true, "scene": "$1 の税をかけると取引量が減る。税収(税額×取引量)は政府の収入だが、減った取引のぶんは誰の手にも渡らない損失=**deadweight loss**。", "compare": {"a": "Elastic Demand/Supply", "b": "Inelastic Demand/Supply", "table": [{"dim": "Trades deterred by tax", "a": "Many trades deterred", "b": "Few trades deterred"}, {"dim": "Lost gains from trade", "a": "Greater lost gains", "b": "Fewer lost gains"}, {"dim": "Deadweight loss (DWL)", "a": "Larger DWL", "b": "Smaller DWL"}]}, "punchline": "Taxes shrink quantity traded and create a deadweight loss that grows with elasticity.", "defEN": "A tax raises **tax revenue = tax x quantity traded** but reduces the quantity traded, creating a **deadweight loss (DWL)** - the lost gains from trades that no longer happen. **More elastic** demand or supply means a tax **deters many trades**, so there are **greater lost gains from trade** and a larger DWL. **Less elastic** demand or supply means **little deterrence** and a smaller DWL. The more elastic either curve is, the greater the DWL.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、税は取引量を減らし、消えた取引ぶんの損失=**deadweight loss (DWL)** を生みます。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• **tax revenue** = 税額 × 取引量(政府の収入)。\n• DWL = 税で行われなくなった取引の失われた利益。\n• **more elastic** → 多くの取引が止まる → DWL 大。\n• **less elastic** → ほとんど止まらない → DWL 小。\n\n演習 Ch6 Q7: $2 の税で失われた consumer surplus は B+E。週テスト Q2: 税収 = $1,800。", "example": "A $2 tax that lowers traded quantity creates a deadweight loss; with elastic demand many trades are deterred, so the DWL is large.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch6 Q2/Q7 と週テスト Q2 で税収・余剰・DWL を面積で読む。試験最頻出テーマの一つ。", "mistakes": ["**tax revenue** を DWL と混同する誤り。税収は転移(transfer)、DWL は純損失。", "inelastic ほど DWL が大きいと考える誤り。逆で elastic ほど DWL 大。"], "memorize": "Tax revenue = tax x Q (transfer); DWL grows with elasticity"}, {"id": "c6_subsidies", "ch": 6, "week": 1, "name": "Subsidies", "star": true, "scene": "**subsidy**(補助金)は『逆の税』。政府が消費者か生産者にお金を渡す。価値より費用が高い財まで作らせてしまい、無駄(waste)を生む。", "compare": {"a": "Tax", "b": "Subsidy", "table": [{"dim": "Direction", "a": "Government takes money", "b": "Government gives money (reverse tax)"}, {"dim": "Quantity traded", "a": "Decreases", "b": "Increases"}, {"dim": "Welfare effect", "a": "Creates deadweight loss", "b": "Creates deadweight loss"}, {"dim": "Who gains/bears most", "a": "Less elastic side bears most burden", "b": "Less elastic side gets most benefit"}]}, "punchline": "A subsidy is a reverse tax that raises quantity but still creates a deadweight loss.", "defEN": "A **subsidy** is a **reverse tax** in which the government gives money to consumers or producers. Like a tax, its incidence depends on relative elasticities: the side that bears more of a tax burden also receives more of the subsidy benefit. **Subsidies increase the quantity traded**, but because they cause goods to be produced **for which the cost exceeds the value, they create waste** - a deadweight loss. Both taxes and subsidies generate a DWL.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**subsidy**(補助金)は『逆の税』で、政府が消費者や生産者にお金を渡します。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 税は取引量を減らし、subsidy は取引量を**増やす**。\n• ただし価値<費用の財まで作らせるので **waste**(DWL)が出る。\n• 負担が重い側(less elastic)が subsidy では恩恵も大きい。\n\nスライド: ΔCS, ΔPS, Cost to gov't, DWL をそれぞれ面積で考える。", "example": "A subsidy that pushes production to units where cost exceeds value creates waste, just as a tax that blocks valuable trades creates a deadweight loss.", "whyNeeded": "税と対称な論点として頻出。『誰が恩恵を受けるか』は弾力性で決まる点が税と共通。", "mistakes": ["subsidy には DWL がないと思う誤り。価値<費用の生産で DWL が生じる。", "subsidy が必ず消費者を最も助けると考える誤り。実際は less elastic な側。"], "memorize": "Subsidy = reverse tax: raises Q, still has DWL"}, {"id": "c8_price_controls", "ch": 8, "week": 1, "name": "Price Controls", "star": false, "scene": "価格が上限を超えるのを禁じる **price ceiling**、下限を割るのを禁じる **price floor**。市場のシグナルに干渉する法律。", "compare": {"a": "Price Ceiling", "b": "Price Floor", "table": [{"dim": "Definition", "a": "Maximum legal price", "b": "Minimum legal price"}, {"dim": "Binding when", "a": "Set below market price", "b": "Set above market price"}, {"dim": "Result", "a": "Shortage (Qd > Qs)", "b": "Surplus (Qs > Qd)"}]}, "punchline": "Price controls cap or floor prices and interfere with market signals.", "defEN": "**Price controls** are laws making it illegal for prices to move **above a maximum price (price ceilings)** or **below a minimum price (price floors)**. They **interfere with market signals**. A binding price ceiling is set below the market price and creates a shortage; a binding price floor is set above the market price and creates a surplus.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**price controls**(価格統制)は価格が一定の上下限を越えるのを違法にする法律です。\n\n--- 2種類 ---\n• **price ceiling**(価格上限): 最高価格。市場価格より下に設定すると拘束的 → **shortage**。\n• **price floor**(価格下限): 最低価格。市場価格より上に設定すると拘束的 → **surplus**。\n\nどちらも市場のシグナルに干渉する。", "example": "A price ceiling set below the market price (e.g. rent control) is binding and causes a shortage; a price floor above the market price causes a surplus.", "whyNeeded": "Ch8 全体の枠組み。演習 Ch8 Q4 では『不足15単位 → price ceiling $10』のように上限/下限を判定する。", "mistakes": ["**price ceiling** と **price floor** を逆にする誤り。ceiling=上限=不足、floor=下限=余剰。", "市場価格より高い ceiling や低い floor が拘束的と思う誤り(その場合は非拘束)。"], "memorize": "Ceiling = max price = shortage; Floor = min price = surplus"}, {"id": "c8_price_ceilings", "ch": 8, "week": 1, "name": "Price Ceilings", "star": true, "scene": "価格上限が市場価格より低いと需要量が供給量を上回り **shortage**(不足)が起きる。さらに品質低下や行列、賄賂まで生じる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A binding price ceiling causes shortages and four other harmful effects.", "defEN": "When a **price ceiling** is set below the market price, **Qd > Qs**, which leads to a **shortage**. Price ceilings create five effects: (1) **shortages**, (2) **reductions in product quality** (sellers evade the law by cutting quality or service), (3) **wasteful lines and other search costs** (buyers pay via bribes to suppliers or time in line that goes to no one), (4) a **loss of gains from trade (DWL)**, and (5) a **misallocation of resources** (goods do not flow to their highest-valued uses).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、市場価格より低い **price ceiling** は需要超過(Qd > Qs)を生み **shortage**(不足)になります。\n\n--- 5つの効果 ---\n1. **Shortages**(不足)\n2. **Reductions in quality**(品質・サービス低下)\n3. **Wasteful lines / search costs**(行列・賄賂。賄賂は供給者へ、行列の時間は誰にも渡らない)\n4. **Lost gains from trade (DWL)**\n5. **Misallocation of resources**(資源が最高価値の用途へ流れない)\n\n演習 Ch8 Q5: 上限で値上げできない売り手は品質を下げる(答え c)。Q6: 上限 $2 で $1 の賄賂が発生。", "example": "At a price ceiling of $2 where buyers value the good at $3, bribes of $1 per unit may be common, and sellers cut quality because they face excess demand.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch8 Q3-Q7 で shortage 量・賄賂・失われた producer surplus を計算。試験頻出。", "mistakes": ["**price ceiling** が surplus を生むと考える誤り。ceiling は shortage。", "賄賂(supplier に渡る)と行列の時間(誰にも渡らない)を同一視する誤り。"], "memorize": "Ceiling effects: Shortage, Quality down, Lines/bribes, DWL, Misallocation"}, {"id": "c8_price_floors_minimum_wage", "ch": 8, "week": 1, "name": "Price Floors and Minimum Wage", "star": true, "scene": "価格下限が市場価格より高いと供給量が需要量を上回り **surplus**(余剰)が出る。労働市場では最低賃金が高すぎると失業(労働の余剰)が生じる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A binding price floor causes surpluses; a high minimum wage creates a labor surplus and deadweight loss.", "defEN": "When a **price floor** is set above the market price, **Qs > Qd**, creating a **surplus**. Price floors create four effects: (1) **surpluses**, (2) a **loss of gains from trade (DWL)**, (3) **wasteful increases in quality** (sellers who can't lower prices compete by offering quality buyers wouldn't otherwise pay for), and (4) a **misallocation of resources**. In a labor market, a **minimum wage** above the equilibrium wage is a price floor that produces a labor surplus (unemployment) and a deadweight loss.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、市場価格より高い **price floor** は供給超過(Qs > Qd)を生み **surplus**(余剰)になります。\n\n--- 4つの効果 ---\n1. **Surpluses**(余剰)\n2. **Lost gains from trade (DWL)**\n3. **Wasteful increases in quality**(値下げ競争できず過剰な品質で競争)\n4. **Misallocation of resources**\n\n労働市場では **minimum wage**(最低賃金)が均衡賃金より高いと price floor となり、労働の余剰(失業)と DWL を生む。演習 Ch8 Q8: 最低賃金 $7 の DWL は X+Z。", "example": "A minimum wage of $7 above the equilibrium wage causes a deadweight loss (e.g. areas X + Z in the labor-market figure).", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch8 Q8 で最低賃金の DWL を面積で問う。price floor と minimum wage の対応は試験頻出。", "mistakes": ["**price floor** が shortage を生むと考える誤り。floor は surplus。", "price ceiling は品質低下、price floor は過剰品質、と逆に覚える誤り。"], "memorize": "Floor effects: Surplus, DWL, Quality UP (wasteful), Misallocation"}, {"id": "c9_gains_from_trade", "ch": 9, "week": 1, "name": "Gains from International Trade", "star": true, "scene": "国境を越える貿易でも基本原理は同じ。好みの違い、専門化(**specialization**)、**comparative advantage**(比較優位)を通じて、人々はより豊かになる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "International trade makes people better off through specialization and comparative advantage.", "defEN": "**International trade is trade across national borders.** The basic principles of trade still apply: (1) trade makes people better off when **preferences differ**; (2) trade increases productivity through **specialization and the division of knowledge**; and (3) trade increases productivity through **comparative advantage**. When a country opens to trade at the **world price**, it can import goods more cheaply than it could produce them, exploiting gains from trade.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**international trade**(国際貿易)は国境を越える取引で、国内取引と同じ利益を生みます。\n\n--- 3つの原理 ---\n1. 好みが違うとき取引で双方が得をする(**preferences differ**)\n2. **specialization**(専門化)と知識の分業で生産性↑\n3. **comparative advantage**(比較優位)で生産性↑\n\n世界価格(**world price**)で貿易を開くと、自国生産より安く輸入でき gains from trade を得る。演習 Ch9 Q3: 国内生産量 = 800。", "example": "At the world price, domestic production might be 800 units while the rest of demand is met by imports, raising total consumer gains.", "whyNeeded": "Ch9 の供給需要分析の土台。演習 Ch9 Q3(国内生産量 800)で需給と世界価格を読む。", "mistakes": ["国際貿易が国内取引と別原理だと考える誤り。基本原理は同じ。", "**comparative advantage** を absolute advantage と混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Trade gains: differing preferences, specialization, comparative advantage"}, {"id": "c9_import_tariff", "ch": 9, "week": 1, "name": "Import Tariff and Its Welfare Effects", "star": true, "scene": "輸入品にかける税=**tariff**(関税)。価格が上がるので国内生産は増え、国内消費は減り、輸入は減る。政府は税収を得るが **deadweight loss** が発生。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A tariff raises domestic prices, cuts imports, gives the government revenue, and creates deadweight loss.", "defEN": "An **import tariff** is a tax on imported goods that raises their price. Its effects: **domestic suppliers respond to the higher price by increasing production**; **domestic consumers respond by buying less**; **imports decrease**; **government revenue = tariff rate x import quantity**; and the tariff creates a **deadweight loss (DWL)**. Trade restrictions waste resources by transferring production from low-cost foreign producers to high-cost domestic producers and prevent consumers from exploiting gains from trade. Domestic producers benefit, but **domestic consumers lose more than the producers gain**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**import tariff**(輸入関税)は輸入品にかける税で、価格を上げます。\n\n--- 効果 ---\n• 国内生産者: 価格↑で生産を**増やす**\n• 国内消費者: 価格↑で購入を**減らす**\n• 輸入: **減る**\n• 政府: **revenue = tariff rate × import quantity**\n• **DWL** 発生\n\n貿易制限は低コストの外国生産者から高コストの国内生産者へ生産を移し資源を浪費。生産者は得をするが**消費者の損 > 生産者の得**。演習 Ch9 Q4: $1 関税で輸入が8000万単位減少。", "example": "A $1 tariff raises the domestic price, so imports decrease by 80 million units; government revenue equals the tariff rate times the remaining import quantity.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch9 Q4(関税で輸入−80M)で関税の数量効果を読む。welfare(消費者損>生産者得)は MC 頻出。", "mistakes": ["関税で消費者が得をすると考える誤り。消費者は価格↑で損をする。", "政府の **tariff revenue** を社会全体の純利益と混同する誤り。DWL がある。"], "memorize": "Tariff: domestic prod UP, consumption DOWN, imports DOWN, gov revenue, DWL"}, {"id": "c9_arguments_against_free_trade", "ch": 9, "week": 1, "name": "Arguments Against Free Trade", "star": false, "scene": "『雇用を守れ』『児童労働の国とは取引するな』『安全保障のため国内に残せ』『重要産業の波及効果』など、自由貿易への反対論。保護は小集団に集中する利益のため残りやすい。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Common anti-trade arguments include saving jobs, child labor, national security, and key industries.", "defEN": "Common **arguments against free international trade** are: trade reduces the number of **domestic jobs**; it is wrong to trade with countries that use **child labor**; we need to keep certain jobs at home for **national security**; and keeping **'key' industries** at home has beneficial spillovers. Trade restrictions sometimes persist because the **benefits are concentrated** on small groups who lobby for protection, while the **costs are spread over millions of consumers** and are small for each individual.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、自由貿易への代表的な反対論をまとめたものです。\n\n--- 4つの主張 ---\n1. **domestic jobs**(国内雇用)を守る\n2. **child labor**(児童労働)の国とは取引すべきでない\n3. **national security**(安全保障)\n4. **key industries**(重要産業)の波及効果\n\n--- 保護が残る理由 ---\n• 利益が小集団に**集中**(ロビー活動)\n• 費用が多数の消費者に**分散**(一人当たりは小さい)\n\n演習 Ch9 Q5: 英国醸造業者が関税を支持 → 『saving domestic jobs』(答え a)。", "example": "British brewers lobbying for tariffs on French wine to avoid foreign competition fits the 'saving domestic jobs' argument.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch9 Q5 で反対論の分類を直接問う。なぜ非効率な保護が続くか(集中する利益)も頻出。", "mistakes": ["これらの反対論を経済的に正当な利益と取り違える誤り。スライドは制限のコストを強調。", "集中する利益(concentrated benefits)と分散するコストの非対称性を見落とす誤り。"], "memorize": "Anti-trade: Jobs, Child labor, National security, Key industries"}, {"id": "c10_externalities", "ch": 10, "week": 1, "name": "Externalities", "star": true, "scene": "取引の当事者ではない第三者(bystanders)に降りかかる費用や便益。抗生物質の乱用は他人に強い耐性菌という外部費用を、ワクチンは他人を守る外部便益を生む。", "compare": {"a": "Negative Externality (External Cost)", "b": "Positive Externality (External Benefit)", "table": [{"dim": "Falls on", "a": "Bystanders pay a cost", "b": "Bystanders receive a benefit"}, {"dim": "Identity", "a": "Cost paid by non-traders", "b": "Benefit received by non-traders"}, {"dim": "Market outcome", "a": "Good is overused (e.g. antibiotics)", "b": "Good is underused (e.g. vaccines)"}, {"dim": "Total relation", "a": "Social cost = private cost + external cost", "b": "Social benefit = private benefit + external benefit"}]}, "punchline": "Externalities are costs or benefits that fall on bystanders, making the market outcome inefficient.", "defEN": "**Externalities** are costs or benefits that fall on **bystanders** (people other than the consumers or producers trading in the market). An **external cost (negative externality)** is a cost paid by people other than the consumers or producers - e.g. **antibiotics are overused** because users get all the benefits but do not bear all of the costs (stronger, resistant bacteria for non-users). An **external benefit (positive externality)** is a benefit received by others - e.g. **vaccines are underused** because the vaccinated person bears all the costs but others gain too. Key identities: **Social cost = private cost + external cost** and **Social benefit = private benefit + external benefit**. With externalities, market prices do not signal true costs and benefits, so the market outcome is inefficient.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**externalities**(外部性)は取引の当事者でない第三者(**bystanders**)にかかる費用や便益です。\n\n--- 2種類 ---\n• **external cost / negative externality**: 当事者以外が払う費用。例: 抗生物質は **overused**(利用者は便益だけ得て耐性菌のコストを負わない)。\n  **Social cost = private cost + external cost**\n• **external benefit / positive externality**: 当事者以外が得る便益。例: ワクチンは **underused**(打つ人が全コストを負担し他人も守られる)。\n  **Social benefit = private benefit + external benefit**\n\n外部性があると価格が真の費用・便益を示さず市場結果は非効率。演習 Ch10 Q1: 外部便益 = $4。", "example": "Antibiotics: users get the benefit but non-users bear the cost of resistant bacteria, so social cost = private cost + external cost and the good is overused.", "whyNeeded": "Ch10 全体の核心。演習 Ch10 Q1(外部便益 $4)・Q3(外部費用 $3 の課税)で社会的費用と効率量を計算。", "mistakes": ["**negative**(過剰利用)と **positive**(過少利用)外部性を逆にする誤り。", "social cost に external cost を足し忘れる誤り。Social = private + external。"], "memorize": "Social = private + external; negative = overused, positive = underused"}, {"id": "c10_government_solutions", "ch": 10, "week": 1, "name": "Government Solutions: Pigouvian Taxes, Subsidies, and Tradable Allowances", "star": true, "scene": "外部性を直すための政府の手段。命令で量を決める **command and control**、外部性を価格に織り込む **Pigouvian tax/subsidy**、排出枠を売買させる **tradable allowances**。", "compare": {"a": "Negative Externality", "b": "Positive Externality", "table": [{"dim": "Command and control", "a": "Order firms to make/use less", "b": "Order firms to make/use more"}, {"dim": "Tax or subsidy", "a": "Pigouvian tax", "b": "Pigouvian subsidy"}, {"dim": "Goal", "a": "Internalize external cost", "b": "Internalize external benefit"}]}, "punchline": "Governments fix externalities via command and control, Pigouvian taxes/subsidies, or tradable allowances.", "defEN": "Three **government solutions to externality problems**: (1) **Command and control** - order firms to make or use less (more) for a negative (positive) externality; it is costly and inflexible. (2) **Tax/subsidy to internalize externalities** - adjusting incentives so decision makers take into account all private and social costs and benefits: a **Pigouvian tax** for negative externalities and a **Pigouvian subsidy** for positive externalities. (3) **Tradable allowances** - permits to emit that firms can buy and sell, achieving abatement at lowest total cost. **Internalizing externalities** means making decision makers account for both private and social effects.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、外部性を直す政府の3手段です。\n\n--- 3手段 ---\n1. **Command and control**(命令統制): 負(正)の外部性で生産・利用を減らせ(増やせ)と命令。費用がかかり柔軟性に欠ける。\n2. **Tax/subsidy で internalizing externalities**: 私的+社会的費用便益を意思決定に織り込む。\n   • 負の外部性 → **Pigouvian tax**\n   • 正の外部性 → **Pigouvian subsidy**\n3. **Tradable allowances**(取引可能な排出枠): 排出権を売買させ最小費用で削減。\n\n演習 Ch10 Q2: 4トン削減を排出枠取引で行うと総費用 $400(最小費用)。Q3: 外部費用 $3 への $3 課税で効率量へ。", "example": "For pollution, a Pigouvian tax equal to the external cost internalizes it; with tradable allowances, reducing 4 tons of pollution can cost as little as $400 when firms trade permits.", "whyNeeded": "演習 Ch10 Q2(tradable allowances で $400)・Q3(Pigouvian $3 tax)で直接問われる。手段の対応関係は MC 頻出。", "mistakes": ["負の外部性に Pigouvian subsidy を当てる誤り。負には **tax**、正には **subsidy**。", "**tradable allowances** が command and control より高コストと思う誤り。柔軟で低コスト。"], "memorize": "Negative -> Pigouvian tax; Positive -> Pigouvian subsidy; permits = tradable allowances"}, {"id": "c10_coase_theorem", "ch": 10, "week": 1, "name": "Coase Theorem", "star": true, "scene": "政府でなく当事者同士の交渉でも外部性を解決できる。取引費用(**transaction costs**)が低く所有権(**property rights**)が明確なら、私的な取り決めで効率的な結果になる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "If transaction costs are low and property rights are clear, private bargains can fix externalities efficiently.", "defEN": "The **Coase theorem** states that if **transaction costs are low** and **property rights are clearly defined**, **private bargains will ensure that the market equilibrium is efficient even when there are externalities**. **Transaction costs** are all the costs necessary to reach an agreement - identifying and bringing buyers and sellers together, bargaining, and drawing up a contract. In practice the theorem's conditions are often not met: transaction costs for many externalities are high and property rights are often not clearly defined.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**Coase theorem**(コースの定理)は『取引費用が低く所有権が明確なら、外部性があっても当事者の私的交渉で効率的になる』という命題です。\n\n--- 条件 ---\n• **transaction costs**(取引費用)が低い\n• **property rights**(所有権)が明確\n\n--- transaction costs とは ---\n合意に至るまでの全費用(買い手と売り手を見つける・交渉・契約作成など)。\n\n--- 現実 ---\n条件は満たされにくい(取引費用が高い/所有権が不明確)。週テスト Q3: 私的当事者が外部性を自力で解決できる命題 = Coase theorem(答え c)。", "example": "If property rights to clean air are clear and bargaining is cheap, a factory and its neighbors can negotiate a private deal that reaches the efficient outcome.", "whyNeeded": "週テスト Q3 で定義そのものが問われた(答え c)。私的解決 vs 政府解決の対比で頻出。", "mistakes": ["**Coase theorem** を政府の解決策と取り違える誤り。これは private solution。", "条件(low transaction costs かつ clear property rights)のどちらかを落とす誤り。両方必要。"], "memorize": "Coase: low transaction costs + clear property rights -> private bargain is efficient"}, {"id": "c13_market_power", "ch": 13, "week": 2, "name": "Market Power", "star": true, "scene": "ある企業が、他社の参入を恐れることなく価格を限界費用より高く設定できる状況。これが **market power**(市場支配力)。市場支配力を持つ企業が **monopoly**(独占企業)。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Market power is the power to raise price above marginal cost (P > MC) without fear of entry.", "defEN": "**Market power** is the power to raise price above marginal cost (**P > MC**) without fear that other firms will enter the market. A **monopoly** is a firm with market power. A monopolist faces a **downward sloping demand curve**: the firm must lower its price to sell an additional unit.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**market power**(市場支配力)は『他社の参入を気にせず価格を **MC** より上げられる力』です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• **P > MC** が可能\n• **monopoly** = market power を持つ企業\n• 需要曲線が **downward sloping**(右下がり)→ 1単位多く売るには値下げが必要", "example": "A monopolist faces a downward sloping demand curve and can set P > MC, unlike a competitive firm where P = MC.", "whyNeeded": "独占・寡占・独占的競争すべての出発点。**market power** があると **P > MC** となり効率が失われる(**deadweight loss**)。試験では P と MC の関係でほぼ必ず問われる。", "mistakes": ["**market power** と単なる『大企業』を混同する誤り。本質は P > MC を恐れず設定できること。", "競争企業(price-taker)では P = MC、独占では P > MC。逆にしない。"], "memorize": "Market power = set P above MC, no fear of entry"}, {"id": "c13_marginal_revenue_monopoly", "ch": 13, "week": 2, "name": "Marginal Revenue (Monopoly)", "star": true, "scene": "独占企業が1単位多く売るには価格を下げねばならないため、追加収入(**marginal revenue**)が今の価格より小さくなる状況。直線需要では **MR** 曲線は需要曲線の2倍の傾き。", "compare": {"a": "Demand Curve", "b": "Marginal Revenue Curve", "table": [{"dim": "Definition", "a": "Price at each quantity (P = AR)", "b": "Change in total revenue from one more unit"}, {"dim": "For monopoly", "a": "MR < P (below demand)", "b": "Twice as steep as demand (linear case)"}, {"dim": "Starting point", "a": "Same intercept", "b": "Same intercept as demand"}]}, "punchline": "For a monopolist, marginal revenue is less than price (MR < P).", "defEN": "**Marginal Revenue (MR)** is the change in total revenue from selling an additional unit: MR = Δ(TR)/ΔQ. Because a monopolist must lower price to sell more, the additional revenue per unit is less than the current price: **MR < P**. For a linear demand curve, the **MR curve is twice as steep as the demand curve** and starts at the same intercept.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**marginal revenue (MR)** は『もう1単位売ったときに総収入(**TR**)がどれだけ増えるか』です。\n\n--- 計算 ---\n**MR** = Δ(TR)/ΔQ\n\n--- 試験ポイント ---\n• 独占では **MR < P**(価格を下げないと追加で売れないから)\n• 直線需要では MR 曲線は需要曲線と同じ切片で傾きが2倍", "example": "R1 = 16 × 2 = 32; R2 = 14 × 3 = 42; MR = Δ(TR)/ΔQ = 42 − 32 = 10, which is less than the price of 14 (MR < P).", "whyNeeded": "利潤最大化条件 **MR = MC** を解く前提。直線需要なら MR の式を即座に書ける(切片同じ・傾き2倍)ことが計算問題で必須。", "mistakes": ["**MR < P** を MR = P と誤る(それは競争企業のみ)。", "MR 曲線の傾きを需要曲線と同じにする誤り。直線需要では2倍steep。"], "memorize": "Linear demand: MR same intercept, twice the slope; MR < P"}, {"id": "c13_profit_max_monopoly", "ch": 13, "week": 2, "name": "Profit Maximization (MR = MC)", "star": true, "scene": "独占企業が利潤を最大化する生産量を選ぶ場面。条件は **MR = MC**。価格はその数量を需要曲線に当てて読む。利潤は (P − AC)Q。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A monopolist maximizes profit where marginal revenue equals marginal cost: MR = MC.", "defEN": "**Profit maximization** for a monopolist occurs where **MR = MC**. MR is the change in total revenue from selling an additional unit; MC is the change in total cost from selling an additional unit. **Profit (π) = TR − TC = (P − AC)Q**. The profit-maximizing price is read off the demand curve at the profit-maximizing quantity, so **P > MR** at that quantity.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、独占の利潤最大化は **MR = MC** で生産量を決めることです。\n\n--- 手順 ---\n1. MR = MC を解いて Q* を出す\n2. 需要曲線に Q* を代入して P* を読む\n3. π = TR − TC = (P − AC)Q\n\n--- 注意 ---\n• 独占では P > MR(価格は MR より上)", "example": "Demand P = 50 − 0.5Q, MR = 50 − Q, MC = 5. Set MR = MC: 50 − Q = 5 → Q = 45. P = 50 − 0.5(45) = 27.5. Profit = TR − TC = (45 × 27.5) − (45 × 5) = 1237.5 − 225 = 1012.5.", "whyNeeded": "週の計算問題の中心。MR=MC で Q を解き、P を需要から読み、利潤を出す流れは演習・週テストで頻出。", "mistakes": ["MR=MC の Q を需要式でなく MR 式に入れて P を出す誤り。価格は需要曲線から読む。", "利潤を P×Q(=TR) と取り違える誤り。利潤は TR − TC =(P−AC)Q。"], "memorize": "MR = MC → find Q*, read P off demand, π = (P−AC)Q"}, {"id": "c13_elasticity_markup", "ch": 13, "week": 2, "name": "Elasticity of Demand and Markup", "star": true, "scene": "独占企業が価格を MC からどれだけ上に乗せる(**markup**)かは需要の弾力性しだい、という場面。需要が非弾力的なほど大きく上乗せできる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The more inelastic the demand, the larger the markup of price over marginal cost.", "defEN": "The size of a monopolist's **markup** of price over marginal cost depends on the **elasticity of demand**. The more **inelastic** the demand curve, the more a monopolist will raise price above MC. When demand is more elastic, the monopolist can mark up price less.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、需要が **inelastic**(非弾力的)なほど独占企業は価格を MC より大きく上乗せ(**markup**)できます。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• inelastic 需要 → 大きな markup\n• elastic 需要 → 小さな markup\n• 2市場で値付けする問題では弾力性の高い市場で値下げ・低い市場で値上げが収入を変える", "example": "A monopolist selling in two markets lowers price by $1 in the more elastic market and raises price by $1 in the more inelastic market; total revenue changes by +$27 (exercise Ch13 Q8).", "whyNeeded": "価格差別や価格設定の直感に直結。『非弾力的=大きな markup』は記述・選択問題で頻出。", "mistakes": ["**elastic** と **inelastic** を逆にして markup を語る誤り。inelastic ほど markup 大。", "markup を利潤と同一視する誤り。markup は P − MC の幅。"], "memorize": "Inelastic demand → bigger markup over MC"}, {"id": "c13_deadweight_loss_monopoly", "ch": 13, "week": 2, "name": "Deadweight Loss of Monopoly", "star": true, "scene": "独占は競争より高い価格・少ない数量を選ぶため、本来起きるはずの取引が消える。その失われた総余剰が **deadweight loss (DWL)**。", "compare": {"a": "Monopoly", "b": "Perfect Competition", "table": [{"dim": "Price", "a": "Higher (P > MC)", "b": "Lower (P = MC)"}, {"dim": "Quantity", "a": "Less", "b": "More (efficient)"}, {"dim": "Total surplus", "a": "Reduced", "b": "Maximized"}, {"dim": "Deadweight loss", "a": "Yes (DWL triangle)", "b": "None"}]}, "punchline": "Monopoly creates a deadweight loss because it prices above MC and produces too little.", "defEN": "Monopolies charge a **higher price** and produce **less** than competitive firms. This reduces **total surplus** (consumer surplus + producer surplus) and creates a **deadweight loss (DWL)**: sales that do not occur because the monopoly price is above the competitive price. DWL is the triangle between the monopoly and competitive quantities.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、独占は『高い価格・少ない量』なので、本来成立したはずの取引が消え、その分の総余剰が失われます。これが **deadweight loss (DWL)**。\n\n--- 計算 ---\n競争の最適点(**P = MC**)と比べる。DWL = (P_mono − MC) × (Q_comp − Q_mono) / 2(三角形の面積)\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 独占 → 価格高・量少 → 総余剰減 → DWL 発生", "example": "Case A: monopoly P = 30, Q = 20; competitive P = MC = 10, Q = 40. DWL = (30 − 10) × (40 − 20) / 2 = 200.", "whyNeeded": "独占の社会的コストを示す中核。図で DWL の三角形を選ぶ問題や面積計算が演習で頻出。", "mistakes": ["DWL を独占利潤と混同する誤り。DWL は失われた取引の余剰。", "比較対象を P=MC(競争)でなく P=AC にして計算する誤り。"], "memorize": "DWL = ½ × (P_mono − MC) × (Q_comp − Q_mono)"}, {"id": "c13_sources_market_power", "ch": 13, "week": 2, "name": "Sources of Monopoly Power", "star": false, "scene": "なぜある企業が独占になれるのか。**economies of scale**, 重要投入の支配, **patents**, 政府ライセンス, **network effects** の5つが源泉。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Monopoly power comes from economies of scale, input control, patents, government licenses, and network effects.", "defEN": "The five **sources of monopoly power** are: (1) **Economies of scale**, (2) **Control over an important input** (raw material), (3) **Patents**, (4) **Government license**, and (5) **Network effects**. Each lets a firm raise price above MC without attracting entry.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、独占が生まれる5つの源泉です。\n\n--- 5つの sources ---\n1. **Economies of scale**(規模の経済)\n2. **Control over important input**(重要投入の支配)\n3. **Patents**(特許)\n4. **Government license**(政府ライセンス)\n5. **Network effects**(ネットワーク効果)", "example": "Utilities such as water, natural gas, railroad, and cable television are often natural monopolies due to economies of scale.", "whyNeeded": "独占の成立要因を問う選択問題で直接出る。寡占の参入障壁(barriers to entry)とも重なる論点。", "mistakes": ["sources of power と regulation tools(価格規制等)を混同する誤り。", "network effects を Ch16 だけの話と思う誤り。独占の源泉でもある。"], "memorize": "SCALE-INPUT-PATENT-LICENSE-NETWORK (5 sources)"}, {"id": "c13_natural_monopoly", "ch": 13, "week": 2, "name": "Natural Monopoly", "star": false, "scene": "規模の経済が強く、1社で市場全体を供給したほうが2社以上より安く済む産業。水道・ガス・鉄道・ケーブルTVなど。これが **natural monopoly**。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A natural monopoly exists when one firm can supply the whole market at lower cost than two or more firms.", "defEN": "**Economies of scale** are the advantages of large-scale production that reduce average cost as quantity increases. A **natural monopoly** arises when a single firm can supply the entire market at a lower cost than two or more firms can. Utilities such as water, natural gas, railroad, and cable television are often natural monopolies.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**natural monopoly** は『規模の経済が強すぎて、1社が市場全体を供給するほうが複数社より安い』状態です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• **economies of scale**(規模の経済)= 量が増えるほど AC が下がる\n• 1社供給のほうが低コスト → 自然独占\n• 例: 水道・ガス・鉄道・ケーブルTV", "example": "Water, natural gas, railroad, and cable television are often natural monopolies because average cost keeps falling as one firm serves more customers.", "whyNeeded": "規制(price control)の対象になる典型例。なぜ政府が介入するかを理解する前提。", "mistakes": ["natural monopoly を『天然資源の独占』と誤読する誤り。本質は economies of scale。", "regulation で Pmax=MC にすると企業が赤字(P<AC)になる点を忘れる誤り。"], "memorize": "Natural monopoly = one firm cheaper than many (strong economies of scale)"}, {"id": "c13_regulating_monopoly", "ch": 13, "week": 2, "name": "Regulating Monopoly", "star": false, "scene": "政府が独占を規制する場面。価格上限を MC に設定すると最適量だが企業は赤字(P<AC)、AC に設定すると正常利潤は確保できるが多少の DWL が残る。", "compare": {"a": "Pmax = MC", "b": "Pmax = AC", "table": [{"dim": "Quantity", "a": "Optimal quantity", "b": "Below optimal (some DWL)"}, {"dim": "Firm's profit", "a": "Loss (P < AC)", "b": "Normal profit guaranteed"}, {"dim": "Deadweight loss", "a": "Eliminated", "b": "Some DWL remains"}, {"dim": "Label", "a": "First best", "b": "Second best"}]}, "punchline": "Setting Pmax = MC gives the optimal quantity but a loss; Pmax = AC gives normal profit but some DWL.", "defEN": "Governments regulate monopolies with **price controls**, **government ownership**, and **antitrust law**. Setting a maximum price **Pmax = MC** could achieve the **optimal quantity**, but this means a **loss for the firm (P < AC)**. Setting **Pmax = AC** (the second best) guarantees **normal profit** for the firm, but leaves some **deadweight loss**. In practice, regulation is much more complicated than the theory.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、政府が独占を規制する方法と価格上限のトレードオフの話です。\n\n--- 規制ツール ---\n• **price controls**(価格規制)\n• **government ownership**(政府所有)\n• **antitrust law**(独占禁止法)\n\n--- 価格上限のトレードオフ ---\n• **Pmax = MC**: 最適量だが企業は赤字(P < AC)→ first best\n• **Pmax = AC**: 正常利潤は確保、でも DWL が残る → second best", "example": "If Pmax = MC, the regulated price falls below average cost (P < AC) and the firm makes a loss; if Pmax = AC, the firm earns normal profit but some deadweight loss remains.", "whyNeeded": "自然独占への政策対応を問う問題で出る。MC 規制と AC 規制の長所短所の対比が論点。", "mistakes": ["Pmax=MC でも企業が黒字と思う誤り。実際は P<AC で赤字。", "Pmax=AC で DWL がゼロになると思う誤り。多少残る(second best)。"], "memorize": "Pmax=MC: optimal Q but loss; Pmax=AC: normal profit but some DWL"}, {"id": "c15_oligopoly", "ch": 15, "week": 2, "name": "Oligopoly", "star": true, "scene": "少数の企業に支配された産業。各社の意思決定が互いに影響し合うため **game theory**(ゲーム理論)で分析する。価格は独占より低く競争より高くなりがち。", "compare": null, "punchline": "An oligopoly is an industry dominated by a small number of firms whose decisions are strategically interdependent.", "defEN": "An **oligopoly** is an industry that is dominated by a small number of firms. Even when an oligopoly is not able to collude, prices are likely to be higher than in a competitive market. The price in an oligopoly is likely to be **below monopoly levels but above competitive levels**. The more firms in an industry, the closer price will be to competitive levels. **Game theory** is used to model decisions where players interact strategically.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**oligopoly**(寡占)は『少数の企業が支配する市場』です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 価格は **monopoly < oligopoly... 正しくは: competitive < oligopoly < monopoly**\n• 企業数が多いほど競争価格に近づく\n• **tacit collusion**(暗黙の共謀): 明示的合意なしに競争を制限\n• 分析には **game theory** を使う", "example": "If oil is produced by 10 countries each producing 10 MBD (100 MBD total), they may form a cartel; oligopoly prices sit below monopoly but above competitive levels.", "whyNeeded": "寡占・カルテル・ゲーム理論の全体枠組み。価格水準の順序(競争<寡占<独占)が選択問題で問われる。", "mistakes": ["価格順序を逆にする誤り。competitive < oligopoly < monopoly。", "**tacit collusion** を違法な明示的カルテルと混同する誤り。暗黙=合意なし。"], "memorize": "Oligopoly price: above competitive, below monopoly"}, {"id": "c15_cartel", "ch": 15, "week": 2, "name": "Cartel", "star": true, "scene": "寡占企業が結託し、供給を絞り価格と利潤を上げて独占のように振る舞おうとする集団が **cartel**。しかし崩壊しやすい。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A cartel is an oligopoly that acts together to reduce supply, raise prices, and increase profits — mimicking a monopoly.", "defEN": "A **cartel** is an oligopoly that tries to act together to **reduce supply, raise prices, and increase profits** — attempting to mimic a **monopoly**. Cartels tend to collapse for three reasons: (1) **cheating** by cartel members, (2) **new entrants and demand response**, and (3) **government prosecution and regulation**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**cartel**(カルテル)は『寡占企業が手を組んで独占のように振る舞う』集団です。\n\n--- 目的 ---\n供給を絞る → 価格を上げる → 利潤を増やす(= monopoly を真似る)\n\n--- 崩壊する3つの理由 ---\n1. メンバーの **cheating**(裏切り・増産)\n2. **new entrants** & 需要の反応\n3. **government prosecution**(政府の摘発・規制)", "example": "When producers engage in cartel-like behavior, they attempt to mimic the behavior of a monopoly (exercise Ch15 Q2 answer: c).", "whyNeeded": "カルテルがなぜ独占を狙い、なぜ崩れるかは記述・選択で頻出。prisoner's dilemma の現実版でもある。", "mistakes": ["cartel が安定だと思う誤り。cheat か new entry でたいてい崩壊する。", "cartel が真似るのは競争でなく **monopoly**。"], "memorize": "Cartel = oligopoly mimicking monopoly; collapses via cheat/entry/government"}, {"id": "c15_incentive_to_cheat", "ch": 15, "week": 2, "name": "Incentive to Cheat", "star": true, "scene": "カルテルのメンバーが約束を破って増産したくなる理由。独占者が増産すれば値下げ損を全部かぶるが、カルテルメンバーは損を仲間と分け合うので、裏切りの誘因が大きい。", "compare": {"a": "Monopoly raises quantity", "b": "Cartel member raises quantity", "table": [{"dim": "Who bears price loss", "a": "Bears all the loss", "b": "Loss shared with other members"}, {"dim": "Incentive to expand", "a": "Smaller", "b": "Greater (incentive to cheat)"}, {"dim": "Outcome", "a": "Restricts output", "b": "Tempted to overproduce"}]}, "punchline": "A cartel member has a greater incentive to cheat than a monopolist has to expand, because the price loss is shared.", "defEN": "When a **monopoly increases quantity**, it bears all of the loss due to the lower price. When a **cartel member increases quantity**, the losses are shared with the other members. Conclusion: a **cartel member has a greater incentive to cheat** (overproduce) than a single monopolist does.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、カルテルメンバーは増産しても値下げの損を仲間と分け合えるので、裏切って増産する誘因が大きいのです。\n\n--- 比較 ---\n• **Monopoly ↑ quantity**: 値下げ損を全部自分でかぶる\n• **Cartel member ↑ quantity**: 損を仲間と分担\n→ 結論: カルテルメンバーは **cheat** の誘因が大きい", "example": "If a cartel sets each country at 8 MBD but nine cheat to 10 MBD while one keeps 8 MBD, each cheater earns $375M/day while the loyal country earns $300M/day (exercise Ch15 Q6: a).", "whyNeeded": "カルテルが崩れる根本理由。週テストでも『各社が増産する誘因を持つから維持が難しい』が正解になる(WT2 Q2: b)。", "mistakes": ["カルテルが価格を上げる誘因で崩れると誤る。崩れる誘因は『増産(production を増やす)』(WT2 Q2: b)。", "monopoly と cartel member で損の負担が同じと思う誤り。"], "memorize": "Cartel member shares the loss → stronger incentive to cheat"}, {"id": "c15_prisoners_dilemma", "ch": 15, "week": 2, "name": "Prisoner's Dilemma", "star": true, "scene": "各自が自分の利益を追うと、誰も望まない悪い結果に全員が陥るゲーム。容疑者がともに黙秘すれば軽い刑だが、それぞれ自白(Talk)が得なので両者自白に。協調の維持が難しいことを示す。", "compare": null, "punchline": "In a prisoner's dilemma, pursuing individual self-interest leads to a group outcome in no one's interest.", "defEN": "A **prisoner's dilemma** is a situation in which the pursuit of individual interest leads to a group outcome that is in the interest of no one. It suggests that **cooperation is difficult to maintain**. In the payoff table, **Talk has a higher payoff than Silent regardless of the other's choice**, so Talk is the **dominant strategy** of each suspect, and the **Nash equilibrium is (Talk, Talk)**. Cartel members cheating is one version of this game.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**prisoner's dilemma**(囚人のジレンマ)は『各自が自己利益を追うと、全員にとって望ましくない結果になる』ゲームです。\n\n--- 容疑者の利得表 ---\n• 相手が何を選んでも **Talk**(自白)の利得が **Silent**(黙秘)より高い\n• よって Talk が各自の **dominant strategy**\n• **Nash equilibrium = (Talk, Talk)**\n→ **cooperation**(協調)の維持は難しい。カルテルの cheat はこの一種。", "example": "Suspect payoffs: (Silent,Silent) = (−1,−1); (Talk,Silent) = (0,−5); both end at the Nash equilibrium (Talk, Talk) = (−2,−2), worse than mutual silence.", "whyNeeded": "カルテル崩壊・寡占行動の理論的核。dominant strategy と Nash equilibrium の判定が試験頻出。", "mistakes": ["協調 (Silent, Silent) が均衡だと思う誤り。Nash 均衡は (Talk, Talk)。", "prisoner's dilemma を coordination game(Ch16)と混同する誤り。前者は dominant strategy あり。"], "memorize": "Self-interest → (Talk,Talk): individually rational, collectively bad"}, {"id": "c15_dominant_strategy_nash", "ch": 15, "week": 2, "name": "Dominant Strategy vs Nash Equilibrium", "star": true, "scene": "ゲーム理論の2つの基礎概念。相手が何を選んでも最善なら **dominant strategy**。誰も単独で戦略を変える誘因がない組合せが **Nash equilibrium**。", "compare": {"a": "Dominant Strategy", "b": "Nash Equilibrium", "table": [{"dim": "Definition", "a": "Best choice no matter what the opponent does", "b": "No player wants to change strategy unilaterally"}, {"dim": "Depends on opponent?", "a": "No — best regardless", "b": "Yes — given others' choices"}, {"dim": "How many?", "a": "At most one per player", "b": "Can be more than one (multiple equilibria)"}, {"dim": "Example", "a": "Cheat / Talk", "b": "(Talk, Talk); coordination games have two"}]}, "punchline": "A dominant strategy is best regardless of the opponent; a Nash equilibrium is where no one wants to deviate unilaterally.", "defEN": "A **dominant strategy** is the best choice no matter the strategy chosen by the opponent (e.g., Cheat is dominant when it is best whatever the rival does). A **Nash equilibrium** is a situation in which **no player has an incentive to change his or her strategy unilaterally**. A game can have **more than one Nash equilibrium** (e.g., coordination games), while a dominant strategy, if it exists, is best regardless of others.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、2つの基礎概念の違いです。\n\n--- **dominant strategy** ---\n相手が何を選ぼうと最善の戦略(例: **Cheat** が常に best)\n\n--- **Nash equilibrium** ---\n誰も単独では戦略を変えたくない組合せ。**unilaterally**(単独で)がキーワード。\n\n--- 注意 ---\n• dominant strategy があれば必ず Nash 均衡\n• Nash 均衡は複数あり得る(coordination game では2つ)", "example": "In the firm game, payoffs (Cooperate,Cooperate)=(400,400), (Cheat,Cheat)=(300,300): Cheat is a dominant strategy for each because it is best no matter the opponent's choice; the Nash equilibrium is (Cheat, Cheat).", "whyNeeded": "ゲーム理論問題の中核。Nash の定義(『unilaterally 変える誘因なし』)が選択肢で頻出(exercise Ch16 Q4: b)。", "mistakes": ["Nash を『相手が変えても変える誘因なし』と誤る。正しくは **unilaterally**(自分だけ)変える誘因なし(Ch16 Q4: b)。", "dominant strategy が常に1つの均衡を生むと思う誤り。coordination game では均衡が2つで dominant strategy なし。"], "memorize": "Dominant = best regardless; Nash = no unilateral deviation"}, {"id": "c15_government_policy_antitrust", "ch": 15, "week": 2, "name": "Antitrust Policy Toward Cartels", "star": false, "scene": "先進国では多くのカルテルが **antitrust law**(独占禁止法)で違法。政府はカルテルを摘発し、合併を阻止し、巨大企業を分割する。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Antitrust laws prosecute cartels, block mergers, and break up very large firms.", "defEN": "In developed countries most cartels are nowadays **illegal** due to **antitrust laws**. Antitrust laws are used to **prosecute cartels, block mergers, and break up very large firms**. However, people spend energy and money trying to get monopoly or cartel privileges from governments, which can lead to **more corrupt government**. Governments break up some cartels but enforce others.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、政府は **antitrust laws**(独占禁止法)でカルテルを取り締まります。\n\n--- 政府の手段 ---\n• カルテルを **prosecute**(摘発)\n• 合併を **block**(阻止)\n• 巨大企業を **break up**(分割)\n\n--- 注意 ---\n• 企業はカルテル特権を政府から得ようとする → 腐敗の温床\n• 政府はカルテルを潰すこともあれば、逆に守ることもある", "example": "Antitrust laws are used to prosecute cartels, block mergers, and break up very large firms; in developed countries most cartels are now illegal.", "whyNeeded": "カルテル崩壊の第3の理由(government prosecution)に対応する政策。ゲーム理論の現実的帰結を理解する。", "mistakes": ["政府が常にカルテルを潰すと思う誤り。enforce(守る)場合もある。", "antitrust を独占そのものの禁止と狭く捉える誤り。合併阻止や分割も含む。"], "memorize": "Antitrust = prosecute cartels, block mergers, break up giants"}, {"id": "c16_network_good", "ch": 16, "week": 2, "name": "Network Good", "star": true, "scene": "使う人が増えるほど一人ひとりにとって価値が上がる財。Facebook や TikTok が典型。みんなが互換性のある製品を使いたがるため、調整圧力が near-monopoly を生む。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A network good increases in value to a person the more other people use it.", "defEN": "A **network good** is a good that increases in value to a given person the more other people use the good (e.g., Facebook, TikTok). Features of network-good markets: (1) they are usually sold by **monopolies or oligopolies**, (2) the **“best” product may not always win**, and (3) competition is **“for the market” instead of “in the market.”** Because most people want software compatible with others, the pressure for coordination creates a **near-monopoly** (e.g., Microsoft).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**network good** は『使う人が増えるほど価値が上がる財』です。\n\n--- 例 ---\nFacebook, TikTok, Microsoft\n\n--- 3つの特徴 ---\n1. 通常 **monopolies/oligopolies** が売る\n2. 『最良』の製品が必ず勝つとは限らない\n3. 競争は **“for the market”**(市場を取る競争)であって **“in the market”** ではない\n\n互換性を求める圧力(coordination)が near-monopoly を生む。", "example": "Facebook and TikTok are network goods: each becomes more valuable as more people use it, pushing the market toward a near-monopoly like Microsoft.", "whyNeeded": "Ch16 全体の出発点。なぜネットワーク財が独占・寡占で売られるか(消費者が同じ標準に coordinate したいから)が頻出(exercise Ch16 Q3: d)。", "mistakes": ["ネットワーク財では『最良の製品が必ず勝つ』と思う誤り。これは FALSE(exercise Ch16 Q2: b)。", "network good を network effects(独占の源泉)と完全同義に扱わない。財そのものの性質を指す。"], "memorize": "Network good = more users → more value (Facebook, TikTok)"}, {"id": "c16_coordination_game_lockin", "ch": 16, "week": 2, "name": "Coordination Game and Lock-in", "star": true, "scene": "プレイヤーが同じ戦略を選ぶほうが得だが、合わせる先(標準)が複数あるゲーム。市場が劣った製品にロックインすることがあり、QWERTY キーボードがその例。", "compare": {"a": "Coordination Game", "b": "Prisoner's Dilemma", "table": [{"dim": "Players better off if", "a": "They choose the same strategy", "b": "Both cooperate (but won't)"}, {"dim": "Dominant strategy?", "a": "No — multiple equilibria", "b": "Yes — Cheat/Talk dominant"}, {"dim": "Number of Nash equilibria", "a": "More than one", "b": "One (mutual defection)"}, {"dim": "Outcome", "a": "May lock in on inferior standard", "b": "Bad outcome for all"}]}, "punchline": "In a coordination game players want the same strategy, so a market can lock in on an inferior network by accidents of history.", "defEN": "A **coordination game** is a game in which the players are better off if they choose the **same strategies**, but in which there is **more than one strategy** on which to coordinate. A market may **lock in on an inferior product or network**. If both choose the same software, neither has an incentive to change. With **two equilibria**, the choice is often determined by **“accidents of history.”** Example: the **QWERTY** keyboard may not be the best design, but it came first and got locked in (versus the Dvorak keyboard).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**coordination game** は『同じ戦略を選ぶほうが互いに得だが、合わせる先が複数ある』ゲームです。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 市場が劣った製品に **lock-in**(固定)し得る\n• 均衡が2つ → どちらになるかは **“accidents of history”**(歴史の偶然)\n• 例: **QWERTY** キーボード(先に来て固定。Dvorak のほうが良いかも)\n\n**Nash equilibrium**: 誰も単独で戦略を変える誘因がない状態。", "example": "The QWERTY keyboard came first and got locked in, even though the Dvorak keyboard (1930s) may be a better design — an accident of history with two equilibria.", "whyNeeded": "『最良の製品が必ず勝つわけではない』(standard wars / lock-in)の仕組み。coordination game と prisoner's dilemma の違いが頻出。", "mistakes": ["coordination game に dominant strategy があると思う誤り。均衡が複数で dominant strategy はない。", "QWERTY が最良だから残ったと思う誤り。lock-in(歴史の偶然)で残った。"], "memorize": "Coordination game = same strategy wins; lock-in by accidents of history (QWERTY)"}, {"id": "c16_competition_for_the_market", "ch": 16, "week": 2, "name": "Competition For the Market", "star": true, "scene": "ネットワーク財では各社が『市場の中で(in the market)』競うのではなく『市場そのものを取るために(for the market)』競う。独占の座は意外と簡単に入れ替わる。", "compare": {"a": "Competition “for the market”", "b": "Competition “in the market”", "table": [{"dim": "What firms compete for", "a": "To become THE dominant standard", "b": "Market share within a shared market"}, {"dim": "Typical of", "a": "Network goods", "b": "Ordinary competitive markets"}, {"dim": "Outcome", "a": "Winner-take-most; monopoly can change hands", "b": "Many firms coexist"}]}, "punchline": "For network goods, competition is “for the market” — firms fight to become the single dominant standard, and the monopoly can change hands quickly.", "defEN": "For network goods, **competition is “for the market” instead of “in the market.”** Consumer loyalties can switch quickly, so a **monopoly can easily change hands**. In 1988 Lotus 1-2-3 had 70% of the spreadsheet market; by 1998 Excel had 70%. Before Facebook became dominant, MySpace, Friendster, and Facebook all competed to be number one. **Standard wars** are common in establishing network goods.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、ネットワーク財では『市場の中での競争(in the market)』ではなく『市場そのものを取る競争(**for the market**)』になります。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 消費者の忠誠は急に移る → 独占の座が入れ替わる\n• **standard wars**(標準争い)が普通\n• 例: Lotus 1-2-3(1988年70%) → Excel(1998年70%); MySpace/Friendster/Facebook の覇権争い", "example": "In 1988 Lotus 1-2-3 held 70% of the spreadsheet market; by 1998 Excel held 70% — the monopoly changed hands, illustrating competition “for the market.”", "whyNeeded": "ネットワーク財の動学を表す中核概念。『network goods might lose their dominance over time』が TRUE になる(exercise Ch16 Q6: c)。", "mistakes": ["ネットワーク財企業が『in the market』で競うと思う誤り。正しくは『for the market』(exercise Ch16 Q6: d は FALSE)。", "ネットワーク財の独占は永久だと思う誤り。覇権は入れ替わり得る。"], "memorize": "Network goods: compete FOR the market, not IN it (Lotus→Excel)"}, {"id": "c16_contestable_market", "ch": 16, "week": 2, "name": "Contestable Market", "star": false, "scene": "潜在的な競争の脅威だけで市場が競争的に振る舞う状態。新規参入の可能性があるため、既存企業は competitively に行動せざるを得ない。既存企業は switching cost を上げて contestability を下げようとする。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A contestable market behaves competitively because the mere threat of entry disciplines incumbents.", "defEN": "A **contestable market** is a market in which the **threat of potential competition** is enough to make the market behave competitively. A competitor could **credibly enter and take away business** from the incumbent. This threat forces firms to make choices in light of potential competition. **Incumbent firms** often try to limit contestability — one way is to **increase switching costs** (e.g., Apple makes it easy to download content to the iPhone but difficult to export it to other systems).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**contestable market** は『潜在的な参入の脅威だけで市場が競争的に動く』状態です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 新規参入が信頼できる脅威 → 既存企業(incumbent)も競争的に行動\n• 既存企業は **switching costs**(乗り換え費用)を上げて contestability を下げようとする\n• 例: Apple は iPhone への取り込みは簡単だが、外部への書き出しは難しくする", "example": "A market is contestable if a competitor could credibly enter and take away business from the incumbent (exercise Ch16 Q7: b). Apple raises switching costs to limit contestability.", "whyNeeded": "ネットワーク財独占でも競争圧力が働く理由。switching cost をどう見せるか(就職後は低く見せて賃上げを引き出す)も問われる(exercise Ch16 Q8: d)。", "mistakes": ["contestable market を『1社支配の市場』と誤る誤り。本質は参入の脅威(Ch16 Q7: b)。", "switching cost を高く見せれば賃金が上がると思う誤り。低く見せるほうが賃上げ圧力(Ch16 Q8: d)。"], "memorize": "Contestable = threat of entry disciplines incumbents"}, {"id": "c17_monopolistic_competition", "ch": 17, "week": 2, "name": "Monopolistic Competition", "star": true, "scene": "多数の売り手・自由参入退出・製品差別化を持つ市場。各社は差別化ゆえに右下がり需要曲線に直面する(=ちょっとした市場支配力)。競争と独占の中間。", "compare": {"a": "Monopolistic Competition", "b": "Monopoly", "table": [{"dim": "Number of sellers", "a": "Many sellers", "b": "One firm"}, {"dim": "Entry", "a": "Free entry and exit", "b": "Blocked (barriers)"}, {"dim": "Demand curve", "a": "Downward sloping, relatively flatter", "b": "Downward sloping, steeper"}, {"dim": "Long-run profit", "a": "Zero (P = AC)", "b": "Above-normal profit"}, {"dim": "Price vs MC", "a": "P > MC", "b": "P > MC"}]}, "punchline": "Monopolistic competition has many sellers, free entry, and differentiated products, giving each firm limited market power.", "defEN": "**Monopolistic competition** combines some features of competitive markets with some features of monopoly. It is a market with **many sellers**, **free entry and exit**, and **product differentiation** (products are similar but not identical). Monopolistic competitors face a **downward-sloping demand curve** because of product differentiation, but it is **relatively flatter** than that of a pure monopoly — so they have **market power limited by competition**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**monopolistic competition**(独占的競争)は『競争と独占の中間』の市場です。\n\n--- 3つの条件 ---\n1. **Many sellers**(多数の売り手)\n2. **Free entry and exit**(自由な参入退出)\n3. **Product differentiation**(製品差別化。似ているが同一でない)\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 差別化ゆえに需要曲線は **downward-sloping**(右下がり)\n• ただし純粋独占より flatter(平ら)→ 市場支配力はあるが競争に制限される", "example": "Many firms selling similar but not identical products with free entry is monopolistic competition (exercise Ch17 Q2: c); the three defining features are free entry and product differentiation (Q3: c = II and III).", "whyNeeded": "Ch17 全体の定義。『few sellers』は誤りで『many sellers』が正しい点が頻出(Q3 で I は除外)。", "mistakes": ["『few sellers』を条件に含める誤り。正しくは **many sellers**(Ch17 Q3: I は除外, 答え c)。", "monopolistic competition を oligopoly と混同する誤り。寡占は少数、独占的競争は多数。"], "memorize": "Monopolistic competition = MANY sellers + free entry + differentiation"}, {"id": "c17_product_differentiation", "ch": 17, "week": 2, "name": "Product Differentiation", "star": false, "scene": "味・スタイル・機能・立地など消費者が気にする任意の次元で製品を差別化すること。同じ水でも Albert Heijn と Albert Heijn to Go で値段が違う。差別化は市場支配力を生む。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Product differentiation makes products similar but not identical, giving firms a downward-sloping demand and market power.", "defEN": "**Product differentiation** means products are similar but not identical. Products can be differentiated along any dimension people care about — **taste, style, features, or location** — and also by **ease of purchase**. Firms want consumers to perceive their products as different and better because that **increases the firms' market power** and gives them a downward-sloping demand curve. Differentiated products are often **highly advertised**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**product differentiation**(製品差別化)は『似ているが同一でない』製品を作ることです。\n\n--- 差別化の次元 ---\n• **taste**(味), **style**(スタイル), **features**(機能), **location**(立地)\n• ease of purchase(買いやすさ)\n\n--- なぜ重要 ---\n差別化 → 消費者が『違う・良い』と認識 → **market power** 増 → 右下がり需要。差別化製品は **highly advertised**(よく広告される)。", "example": "The same bottle of water is sold for different prices at Albert Heijn and Albert Heijn to Go — differentiation by location and ease of purchase.", "whyNeeded": "独占的競争の心臓部。なぜ需要が右下がりになるか、なぜ広告が多いかの根拠。差別化製品は highly advertised(Ch17 Q4: d)。", "mistakes": ["差別化を『物理的に違う製品』だけと狭く捉える誤り。立地や買いやすさも含む。", "差別化財は『rarely advertised』と思う誤り。正しくは **highly** advertised(Ch17 Q4: d)。"], "memorize": "Differentiation (taste/style/features/location) → market power + downward demand"}, {"id": "c17_longrun_zero_profit", "ch": 17, "week": 2, "name": "Long-Run Zero Profit (P = AC)", "star": true, "scene": "独占的競争の長期。自由参入で利潤がゼロになるまで企業が入り、価格が AC まで下がる。ただし P > MC のまま、AC の最小点では生産しない(超過設備)。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Free entry drives price down to P = AC in the long run, so economic profits are zero — but P stays above MC.", "defEN": "In monopolistic competition, **product differentiation means P > MC** and a firm does **not** produce at the **minimum of its AC curve**. **Free entry drives price down to P = AC**, where **economic profits = 0** in the long run. In the long run you would expect **more firms to enter** when profits are positive. The resulting inefficiency could be (more than) offset by the **availability of new product variety and new features**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、独占的競争の長期では自由参入で利潤がゼロ(**P = AC**)になります。\n\n--- 長期の特徴 ---\n• 利潤が出る → **more firms enter**(新規参入)→ 価格が下がる\n• 最終的に **P = AC**, economic profit = 0\n• ただし **P > MC** のまま\n• **AC の最小点では生産しない**(超過設備=非効率)\n\n--- 救い ---\nその非効率は **new product variety**(製品多様性)で相殺され得る。", "example": "If a monopolistically competitive firm earns positive profit in the short run, in the long run you would expect more firms to enter the market (exercise Ch17 Q5: d), driving price to P = AC.", "whyNeeded": "独占的競争の長期均衡。利潤ゼロ・P=AC だが P>MC で最小 AC でない、という三点が記述で問われる。企業は MR=MC で操業(Ch17 Q6: b)。", "mistakes": ["長期でも超過利潤が残ると思う誤り。free entry で economic profit = 0。", "P = AC = 最小 AC と思う誤り。最小 AC では生産しない(P>MC のため)。"], "memorize": "Long run: P = AC (zero profit) but P > MC, not at min AC"}, {"id": "c17_advertising", "ch": 17, "week": 2, "name": "Economics of Advertising", "star": false, "scene": "差別化製品を持つ企業が最も広告する。無差別財の企業は広告の利益が業界全体に流れるのでほぼ広告せず、独占は競争相手がいないので広告しない。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Firms with differentiated products advertise the most; undifferentiated sellers and pure monopolies advertise little.", "defEN": "Firms that sell **undifferentiated goods don't advertise much**, because the benefits would flow mostly to other firms in the same industry. **Monopolies are also unlikely to advertise** because they have no competitors. Firms with **differentiated products are the most likely to advertise**: they want more customers and can advertise their specific product rather than the industry category. **Persuasive advertising can create market power by brand differentiation**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、誰が一番広告するかの話です。\n\n--- 広告しない企業 ---\n• 無差別財の企業: 広告の恩恵が同業他社に流れる\n• **monopoly**: 競争相手がいない\n\n--- 一番広告する企業 ---\n• **differentiated products** を持つ企業: 自社製品を宣伝でき、客を増やせる\n\n--- 効果 ---\n**persuasive advertising**(説得的広告)は **brand differentiation** で市場支配力を生む。", "example": "Firms with differentiated products are most likely to advertise; monopolistically competitive products are usually highly advertised (exercise Ch17 Q4: d).", "whyNeeded": "差別化と広告の結びつきを問う問題で出る。なぜ独占や無差別財企業は広告しないかの論理が重要。", "mistakes": ["独占が最も広告すると思う誤り。競争相手がいないのでむしろ広告しない。", "無差別財企業が広告すると思う誤り。恩恵が業界全体に漏れるためあまりしない。"], "memorize": "Differentiated firms advertise most; monopolies & commodity sellers don't"}, {"id": "c18_labor_demand_mpl", "ch": 18, "week": 2, "name": "Demand for Labor (MPL)", "star": true, "scene": "企業が労働者を1人雇うかどうかの判断。追加労働者が生む収入(MRPL = 金銭表示の MPL)が賃金を上回るなら雇う。市場の労働需要は MPL に基づく。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A firm hires a worker when the marginal product of labor is at least the wage: MPL ≥ w.", "defEN": "The **Marginal Revenue Product of labor (MRPL)** is the increase in a firm's revenues created by hiring an additional laborer. It is the same as the **marginal product of labor (MPL)** measured in monetary terms. A firm is willing to hire a worker when the marginal product of labor is greater than the wage (cost): **MPL ≥ w**. The **market demand curve for labor is based on the marginal product of labor**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、企業は『追加労働者が生む価値(**MPL**)が賃金(**w**)以上なら雇う』のです。\n\n--- キーワード ---\n• **MRPL**(労働の限界収入生産物)= 追加労働者が生む収入増\n• MRPL = 金銭表示の **MPL**(教科書は MPL を使う)\n\n--- 雇用条件 ---\n**MPL ≥ w**\n\n--- 市場 ---\n労働需要曲線は **marginal product of labor** に基づく。", "example": "Refer to Cleaners' Wages: at a wage of $29 the firm hires 2 workers (exercise Ch18 Q3: c) — it hires while MPL ≥ w.", "whyNeeded": "労働需要の基礎。『市場労働需要は MPL に基づく』が頻出(exercise Ch18 Q2: d)。雇用量決定の出発点。", "mistakes": ["労働需要を労働供給の弾力性に基づくと誤る。正しくは **MPL**(Ch18 Q2: d)。", "MPL < w でも雇うと思う誤り。雇用条件は MPL ≥ w。"], "memorize": "Hire while MPL ≥ w; labor demand based on MPL"}, {"id": "c18_labor_supply_wage", "ch": 18, "week": 2, "name": "Labor Supply and Wage (MPL = W)", "star": false, "scene": "個人の労働供給は賃金が高いとやがて余暇を取り後方屈折し得る。市場供給は賃金が上がると新たな労働者が入るため右上がり。均衡賃金は需要と供給の交点で MPL = W。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Market labor supply slopes upward; equilibrium wage is set where labor demand meets supply, with MPL = W.", "defEN": "An **individual's labor supply** can bend backward: Joe works more hours as the wage rises from $16 to $20 but **fewer hours when the wage rises above $20** (taking part of income as leisure). The **market supply of labor is upward sloping** because higher wages attract more workers into the industry. The market **wage is found at the intersection of demand and supply**, where **MPL = W**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、市場の労働供給は右上がりで、均衡賃金は需要と供給の交点(**MPL = W**)で決まります。\n\n--- 個人の供給 ---\n• 賃金が高くなりすぎると余暇を取り、労働時間を減らす(後方屈折)\n\n--- 市場の供給 ---\n• **upward sloping**(右上がり): 賃金上昇 → より多くの労働者が参入\n\n--- 均衡 ---\n需要と供給の交点で **MPL = W**", "example": "Joe works fewer hours when the wage rises above $20 (individual backward bend), but market supply slopes up because higher wages attract more workers (exercise Ch18 Q5: b).", "whyNeeded": "労働市場の均衡を理解する基礎。個人供給(後方屈折)と市場供給(右上がり)の区別が選択問題で問われる(Ch18 Q4: a, Q5: b)。", "mistakes": ["個人の供給と市場の供給を混同する誤り。市場は upward sloping(Ch18 Q5: b)、個人は後方屈折し得る。", "個人供給が下を向くのは余暇を取るから(Ch18 Q4: a)であって賃金が下がるからではない。"], "memorize": "Market supply upward (more wage → more workers); equilibrium MPL = W"}, {"id": "c18_minimum_wage_monopsony", "ch": 18, "week": 2, "name": "Minimum Wage and Unemployment", "star": false, "scene": "最低賃金が失業を生むかは雇用側の市場支配力しだい。競争的労働市場では失業を生み得るが、単一雇用主(monopsonist)の場合は結果が異なる。", "compare": {"a": "Competitive labor market", "b": "Single employer (monopsonist)", "table": [{"dim": "Employer market power", "a": "None (many employers)", "b": "High (one buyer of labor)"}, {"dim": "Effect of minimum wage", "a": "Can create unemployment", "b": "Unemployment effect differs"}, {"dim": "Key determinant", "a": "Employer's market power", "b": "Employer's market power"}]}, "punchline": "A minimum wage may create unemployment, but the extent depends on the employer's market power.", "defEN": "A **minimum wage** may create **unemployment**, the extent of which **depends on the employer's market power**. In a **competitive labor market** a binding minimum wage can create unemployment. With a **single employer (monopsonist)** — the only buyer of labor — the employment effect of a minimum wage differs from the competitive case.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、最低賃金が失業を生むかは『雇用主の市場支配力』しだいです。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 競争的労働市場: 拘束的な最低賃金は失業を生み得る\n• **monopsonist**(単一雇用主=労働の唯一の買い手): 失業への影響は競争市場と異なる\n• 失業の程度は **employer's market power** に依存", "example": "A minimum wage may create unemployment, the extent of which depends on the employer's market power — a monopsonist (single employer) sets wage wm and employment Lm differently from a competitive market.", "whyNeeded": "最低賃金の効果が一律でない理由を理解する。monopsony という雇用側の市場支配力概念が論点。", "mistakes": ["最低賃金が常に失業を生むと思う誤り。雇用主の市場支配力に依存する。", "monopoly(売り手1社)と monopsony(買い手1社)を混同する誤り。労働市場は monopsony。"], "memorize": "Min wage → unemployment depends on employer's market power (monopsony)"}, {"id": "c18_human_capital_signaling", "ch": 18, "week": 2, "name": "Human Capital vs Signaling", "star": true, "scene": "なぜ大卒は高卒より賃金が高いのか。教育が生産性を高める(human capital theory)からか、学位が知性・誠実さを示す(signaling theory)からか。2つの説は排他的でない。", "compare": {"a": "Human Capital Theory", "b": "Signaling Theory", "table": [{"dim": "Why education raises wages", "a": "Education increases productivity", "b": "Degree signals intelligence & conscientiousness"}, {"dim": "Does college make you more productive?", "a": "Yes", "b": "Not necessarily"}, {"dim": "If everyone gets a degree", "a": "Wages reflect higher productivity", "b": "Wage falls — harder to differentiate workers"}]}, "punchline": "College grads earn more either because education raises productivity (human capital) or because a degree signals ability (signaling).", "defEN": "**Human capital** is “tools of the mind” — the stuff in people's heads that makes them productive — built by investment in **education, training, and experience** (costly: tuition + opportunity costs; returns come in the future). On average, more education brings a higher wage. The wage gap could be because (1) **education increases productivity (human capital theory)**, or (2) **a degree signals intelligence, competence, and conscientiousness (signaling theory)**. The two theories are **not mutually exclusive**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、大卒が高賃金な理由には2説あります。\n\n--- **human capital**(人的資本) ---\n『頭の中の生産性を高める道具』。education/training/experience への投資。費用は授業料+機会費用、見返りは将来。\n\n--- 2つの説(排他的でない) ---\n1. **Human capital theory**: 教育が生産性を高める\n2. **Signaling theory**: 学位が知性・誠実さを示すだけ\n\n--- カギ ---\n大卒と高卒の比較には『college に行かなかった場合の収入』を知る必要(twins / natural experiments で近似)。", "example": "If the signaling theory is dominant and everyone received a college degree, the average wage for college graduates would decrease because it would be harder to differentiate workers (exercise Ch18 Q8: c).", "whyNeeded": "賃金格差の二大理論。『大卒が高賃金=より生産的』(human capital, Ch18 Q6: d)と『学位は知性の証明』(signaling, Q7: b)の区別が頻出。", "mistakes": ["signaling theory を『教育がスキルを高めるから高賃金』と誤る。signaling は『スキルでなく知性・誠実さの証明』(Ch18 Q7: b)。", "全員が学位を取ると賃金が上がると思う誤り。signaling が支配的なら下がる(差別化困難, Q8: c)。"], "memorize": "Human capital = education raises productivity; Signaling = degree just signals ability"}, {"id": "c18_compensating_differentials", "ch": 18, "week": 2, "name": "Compensating Differentials", "star": true, "scene": "労働条件の差を埋め合わせる賃金の差。危険な仕事ほど(他が同じなら)高く払われ、楽しい仕事は給料が少ない。消防士が受付係より高給なのは仕事が危険だから。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A compensating differential is a wage difference that offsets differences in working conditions — riskier jobs pay more.", "defEN": "A **compensating differential** is a difference in wages that **offsets differences in working conditions**. “More money, less fun” versus “more fun, less money.” **Riskier jobs pay more, all else being equal.** Compensating differentials explain why **fun jobs pay less and dangerous jobs pay more**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**compensating differential**(補償賃金差)は『労働条件の差を埋め合わせる賃金の差』です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 危険な仕事 → (他が同じなら)高給\n• 楽しい仕事 → 低給\n• “more money, less fun” vs “more fun, less money”\n\n--- 供給の動き ---\n仕事 B が寿命を縮めると分かれば、B の労働供給が減って B の賃金が上がり、A の供給が増えて A の賃金が下がる。", "example": "A firefighter is likely to earn more than a receptionist because the job is more dangerous (exercise Ch18 Q9: c) — a compensating differential.", "whyNeeded": "賃金格差の非差別的説明。危険・不快な条件への補償という論理が選択問題で頻出。週テストでも労働供給シフトで問われる(WT2 Q3: b)。", "mistakes": ["消防士の高給を『より楽しい/名誉』と誤る。正しくは『より危険』(Ch18 Q9: c)。", "危険判明で供給がどう動くか逆にする誤り。B の供給は減り賃金は上がる(WT2 Q3: b)。"], "memorize": "Compensating differential: risky/unpleasant jobs pay more"}, {"id": "c18_labor_discrimination", "ch": 18, "week": 2, "name": "Labor Market Discrimination", "star": true, "scene": "性別・人種で賃金が不平等な一部は差別による。集団平均で個人を判断する **statistical discrimination** と、特定集団への嫌悪に基づく **taste-based discrimination** の2種類。市場は時間とともに差別を弱める傾向。", "compare": {"a": "Statistical Discrimination", "b": "Taste-Based Discrimination", "table": [{"dim": "Basis", "a": "Group averages applied to individuals", "b": "Dislike (taste) for a group"}, {"dim": "Source", "a": "Imperfect information", "b": "Prejudice (employers, customers, employees)"}, {"dim": "Under perfect information", "a": "Would not exist", "b": "Could still exist"}, {"dim": "Effect on prejudiced employer", "a": "—", "b": "Faces higher costs; outcompeted over time"}]}, "punchline": "Two kinds of labor-market discrimination occur: statistical (group averages) and taste-based (prejudice) — markets tend to erode both over time.", "defEN": "At least two kinds of discrimination occur in labor markets. (1) **Statistical discrimination**: using information about **group averages** to make conclusions about individuals — it would **not exist in a world of perfect information**. (2) **Preference/taste-based discrimination**: a **dislike** for some group of people, which includes discrimination by **employers, customers, and/or employees**. When discrimination stems from employers' personal prejudices, those **employers face higher costs** and tend to be **outcompeted**, so **markets tend to break down discrimination over time**. A field experiment found “white”-sounding names got 9.7% callbacks versus 6.5% for “black”-sounding names.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、労働市場の差別には少なくとも2種類あります。\n\n--- 2種類 ---\n1. **Statistical discrimination**(統計的差別): 集団平均で個人を判断。完全情報下では消える。\n2. **Taste-based / preference discrimination**(嗜好に基づく差別): 特定集団への嫌悪。employers / customers / employees による。\n\n--- 市場の力 ---\n偏見を持つ雇用主は **higher costs** を負い、outcompete される → 市場は時間とともに差別を弱める。\n\n--- 実証 ---\nEmily/Greg(白人風)9.7% vs Lakisha/Jamal(黒人風)6.5% のコールバック率差。", "example": "Statistical discrimination is using information about group averages to make conclusions about individuals (exercise Ch18 Q11: a); in a world of perfect information it would not exist (Q12: a). A field experiment found résumés with names like Lakisha and Jamal got fewer interview requests (Q14: a).", "whyNeeded": "差別の2分類は試験頻出。完全情報下では統計的差別が消える(Q12: a)、偏見雇用主は高コストで不利(Q13: d)が論点。", "mistakes": ["statistical discrimination を『悪意ある違法行為』と誤る。実態は集団平均の利用(Ch18 Q11: a)。", "偏見雇用主が儲かると思う誤り。実際は higher costs で不利(Ch18 Q13: d)。"], "memorize": "Statistical = group averages (gone under perfect info); Taste-based = prejudice (costly, eroded by markets)"}, {"id": "c22_you_get_what_you_pay_for", "ch": 22, "week": 3, "name": "You Get What You Pay For (Incentive Alignment)", "star": true, "scene": "企業が**stock options**でCEOに報酬を与えたら、株価を上げるため懸命に働くCEOもいたが、決算を操作して**cheat**するCEOも出た。これは「**hoping for A while paying for B**」という、報酬設計が望む行動とズレる状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A successful organization aligns self-interest with the organization's interest, but getting incentives right is not always easy.", "defEN": "A good social system aligns **self-interest** with the **social interest**, and a successful organization aligns self-interest with the **organization's interest**. The folly of **hoping for A while paying for B** means a badly designed incentive scheme creates a gap between what you pay for and what you want. In the 1980s, CEOs given **stock options** (which pay off only if the stock rises above a certain price) were encouraged to work harder, but some were also encouraged to **cheat by manipulating earnings reports**. Paying teachers for student performance can mean better education but also **teaching to the test** and cheating.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、報酬制度は『払った対象の行動』を引き出すので、本当に欲しい成果(A)とは別物(B)に金を払うと失敗する、という話です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 良い社会システムは**self-interest**(自己利益)と**social interest**(社会的利益)を一致させる。\n• 良い組織は**self-interest**を**organization's interest**(組織の利益)と一致させる。\n• 1980年代CEOへの**stock options**は、株価を上げる努力を促す一方、**earnings reports**(決算報告)の操作という不正も誘発した。\n• 教師に生徒の成績で報酬を払うと、**teaching to the test**(テスト対策偏重)や不正が起きうる。\n• **Incentives matter**だが、正しく設計するのは簡単ではない。", "example": "In the 1980s, CEOs were given stock options that pay off only if the stock rises above a certain price: some worked harder and smarter (A), but some cheated by manipulating earnings reports (B).", "whyNeeded": "報酬設計の本質を理解する基礎。**stock options**が不正や**excessive risk-taking**を招き、2008年の**financial crisis**につながった例は試験で問われやすい。良い行動を引き出すには測定対象の選択が鍵。", "mistakes": ["**self-interest** と **social interest** の一致を『常に自動的に起こる』と誤解する。設計が必要。", "**incentives matter** を『お金さえ払えば望む成果が出る』と誤解する。払う対象がズレると逆効果。"], "memorize": "Pay for B, get B — not A. Align self-interest with the organization's interest."}, {"id": "c22_strong_vs_weak_incentives", "ch": 22, "week": 3, "name": "Strong vs Weak Incentive Schemes", "star": true, "scene": "報酬を成果に強く連動させる**strong incentive scheme**は、もし間違ったものを評価していると逆効果。『払うもの』と『欲しいもの』のギャップを埋められないなら、弱い制度の方がマシなこともある。", "compare": {"a": "Strong Incentive Scheme", "b": "Weak Incentive Scheme", "table": [{"dim": "Link between pay and measured performance", "a": "Strong / tight", "b": "Loose / weak"}, {"dim": "When 'what you pay for' is close to 'what you want'", "a": "Better — you can rely on it", "b": "Less effective"}, {"dim": "When it incentivizes the wrong thing", "a": "Can be worse than a weak one", "b": "Less harmful"}, {"dim": "When the gap cannot be bridged", "a": "Strong can still be better than weak (Statement II is false)", "b": "Can be better than a strong scheme that pays for the wrong thing"}]}, "punchline": "A strong incentive scheme that incentivizes the wrong thing can be worse than a weak one.", "defEN": "Careful design of an incentive scheme can narrow the gap between what you want and what you pay for. The closer **what you pay for** is to **what you want**, the more you can rely on **strong incentives**. However, a **strong incentive scheme** that incentivizes the wrong thing can be worse than a **weak** one. If you cannot bridge the gap between what you pay for and what you want, then a weak incentive scheme can be safer.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、『払う対象』と『欲しい成果』が近いほど**strong incentives**(強い誘因)に頼ってよい、という話です。\n\n--- 試験で問われるポイント ---\n• **what you pay for** が **what you want** に近い → **strong incentives** に頼れる(=Statement I は真)。\n• ギャップを埋められないとき → 強い制度が必ずしも良いとは限らない(週テストの設問: Statement II『埋められないなら strong が weak より良い』は偽)。\n• 間違ったものに強く報酬を払うと、**weak** な制度より悪化する。\n• 丁寧な設計でギャップを狭められる。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q3: Statement I ('the closer what you pay for is to what you want, the more you can rely on strong incentives') is TRUE; Statement II ('if you can't bridge the gap, then strong schemes can be better than weak schemes') is FALSE. Answer: I true, II false.", "whyNeeded": "演習Q3で直接問われた論点。強い誘因が常に良いという誤解を正す。測定の精度と報酬の強さの関係を理解する必要がある。", "mistakes": ["**strong incentives** が常に **weak incentives** より優れていると誤解する。間違った対象を測ると逆。", "Statement II を真と誤答する。ギャップを埋められないなら強い制度が良いとは限らない。"], "memorize": "Close gap → rely on strong; wrong target → strong is worse than weak."}, {"id": "c22_piece_rate", "ch": 22, "week": 3, "name": "Piece Rate", "star": true, "scene": "工場で作った製品の数だけ給料が増える**piece rate**(出来高払い)。たくさん作るほど稼げるので懸命に働くが、品質が大事で測りにくい仕事には向かない。", "compare": {"a": "Piece Rate", "b": "Hourly (Wage) Rate", "table": [{"dim": "Basis of pay", "a": "Directly for output", "b": "For time worked"}, {"dim": "Incentive to work hard", "a": "Increases it", "b": "Weaker"}, {"dim": "Best when", "a": "Output is easy to measure", "b": "Output is difficult to measure (quality important)"}, {"dim": "Weakness", "a": "Doesn't work well when quality is important and hard to measure", "b": "Less direct effort incentive"}]}, "punchline": "A piece rate is any payment system that pays workers directly for their output.", "defEN": "A **piece rate** is any payment system that pays workers directly for their **output**. It increases the incentive to work hard and works well when output is easy to measure. It does not work well when **quality is important and hard to measure**. **Hourly rates** are preferred to piece rates when it is difficult to measure output.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**piece rate**(出来高払い)は『作った量に直接お金を払う』方式です。\n\n--- 特徴 ---\n• **output**(産出量)に直接連動して支払う。\n• 一生懸命働く誘因を高める。\n• 産出量が測りやすいとき有効。\n• **quality**(品質)が重要で測りにくいときはうまく機能しない。\n\n--- 対比 ---\n• 産出量の測定が難しいときは **hourly rate**(時給)が好まれる(演習Q5の答え)。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q5: Hourly rates are preferred to piece rates 'when it is difficult to measure output.' Answer: a.", "whyNeeded": "演習Q5で出題。出来高払いと時給の使い分け(測定可能性と品質)を理解する必要がある。**incentive scheme**設計の代表例。", "mistakes": ["**piece rate** を品質重視の仕事に常に良いと誤解する。品質が測りにくいと逆効果。", "**piece rate** と **hourly rate** の使い分け条件(測定の難易)を逆にする。"], "memorize": "Piece rate = pay per output; use when output is easy to measure."}, {"id": "c22_tournament", "ch": 22, "week": 3, "name": "Tournament (Pay for Relative Performance)", "star": true, "scene": "セールスマン全員を比べて、一番売った人にボーナスを出す**tournament**(相対評価)。景気やガソリン価格など全員に共通の要因は無関係になり、本人の**effort**(努力)が効く。ただし社内の協力が減るリスクも。", "compare": {"a": "Tournament (Relative Performance)", "b": "Piece Rate (Absolute Output)", "table": [{"dim": "Pay based on", "a": "Relative performance vs others", "b": "Own absolute output"}, {"dim": "Environment risk (common outside factors)", "a": "Insulated / removed", "b": "Borne by the worker"}, {"dim": "Ability risk", "a": "Adds it (others' ability not under your control)", "b": "Less relevant"}, {"dim": "Side effect", "a": "Can discourage cooperation / lead to sabotage", "b": "Quality issues if hard to measure"}]}, "punchline": "A tournament is a compensation scheme in which payment is based on relative performance.", "defEN": "A **tournament** is a compensation scheme in which payment is based on **relative performance**. Since every worker faces the same conditions, factors a worker doesn't control no longer influence rewards, and factors a worker does control (like **effort**) become more important. Tournaments **insulate rewards from environment risk** due to outside factors common to all players, but **add ability risk** (someone else's ability is not under a player's control). They **work best when environment risk is more important than ability risk**, can **discourage cooperation (or lead to sabotage)**, and can be structured to reduce ability risk.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**tournament**(トーナメント/相対評価)は『他人と比べた相対成績』で報酬を決める方式です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• **relative performance**(相対的成績)に基づいて支払う。\n• 全員が同じ条件 → 本人が制御できない要因(景気等)は報酬に影響しない。\n• 本人が制御できる **effort**(努力)がより重要になる。\n• **environment risk**(共通の外部リスク)から報酬を隔離する。\n• ただし **ability risk**(他人の能力という制御不能リスク)を追加する。\n• **environment risk** が **ability risk** より重要なとき最も有効。\n• 協力を妨げたり **sabotage**(妨害)を招くことがある。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q6: 'Pay for relative performance more closely ties the quality of the product to employee rewards' (answer d). Q7: 'Ability risk is a factor prevalent in tournament pay' (answer c).", "whyNeeded": "演習Q6・Q7で出題。**environment risk**と**ability risk**の概念を区別する核心。出来高払いとの違い(共通要因の除去)が頻出。", "mistakes": ["**environment risk** と **ability risk** を混同する。トーナメントは前者を除き後者を加える。", "**tournament** が『不正をなくす』と誤解する(Q6で c は誤答)。協力を妨げ妨害を招くこともある。"], "memorize": "Tournament = relative pay: removes environment risk, adds ability risk."}, {"id": "c22_intrinsic_motivation", "ch": 22, "week": 3, "name": "Money Isn't Everything (Intrinsic Motivation)", "star": false, "scene": "子どもに家事の手伝いでお金を払うと、かえって自発的に手伝う気持ち(**intrinsic motivation**)が減ることがある。お金だけが強い誘因ではなく、**status**や**belonging**、**job satisfaction**も人を動かす。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Money is not the only powerful incentive; status, belonging, and job satisfaction matter too.", "defEN": "Money is not the only powerful incentive. Other incentives include **status**, **belonging**, and **job satisfaction**. One way of motivating workers is to help them identify with the corporation and its goals. When **intrinsic motivation** is strong, people are sometimes insulted by offers of money. Monetary rewards are most effective when supported by intrinsic motivation and measures of social status.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、人を動かすのはお金だけではない、という話です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• お金以外の誘因: **status**(地位)、**belonging**(帰属感)、**job satisfaction**(仕事の満足)。\n• 従業員を企業やその目標と同一視させることが動機づけの一つ。\n• **intrinsic motivation**(内発的動機)が強いと、金銭の申し出が逆に侮辱になることもある。\n• 金銭報酬は内発的動機と社会的地位に支えられたとき最も効果的。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q8: 'Paying children money to do family chores may reduce the child's intrinsic motivation for helping out around the house.' Answer: a.", "whyNeeded": "演習Q8で出題。金銭報酬が**intrinsic motivation**を損なう逆効果(crowding out)を理解する必要がある。報酬設計の限界を示す。", "mistakes": ["金銭報酬が**intrinsic motivation**を常に高めると誤解する。むしろ減らすことがある(Q8で b は誤答)。", "お金以外の誘因(**status**, **belonging**)を軽視する。"], "memorize": "More money can crowd out intrinsic motivation."}, {"id": "c22_nudge", "ch": 22, "week": 3, "name": "Nudge (Choice Architecture)", "star": false, "scene": "選択肢の見せ方をちょっと変えるだけで行動が変わる**nudge**。臓器提供を『初期設定で参加』にすると参加者が増える。『80% lean beef』は『20% fat beef』より売れる。禁止も大きな金銭変更もしない。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A nudge alters behavior in a predictable way without forbidding options or significantly changing economic incentives.", "defEN": "A **nudge** is any aspect of the **choice architecture** that alters behavior in a predictable way without forbidding any options or significantly changing their economic incentives. A nudge must be **easy and cheap to avoid**. Small changes in how a choice is presented, or **framed**, can matter a great deal (e.g., 80% lean beef sells better than 20% fat beef). Advocates stress their noncoercive nature and freedom of choice; critics see nudging as a form of manipulation or paternalism (Big Brother).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**nudge**(ナッジ)は『選択肢の見せ方を変えて行動をそっと変える』手法です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• **choice architecture**(選択の設計)の一部で、予測可能な形で行動を変える。\n• 選択肢を禁止せず、経済的誘因も大きく変えない。\n• **easy and cheap to avoid**(簡単・安価に避けられる)ものでなければならない。\n• **framing**(見せ方)が大きな差を生む: 『80% lean beef』>『20% fat beef』。\n• 臓器提供(**Organ Donation**)の初期設定が代表例。\n• 賛成派は非強制性を強調、批判派は**manipulation**(操作)や**paternalistic**(温情主義的)と見る。", "example": "80% lean beef sells better than 20% fat beef — the same product framed differently changes behavior. Organ donation default settings are a classic nudge.", "whyNeeded": "Ch22 Lesson 4の核心。**framing**で行動が変わる仕組みと、強制せず行動を誘導する点を理解する。", "mistakes": ["**nudge** が選択肢を禁止する/経済的誘因を大きく変えると誤解する。どちらもしない。", "**nudge** を避けにくいものと誤解する。easy and cheap to avoid が条件。"], "memorize": "Nudge = reframe the choice, easy to avoid, no ban."}, {"id": "c24_asymmetric_information", "ch": 24, "week": 3, "name": "Asymmetric Information", "star": true, "scene": "中古車の売り手は本当の品質を知っているが、買い手は知らない。このように取引の一方が相手より多くの情報を持つ状態が**asymmetric information**。情報が少ない側は取引が危険すぎて手を引くことがある。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Asymmetric information is when one party to an exchange has more or better information than the other.", "defEN": "**Asymmetric information** occurs when one party to an exchange has more or better information than the other party. When one party has more or better information, the **less-informed party may withdraw because trade is too risky**. Market institutions and regulations have evolved to deal with problems of asymmetric information. A study found taxi drivers detoured out-of-town passengers (about 10% longer rides) most when their information advantage was greatest; Swiss dentists recommended unnecessary fillings to 28% of test patients.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**asymmetric information**(情報の非対称性)は『取引の一方が相手より多く・良い情報を持つ』状態です。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 情報が少ない側(**less-informed party**)は、取引が危険すぎて撤退することがある。\n• 市場の制度や規制はこの問題に対処するため発達してきた。\n• 二大問題: **moral hazard**(モラルハザード)と **adverse selection**(逆選択)、そして **signaling**(シグナリング)。\n• 例: タクシー運転手が地元外の客を遠回り(約10%長く)させる/スイスの歯科医が不要な詰め物を勧める(180人中50人=28%)。", "example": "A study tracked airport-to-hotel cab rides: half of passengers were taken on detours about 10% longer, and out-of-town passengers were detoured more often — drivers took the longest detours when their information advantage was greatest.", "whyNeeded": "Ch24全体の土台概念。**moral hazard**、**adverse selection**、**signaling**はすべてここから派生する。情報が少ない側の撤退がなぜ市場を壊すか理解する基礎。", "mistakes": ["**asymmetric information** を単なる『情報不足』と誤解する。重要なのは一方が他方より優位な点。", "情報優位側ではなく、情報の少ない側(less-informed)が撤退する点を見落とす。"], "memorize": "Asymmetric info = one side knows more; the uninformed may withdraw."}, {"id": "c24_principal_agent", "ch": 24, "week": 3, "name": "Principal-Agent Problem", "star": true, "scene": "患者(**principal**)は歯科医(**agent**)を雇うが、歯科医の方が治療の必要性を知っている。どうすれば歯科医を患者の利益のために働かせられるか、という**principal-agent problem**。株主と経営者、有権者と政治家も同じ構造。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The principal-agent problem: how can a principal get an agent to act in the principal's interest when the agent has information the principal lacks?", "defEN": "The **principal-agent problem** asks: how can a **principal** incentivize an **agent** to work in the principal's interest even when the agent has information that the principal does not? Examples include patient-dentist, shareholder-management, manager-employee, voters-politicians, client-lawyer, and buyer/seller-real estate agent. A good incentive plan reduces unnecessary risk by tying rewards to actions that an agent controls.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**principal-agent problem**(プリンシパル・エージェント問題)は『情報を持つ**agent**(代理人)を、**principal**(依頼人)の利益のために働かせるにはどうするか』という問題です。\n\n--- 例 ---\n• 患者 ↔ 歯科医\n• 株主 ↔ 経営陣(**shareholder-management**)\n• 経営者 ↔ 従業員\n• 有権者 ↔ 政治家\n• 依頼人 ↔ 弁護士\n• 買い手/売り手 ↔ 不動産業者\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• **agent** が **principal** の持たない情報を持つことが問題の核。\n• 良い誘因計画は、**agent** が制御できる行動に報酬を結びつけ不要なリスクを減らす。", "example": "Patient (principal) vs dentist (agent): the dentist knows whether a filling is truly needed; the Swiss study found 28% of dentists recommended at least one unnecessary filling to a test patient who needed no treatment.", "whyNeeded": "情報の非対称性が引き起こす中心問題。**moral hazard**はこの枠組みで起こる。報酬設計(Ch22)とも直結する重要概念。", "mistakes": ["**principal**(依頼人)と **agent**(代理人)の役割を逆にする。情報優位なのは agent。", "**principal-agent problem** を **moral hazard** と完全に同一視する。前者は構造、後者は不正行動。"], "memorize": "Principal hires agent; agent knows more → principal-agent problem."}, {"id": "c24_moral_hazard", "ch": 24, "week": 3, "name": "Moral Hazard (Hidden Action)", "star": true, "scene": "保険に入った人が、守られているからと注意を怠る。あるいは車のディーラーが、まだ使えるタイヤの交換を勧める。契約後に情報優位を悪用するこの**hidden action**が**moral hazard**。", "compare": {"a": "Moral Hazard", "b": "Adverse Selection", "table": [{"dim": "Type of hidden information", "a": "Hidden action", "b": "Hidden characteristics"}, {"dim": "When it occurs", "a": "After a contract is agreed upon", "b": "Before/at the time of the offer"}, {"dim": "Definition", "a": "Agent exploits an information advantage dishonestly", "b": "An offer conveys negative information about the product"}, {"dim": "Classic example", "a": "Insured person is less careful; dealer recommends needless tire replacement", "b": "Lemons market; only sick people buy health insurance"}, {"dim": "Remedies", "a": "More information (reviews); better incentives (split inspection from sales, no-cure-no-pay)", "b": "Inspections, warranties, group rates, signaling"}]}, "punchline": "Moral hazard is when an agent exploits an information advantage in a dishonest or undesirable way, after a contract has been agreed.", "defEN": "**Moral hazard** (a **hidden action** problem) occurs when an agent tries to exploit an information advantage in a dishonest or undesirable way. Someone who is insured may be less careful. **Moral hazard occurs once a contract has been agreed upon.** The problem runs deeper than a transfer of wealth: unnecessary work wastes resources, and buyers aware of the moral hazard may decide not to buy, so the possibility of mutual gain is lost. Two ways to overcome it: (1) providing more information (reviews and ratings); (2) creating better incentives (splitting inspectors from salespeople; no-cure-no-pay / contingent-fee lawyers).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**moral hazard**(モラルハザード)は『契約後に、情報優位を不正・好ましくない形で悪用する』ことです(=**hidden action**, 隠れた行動)。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• **契約成立後**に起こる(ここが adverse selection と決定的に違う)。\n• 例: 保険に入ると不注意になる/カーディーラーがほぼ未使用のタイヤ交換を勧める。\n• 富の移転以上に深刻 — 不要な作業は資源の浪費。\n• 買い手が気づくと買わなくなり、相互利益(**mutual gain**)が失われる。\n\n--- 克服法 ---\n1. **more information**: レビューと評価。\n2. **better incentives**: 検査と販売を分離(会計士vsコンサル、不動産業者vs建物検査)、**no-cure-no-pay**(成功報酬)弁護士。", "example": "Weekly Test 3 Q2: 'A car dealership recommends that a customer replace barely used tires' is moral hazard (answer A). Solutions 3 Q2: a cab driver taking an out-of-town rider on a longer route is moral hazard (answer b).", "whyNeeded": "週テストQ2・演習Q2で頻出。**adverse selection**との区別(契約後 vs 提供時、隠れた行動 vs 隠れた特性)が試験の最重要ポイント。", "mistakes": ["**moral hazard** と **adverse selection** を混同する。前者は契約『後』の hidden action、後者は提供『時』の hidden characteristics。", "保険購入者『健康でない人が保険を買う』を moral hazard と誤答する(それは adverse selection)。"], "memorize": "Moral hazard = hidden ACTION, AFTER the contract."}, {"id": "c24_adverse_selection_lemons", "ch": 24, "week": 3, "name": "Adverse Selection & the Lemons Market", "star": true, "scene": "中古車市場で、売り手だけが品質を知る。買い手は平均価値$10,000しか払わないので、$12,000の良い車(**plum**)の持ち主は売らない。結果、市場には**lemon**(質の悪い車)ばかり残り、良い車が取引されなくなる**market failure**。", "compare": {"a": "Lemons (Low Quality)", "b": "Plums (High Quality)", "table": [{"dim": "Value", "a": "$8,000", "b": "$12,000"}, {"dim": "Buyer's willingness to pay (expected value)", "a": "Buyer pays the average = (½×$8,000)+(½×$12,000) = $10,000", "b": "Same average $10,000 offered"}, {"dim": "Will the seller sell at $10,000?", "a": "Yes (above $8,000 value)", "b": "No (below $12,000 value)"}, {"dim": "Outcome", "a": "If offered for sale, it's probably a lemon", "b": "High-quality used cars don't trade → market failure"}]}, "punchline": "Adverse selection occurs when an offer conveys negative information about the product being offered.", "defEN": "**Adverse selection** (a **hidden characteristics** problem) occurs when an offer contains negative information about the product being offered. In the lemons market, assume only sellers know true quality and there are equal numbers of **lemons** (worth $8,000) and **plums** (worth $12,000). Buyers will pay the expected value (½×$8,000)+(½×$12,000) = $10,000. A seller with a $12,000 car won't sell at $10,000, so if a car is offered, it's probably a **lemon**, and high-quality used cars don't trade — a **market failure**. The same logic applies to health insurance: sick people are more likely to want insurance, so the offer to buy implies above-average costs. Remedies: inspections, **warranties**, group rates, and propitious (favorable) selection.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**adverse selection**(逆選択)は『売り手の申し出自体が、その商品の悪い情報を伝えてしまう』ことです(=**hidden characteristics**, 隠れた特性)。\n\n--- レモン市場の数値 ---\n• **lemon**(質の悪い車)= $8,000、**plum**(質の良い車)= $12,000。\n• 仮定: 売り手だけが真の品質を知る/lemonとplumが同数。\n• 買い手は期待値 (½×$8,000)+(½×$12,000) = **$10,000** しか払わない。\n• $12,000の良い車の持ち主は$10,000では売らない。\n• → 売りに出される車はたいてい lemon。良質中古車は取引されず **market failure**(市場の失敗)。\n\n--- 健康保険でも同様 ---\n• 病気の人ほど保険を欲しがる → 保険購入の申し出が『平均以上のコスト』を示唆。\n• 保険料引上げ → 健康な人が抜ける → さらに引上げ → 採算が合わず market failure。\n\n--- 対策 ---\n• **inspections**(検査)、**warranties**(保証)、**group rates**(団体料率)、**propitious/favorable selection**。", "example": "Lemons market: lemons = $8,000, plums = $12,000, equal numbers. Buyer pays expected value (½×$8,000)+(½×$12,000) = $10,000. The plum owner won't sell at $10,000, so high-quality used cars don't trade — a market failure.", "whyNeeded": "演習Q5(良質中古車が売れない=market failure)で出題。**moral hazard**との対比と期待値$10,000の計算が試験頻出。健康保険の悪循環も重要。", "mistakes": ["**adverse selection** を **moral hazard** と混同する。前者は提供時の hidden characteristics、後者は契約後の hidden action。", "『健康でない人が保険を買う』を moral hazard と誤答する(週テストQ2 C は adverse selection の例)。"], "memorize": "Adverse selection = hidden CHARACTERISTICS; lemons drive out plums; expected value $10,000."}, {"id": "c24_signaling", "ch": 24, "week": 3, "name": "Signaling", "star": true, "scene": "Hyundaiは安かろう悪かろうと見られていたが、新工場や品質管理に投資し、手厚い**warranty**(保証)を導入した。保証は『車が壊れなければ利益になる』ので、品質への本気度を伝える信頼できる**signal**となり売上が急増した。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A signal is an expensive action taken to reveal information.", "defEN": "A **signal** is an **expensive action that is taken to reveal information**. When Hyundai entered the world market, its cars were seen as low quality, so it invested in new factories, worker training, and quality control, and introduced generous **warranty** plans; sales jumped fast. The warranty served two purposes: (1) it has value as insurance if something goes wrong; (2) it **signaled** that Hyundai was serious about quality. The signal was **credible** because it would only be profitable if the cars did not break down. In the labor market, a university degree signals desirable qualities, while offering to work for low pay signals you might be a low-quality worker.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**signal**(シグナル)は『情報を伝えるために、わざとコストのかかる行動をとる』ことです。\n\n--- Hyundaiの例 ---\n• 当初は低品質と見られていた。\n• 新工場・研修・品質管理に投資し、手厚い **warranty**(保証)を導入。\n• 売上が急増。\n• 保証の二つの役割: (1)故障時の保険としての価値、(2)品質への本気度の **signal**。\n• **credible**(信頼できる)理由: 車が壊れなければ利益になるから = 自信の表れ。\n\n--- 労働市場 ---\n• 大学の学位は employer に望ましい資質を伝える **signal**。\n• 低賃金で働くと申し出ると『低品質な労働者かも』というシグナルになる。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q6: obtaining a college education signals that a potential employee 'has determination and a relatively high IQ' (answer c). Hyundai's generous warranty signaled quality because it would only be profitable if its cars did not break down.", "whyNeeded": "演習Q6で出題。**signal**が信頼できる条件(コストがかかり、嘘なら割に合わない)を理解する。学位や保証がなぜ情報を伝えるか問われる。", "mistakes": ["大学教育のシグナルを『job に必要な知識を全て知っている』と誤答する(Q6 d は誤り、c が正解)。", "**signal** を『安い宣伝』と誤解する。expensive(高コスト)であることが信頼性の源。"], "memorize": "Signal = expensive action revealing info; credible only if costly to fake."}, {"id": "c25_budget_constraint", "ch": 25, "week": 3, "name": "Budget Constraint", "star": true, "scene": "所得$100で、ピザ(X, 価格$10)とドリンク(Y, 価格$2)を買う。買える組み合わせは 10X + 2Y = 100 の**budget line**(予算線)上。所得が増えると線は平行に外側へ、Xの価格が下がると線は外側に回転して平らになる。", "compare": {"a": "Increase in Income", "b": "Decrease in Price of X", "table": [{"dim": "Effect on the budget line", "a": "Shifts upward in a parallel way", "b": "Rotates outward (becomes flatter)"}, {"dim": "Slope", "a": "Unchanged", "b": "Changes (flatter)"}, {"dim": "Intercepts", "a": "Both move out equally", "b": "Only the X-intercept moves out"}]}, "punchline": "The budget constraint shows all the consumption bundles a consumer can afford, given income and prices.", "defEN": "The **budget constraint** shows all the consumption bundles a consumer can afford, given the consumer's income and prices. With two goods x and y, spending on good x = **Px·X** and on good y = **Py·Y**, and total spending must satisfy **Px·X + Py·Y ≤ I**. Example: with Px=10, Py=2, I=100, the budget line is 10X + 2Y = 100. An **increase in income** shifts the budget line upward in a **parallel** way; a **decrease in the price of X** rotates the budget line **outward (becomes flatter)**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**budget constraint**(予算制約)は『所得と価格のもとで買える消費の組み合わせ全部』を示します。\n\n--- 計算 ---\n• 財X支出 = **Px·X**、財Y支出 = **Py·Y**。\n• **Px·X + Py·Y ≤ I**(所得)。\n• 例: Px=10, Py=2, I=100 → **budget line**: 10X + 2Y = 100。\n\n--- シフト ---\n• 所得増 → 予算線が**平行**に外側へ移動。\n• Xの価格低下 → 予算線が外側に**回転**し平らになる。\n• 所得減 → 予算線が内側に平行移動(演習Q5の答え)。", "example": "Weekly Test 3 Q3: Pa=$2, Pb=$5, I=$30. On the edge of the budget constraint: 2A+5B=30. Bundle (5,4): 2(5)+5(4)=10+20=30 ✓ (answer B). Other bundles either fall short or exceed $30.", "whyNeeded": "週テストQ3・演習Q5で出題。予算線の式 Px·X+Py·Y=I の計算と、所得・価格変化によるシフト/回転の区別が試験頻出。消費者最適化の前提。", "mistakes": ["所得変化(平行シフト)と価格変化(回転)を混同する。", "予算線『上』(=支出が所得に等しい edge)と『内側』(余り)を混同する。"], "memorize": "Px·X + Py·Y = I. Income → parallel shift; price → rotation."}, {"id": "c25_indifference_curve_mrs", "ch": 25, "week": 3, "name": "Indifference Curve & MRS", "star": true, "scene": "同じ満足(**utility**)を与える財の組み合わせを結んだ線が**indifference curve**(無差別曲線)。その傾きの絶対値が**MRS**(限界代替率)で、消費者がある財をもう一方とどれだけ交換しても無差別かを表す。", "compare": null, "punchline": "An indifference curve connects all bundles giving the same utility; its slope is the MRS.", "defEN": "An **indifference curve** is a curve connecting all combinations of goods, or consumption bundles, that give the consumer the same **utility**. The **marginal rate of substitution (MRS)** is the rate at which the consumer is willing to trade one good for another and remain indifferent, and **MRS = |the slope of the indifference curve|**. The optimality condition is **MRSab = Pa/Pb**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**indifference curve**(無差別曲線)は『同じ**utility**(効用)を与える財の組み合わせを結んだ線』です。\n\n--- MRS ---\n• **MRS**(marginal rate of substitution, 限界代替率)= 消費者が無差別なまま一方の財をもう一方とどれだけ交換するか。\n• **MRS = |無差別曲線の傾き|**。\n• 最適条件: **MRSab = Pa/Pb**。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q6: 'The MRS is 3; the consumer is willing to give up 3 movie downloads for an additional music download' between bundles A and B (answer b).", "whyNeeded": "演習Q6で出題。**MRS**の意味(交換比率=傾きの絶対値)と最適化条件 MRS=Pa/Pb への橋渡し。消費者選択の中核。", "mistakes": ["**MRS** を傾きそのもの(負)と曲線の傾きの『絶対値』を混同する。MRS は絶対値。", "MRS を『何倍買うか』と誤解する(Q6 c は誤答)。交換して諦める量。"], "memorize": "MRS = |slope of indifference curve| = willingness to trade."}, {"id": "c25_utility_maximization_rule", "ch": 25, "week": 3, "name": "Utility Maximization (MU per Dollar Rule)", "star": true, "scene": "最後の1ドルから得られる満足(**marginal utility per dollar**)が全ての財で等しくなるように予算を配分すれば効用が最大。**MUa/Pa = MUb/Pb = … = MUz/Pz** が成り立ち、かつ所得を全て使い切る。", "compare": null, "punchline": "To maximize utility, allocate spending so the marginal utility per dollar is equal for all goods.", "defEN": "**Marginal utility** is the change in utility from consuming an additional unit (MUa is the marginal utility of good A). The optimal consumption bundle is on the highest indifference curve still on the budget constraint. The optimality rule **MRSab = Pa/Pb** can also be written as **MUa/MUb = Pa/Pb**, i.e., **MUa/Pa = MUb/Pb**. To maximize utility, a consumer should allocate spending so that the **marginal utility per dollar is equal for all goods**: MUa/Pa = MUb/Pb = … = MUz/Pz, and all income is spent.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、効用を最大化するには『1ドルあたりの満足(**marginal utility per dollar**)を全部の財で同じにする』ように配分します。\n\n--- 定義と式 ---\n• **marginal utility**(限界効用)= 追加1単位の消費による効用の変化。MUa は財Aの限界効用。\n• 最適バンドルは、予算制約上で最も高い無差別曲線上の点。\n• 最適条件: **MRSab = Pa/Pb = MUa/MUb** → **MUa/Pa = MUb/Pb = … = MUz/Pz**。\n• かつ所得を全て使い切る(all income is spent)。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q4: 'Consumers maximize their utility when the marginal utility per dollar is equal across all goods consumed and all income is spent.' Answer: b.", "whyNeeded": "演習Q4で直接出題。**MU/P**均等化ルールは消費者理論の核心で、需要曲線の導出につながる。試験で式と条件が頻出。", "mistakes": ["『総便益>総費用なら最大化』と誤解する(Q4 a は誤答)。条件は限界効用/価格の均等。", "**marginal utility**(限界効用)と total utility(総効用)を混同する。最適化は限界で見る。"], "memorize": "Max utility: MUa/Pa = MUb/Pb = … and spend all income."}, {"id": "c25_income_substitution_effects", "ch": 25, "week": 3, "name": "Income & Substitution Effects", "star": true, "scene": "ある財の価格が下がると、その財の消費が変わる。理由は二つ: 実質的な購買力が増える**income effect**(所得効果)と、相対価格が変わって安くなった財に乗り換える**substitution effect**(代替効果)。", "compare": {"a": "Income Effect", "b": "Substitution Effect", "table": [{"dim": "Cause", "a": "Change in purchasing power from a price change", "b": "Change in relative price"}, {"dim": "Held constant", "a": "(Real purchasing power changes)", "b": "Utility held constant"}, {"dim": "Definition", "a": "Change in consumption from changed purchasing power", "b": "Change in consumption from a change in relative price, holding utility constant"}, {"dim": "Labor supply when wage falls", "a": "Less leisure; more work", "b": "Leisure cheaper → more leisure; less work"}]}, "punchline": "A price change has two effects: the income effect and the substitution effect.", "defEN": "A change in price causes consumers to change their consumption bundle, and a drop in the price of one good can increase consumption of both goods, because a price change has two effects. The **income effect** is the change in consumption caused by the change in **purchasing power** resulting from a price change. The **substitution effect** is the change in consumption caused by a change in the **relative price**, **holding utility constant**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、価格が変わると消費が変わり、その変化は二つの効果に分解できます。\n\n--- 二つの効果 ---\n• **income effect**(所得効果): 価格変化による**purchasing power**(購買力)の変化が引き起こす消費の変化。\n• **substitution effect**(代替効果): **relative price**(相対価格)の変化が引き起こす消費の変化。ただし**utility constant**(効用一定)で測る。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• ある財の価格低下 → 両方の財の消費が増えることもある。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q7: a consumer moves from point A to point B; the substitution effect of the price change causes the consumer to 'reduce the number of music downloads by 3' (answer a).", "whyNeeded": "演習Q7・労働供給モデルで出題。**income effect**と**substitution effect**の分解は価格変化や賃金変化の分析に不可欠。両者の区別が試験頻出。", "mistakes": ["**income effect**(購買力)と **substitution effect**(相対価格、効用一定)を混同する。", "substitution effect が utility を一定に保つ点を見落とす。"], "memorize": "Income effect = purchasing power; substitution effect = relative price (utility held constant)."}, {"id": "c25_labor_supply_backward_bending", "ch": 25, "week": 3, "name": "Labor Supply (Income-Leisure Model)", "star": true, "scene": "賃金が変わると、働く時間も**income effect**と**substitution effect**で決まる。賃金が下がると、所得効果では『余暇も減らしてもっと働く』、代替効果では『余暇が割安になりもっと休む』。どちらが勝つかで労働供給曲線が右上がりか後方屈曲かが決まる。", "compare": {"a": "Substitution Effect Dominates", "b": "Income Effect Dominates", "table": [{"dim": "When wage falls", "a": "Leisure cheaper → more leisure, less work", "b": "Demand for normal goods (incl. leisure) falls → less leisure, more work"}, {"dim": "Labor supply curve shape", "a": "Upward sloping (more wage → more work)", "b": "Backward-bending / downward sloping"}, {"dim": "Worker's response to higher wages", "a": "Works more hours", "b": "May work fewer hours"}]}, "punchline": "A worker's response to a wage change depends on the income and substitution effects.", "defEN": "In the **income-leisure model**, a worker's response to a change in wages depends on the income and substitution effects. The **income effect (IE)**: when the wage (income) falls, the demand for **normal goods (including leisure)** also falls — less leisure, more work. The **substitution effect (SE)**: when the wage falls, leisure becomes relatively cheaper — more leisure, less work. When the substitution effect dominates, the labor supply curve is upward sloping; when the income effect dominates, it can be **backward-bending (downward sloping)**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、賃金が変わったとき何時間働くかは、所得効果と代替効果のどちらが勝つかで決まります。\n\n--- 賃金が下がるとき ---\n• **income effect (IE)**: 所得が減る → 正常財(余暇 **leisure** 含む)の需要も減る → 余暇を減らし**もっと働く**。\n• **substitution effect (SE)**: 余暇が相対的に割安に → 余暇を増やし**働かなくなる**。\n\n--- 曲線の形 ---\n• **SE が勝つ** → 労働供給曲線は右上がり(賃上げで労働増)。\n• **IE が勝つ** → **backward-bending**(後方屈曲)/右下がりの労働供給曲線。", "example": "Solutions 3 Q8 (Leisure 2 figure): the statement that is TRUE is 'The labor supply curve is downward sloping' (answer b) — the income effect dominates.", "whyNeeded": "演習Q8で出題。**income effect**と**substitution effect**を労働供給に応用する典型問題。後方屈曲労働供給曲線の理解が試験頻出。", "mistakes": ["賃金低下時の IE(働く増)と SE(働く減)の方向を逆にする。", "**backward-bending** 労働供給曲線がいつ生じるか(IE 優位)を誤解する。"], "memorize": "SE dominates → upward labor supply; IE dominates → backward-bending."}, {"id": "c26_gdp_definition", "ch": 26, "week": 5, "name": "Gross Domestic Product (GDP)", "star": true, "scene": "ある国が1年間にどれだけ生産したかを1つの数字で表したい状況。経済には何百万種類もの財・サービスがあり、しかも価値が違うので単純に量を足せない。そこで**market value**(市場価値)を使って合計する **GDP** が登場する。", "compare": null, "punchline": "GDP is the market value of all final goods and services produced within a country in a year.", "defEN": "**Gross Domestic Product (GDP)** is the **market value** of all **final goods and services** produced within a country in a year.\n\nAn economy's total output includes millions of different goods and services, and some goods are more valuable than others, so we cannot just add up quantities. GDP uses **market values** to determine how much each good or service is worth and then sums the total. To avoid **double counting**, only **final goods** are included in GDP; **intermediate goods** (sold to firms and processed for sale at a later stage) are excluded.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**GDP**(国内総生産)は『その国で1年間に作られた**final goods and services**(最終財・サービス)の市場価値の合計』です。\n\n--- なぜ market value を使うか ---\n• 経済には何百万種類もの財・サービスがあり、価値が違うので量を単純に足せない。\n• そこで **market value**(市場価値)で各財の価値を測って合計する。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• **double counting**(二重計上)を避けるため、**final goods**(最終財)だけを数える。\n• **intermediate goods**(中間財)は企業に売られ後工程で加工されるので除外。\n• \"within a country\" なので、アメリカ国内で生産していれば外国企業(例: Toyota)の生産もアメリカの GDP に含まれる。", "example": "A set of tires installed on a vehicle in an automobile factory is an intermediate good, so its market price is NOT separately part of GDP. Toyota, a Japanese car company, producing cars in the United States IS counted in U.S. GDP.", "whyNeeded": "経済成長を測るには『縦軸=何が growth か』を定義する必要があり、その基礎が **GDP**。**final goods** と **intermediate goods** の区別、**market value** の使い方は試験で頻出。", "mistakes": ["**final goods** と **intermediate goods** を混同する誤り。自動車工場で取り付けるタイヤは intermediate good。", "GDP を生産者の国籍で決めると誤解する誤り。基準は『どの国の領域内で生産したか(within a country)』。"], "memorize": "GDP = market value of FINAL goods within a country in a year"}, {"id": "c26_gdp_per_capita", "ch": 26, "week": 5, "name": "GDP per Capita", "star": true, "scene": "2つの国が同じ **real GDP** の成長率でも、人口の増え方が違えば一人当たりの豊かさは大きく異なる状況。生活水準を測るには人口で割った **GDP per capita** が要る。", "compare": {"a": "Real GDP Growth", "b": "Real GDP per Capita Growth", "table": [{"dim": "Adjusts for population?", "a": "No", "b": "Yes"}, {"dim": "What it reflects", "a": "Total national output", "b": "Living standards / standard of living"}, {"dim": "Guatemala 1993-2003", "a": "3.6% per year", "b": "0.8% per year"}, {"dim": "United States 1993-2003", "a": "3.6% per year", "b": "2.1% per year"}]}, "punchline": "GDP per capita is GDP divided by population, the best rough measure of living standards.", "defEN": "**GDP per capita** is **GDP divided by population**. Growth in real GDP does not account for changes in population, so growth in **real GDP per capita** is usually the best reflection of changing **living standards**. There can be large differences for countries with rapidly growing populations.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**GDP per capita**(一人当たり GDP)は『**GDP ÷ population**(人口)』です。生活水準のざっくりした目安になります。\n\n--- なぜ必要か ---\n• **real GDP** の成長は人口変化を考慮しない。\n• **real GDP per capita** の成長こそ **living standards**(生活水準)の変化を最もよく反映する。\n• 人口が急増する国では real GDP と一人当たりとで大きな差が出る。", "example": "Guatemala and the U.S. both had 3.6% annual real GDP growth (1993-2003), but Guatemala's population grew 2.8% and the U.S.'s only 1.2%. So real GDP per capita grew only 0.8% in Guatemala versus 2.1% in the U.S., meaning living standards rose much faster in the U.S.", "whyNeeded": "国の総生産(**real GDP**)ではなく『国民一人の豊かさ』を比較するのに不可欠。人口成長が速い国の比較で **per capita** を使う判断は試験で頻出。", "mistakes": ["**real GDP growth** と **real GDP per capita growth** を同一視する誤り。人口成長を引かないと生活水準を測れない。", "GDP per capita を所得分配の指標と勘違いする誤り。GDP は distribution of income を測らない。"], "memorize": "Per capita = GDP / population → living standards"}, {"id": "c26_growth_rate", "ch": 26, "week": 5, "name": "GDP Growth Rate", "star": true, "scene": "GDP の『水準(level)』は国がどれだけ生産したかを示すが、生産が『どれだけ速く増減しているか』を知りたい状況。そこで2年間の GDP を比べる **growth rate** を計算する。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The GDP growth rate is the percentage change in GDP from one year to the next.", "defEN": "GDP tells us how much a country produced; the **growth rate of GDP** tells us how rapidly the country's production is rising or falling.\n\nGrowth rate = ((GDP_this_year − GDP_last_year) / GDP_last_year) × 100.\n\nThis distinguishes the **level** of GDP from the **growth rate** of GDP.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**GDP growth rate**(GDP成長率)は『前年と比べて GDP が何%増えた(減った)か』です。\n\n--- 計算 ---\nGrowth = (GDP今年 − GDP前年) ÷ GDP前年 × 100\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• **level**(水準)は『どれだけ生産したか』、**growth rate**(成長率)は『どれだけ速く増減したか』。この区別が重要。\n• 価格調整しないものは **nominal growth rate**(名目成長率)と呼ぶ。", "example": "Using actual U.S. numbers (in billions): for 2013, ($16,798 − $16,245) / $16,245 × 100 = 3.4%.", "whyNeeded": "景気が拡大しているか後退しているかを判断する基本指標。**level** と **growth rate** の混同を避けることが試験で問われる。", "mistakes": ["GDP の **level**(水準)と **growth rate**(成長率)を混同する誤り。", "計算で分母を当年(後の年)にしてしまう誤り。分母は基準となる前年の GDP。"], "memorize": "Growth = (ΔGDP / GDP_old) × 100"}, {"id": "c26_nominal_vs_real_gdp", "ch": 26, "week": 5, "name": "Nominal vs. Real GDP", "star": true, "scene": "GDP が増えたとき、それが『本当に生産量が増えた』のか『価格が上がっただけ』なのか区別したい状況。価格変化を含む **nominal GDP** と、価格を一定にした **real GDP** を分けて考える。", "compare": {"a": "Nominal GDP", "b": "Real GDP", "table": [{"dim": "Prices used", "a": "Prices at the time of sale (current prices)", "b": "Same (constant) prices in all periods"}, {"dim": "Adjusted for price changes?", "a": "No (nominal variable)", "b": "Yes (real variable)"}, {"dim": "2000 GDP example", "a": "2000 prices × 2000 quantities = $10.3 trillion", "b": "2013 prices × 2000 quantities = $13.8 trillion"}, {"dim": "Increase 2000 to 2013", "a": "(16.8 − 10.3)/10.3 × 100 = 63%", "b": "(16.8 − 13.8)/13.8 × 100 = 21.7%"}]}, "punchline": "Nominal GDP uses current prices; real GDP uses constant prices to strip out inflation.", "defEN": "**Nominal GDP** is calculated using prices at the time of sale (GDP in 2013 uses 2013 prices). **Nominal variables** are variables such as GDP that have not been adjusted for changes in price.\n\nTo remove the effect of price changes, we calculate GDP in **constant prices**. **Real variables** are variables that have been adjusted for changes in prices by using the same set of prices in all time periods. The increase in **real GDP** measures the true change in output.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**nominal GDP**(名目GDP)は『その時点の価格』で計算した GDP、**real GDP**(実質GDP)は『すべての年で同じ価格』を使って価格変化を除いた GDP です。\n\n--- 仕組み ---\n• **nominal**: 各年をその年の価格で評価(価格変化を含む)。\n• **real**: すべての年を同じ(基準年の)価格で評価(価格変化を除く)。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• 名目の伸びには『価格上昇分+生産増加分』が混ざる。\n• 実質の伸びは『純粋な生産増加分』だけ。", "example": "2000 nominal GDP = 2000 prices × 2000 quantities = $10.3 trillion. 2000 real GDP (in 2013 dollars) = 2013 prices × 2000 quantities = $13.8 trillion. Nominal rose 63% to 2013 but real GDP rose only 21.7%, because nominal includes price increases.", "whyNeeded": "経済成長(生産の増加)とインフレ(価格の上昇)を区別するために不可欠。**nominal** と **real** の取り違えは計算問題で命取り。", "mistakes": ["**nominal GDP** と **real GDP** を逆にする誤り。real は『同じ価格をすべての年に使う』。", "real GDP を計算するとき各年のその年の価格を使ってしまう誤り。基準年の価格を全年に適用する。"], "memorize": "Nominal = current prices; Real = constant (base-year) prices"}, {"id": "c26_gdp_deflator", "ch": 26, "week": 5, "name": "GDP Deflator", "star": true, "scene": "名目GDPと実質GDPの両方が分かったとき、その差から物価がどれだけ上がったか(インフレ)を測りたい状況。両者の比から **GDP deflator** を作る。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The GDP deflator is a price index equal to (nominal GDP / real GDP) × 100, used to measure inflation.", "defEN": "The **GDP Deflator** is a **price index** that can be used to measure **inflation**. It is the ratio of nominal to real GDP:\n\nGDP Deflator = (Nominal GDP / Real GDP) × 100.\n\nA deflator above 100 indicates prices have risen relative to the base year, and the amount above 100 gives the inflation rate from the base year.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**GDP deflator**(GDPデフレーター)は『**nominal GDP ÷ real GDP × 100**』で求める物価指数で、**inflation**(インフレ)を測るのに使います。\n\n--- 計算 ---\nGDP Deflator = (Nominal GDP ÷ Real GDP) × 100\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• 100 を超えた分が基準年からのインフレ率。\n• 例: deflator が 110 ならインフレ率は 110 − 100 = 10%。", "example": "If 2013 nominal GDP = $16.79 trillion and 2013 real GDP = $15.76 trillion, then GDP Deflator = (16.79 / 15.76) × 100 = 106.5. In the pizza/pretzel economy, GDP deflator 2011 = (3,630,000 / 3,300,000) × 100 = 110, implying inflation of 110 − 100 = 10%.", "whyNeeded": "名目と実質の GDP データだけからインフレ率を計算する標準ツール。演習・週テストの計算問題で頻出。", "mistakes": ["分子と分母を逆にする誤り。Nominal が上、Real が下。", "deflator の値そのものをインフレ率と勘違いする誤り。インフレ率は『deflator − 100』。"], "memorize": "Deflator = (Nominal / Real) × 100; inflation = deflator − 100"}, {"id": "c26_national_spending_approach", "ch": 26, "week": 5, "name": "National Spending Approach (Y = C + I + G + NX)", "star": true, "scene": "GDP を『誰が何に支出したか』の側面から分解したい状況。消費・投資・政府支出・純輸出の4つの支出要素を足し上げる **national spending approach** を使う。", "compare": {"a": "National Spending Approach", "b": "Factor Income Approach", "table": [{"dim": "Identity", "a": "Y = C + I + G + NX", "b": "Y = Wages + Rent + Interest + Profit"}, {"dim": "What it adds up", "a": "Components of spending", "b": "Income generated by production"}, {"dim": "Perspective", "a": "Classes of income spending", "b": "Classes of income receiving"}, {"dim": "Adjustment needed", "a": "Net exports = exports − imports", "b": "Adjust for things like sales taxes"}]}, "punchline": "The national spending approach splits GDP into spending: Y = C + I + G + NX.", "defEN": "The **national spending approach** adds up the components of spending: **Y = C + I + G + NX**.\n\n- **C (Consumption)**: private spending on final goods and services.\n- **I (Investment)**: private spending on tools, plant, and equipment used to produce future output.\n- **G (Government purchases)**: spending by all levels of government on final goods and services; **transfers are not included**.\n- **NX (Net exports)**: the value of exports minus the value of imports.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**national spending approach**(支出アプローチ)は GDP を支出の側から分解する『**Y = C + I + G + NX**』です。\n\n--- 各要素 ---\n• **C (Consumption)**: 最終財・サービスへの民間支出。\n• **I (Investment)**: 将来の生産に使う道具・工場・設備への民間支出。\n• **G (Government purchases)**: 各レベルの政府の最終財・サービス支出。**transfers**(移転支出)は含まない。\n• **NX (Net exports)**: 輸出 − 輸入。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• 輸入された消費財は C に入っても NX で差し引かれ、最終 GDP に二重に乗らない。", "example": "Robinson Crusoe produces fish, coconuts and huts worth £4,400. With C = £4,000 (eaten goods) and I = £400 (huts built as future-output capital) and no trade, Y = C + I = £4,400. When a clock, shirt and books worth £7 wash up as imported consumer goods, C rises to £4,007 but NX = −£7, so Y stays £4,400.", "whyNeeded": "マクロ経済の最重要恒等式。各支出要素の定義(特に G から transfers を除く、I が将来生産のための支出である点)が試験で問われる。", "mistakes": ["**government purchases** に **transfers**(移転支出)を含めてしまう誤り。transfers は含まない。", "輸入された消費財をそのまま GDP に加える誤り。NX で imports を差し引く必要がある(GDP の P は『国内生産』)。"], "memorize": "Y = C + I + G + NX (spending side)"}, {"id": "c26_factor_income_approach", "ch": 26, "week": 5, "name": "Factor Income Approach", "star": false, "scene": "消費者が支払ったお金は、労働者・地主・資本所有者・企業の誰かが受け取る。そこで GDP を『受け取った所得』の側から積み上げたい状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The factor income approach computes GDP by summing the incomes earned in production: wages + rent + interest + profit.", "defEN": "The **factor income approach** adds up the income generated by producing goods and services:\n\n**Y = Employee Compensation + Rent + Interest + Profit**.\n\nWhen a consumer spends money, the money is received by workers, landlords, owners of capital, and businesses, so we can calculate GDP by adding up all the incomes received. When using the factor income approach, we need to adjust for things like **sales taxes**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**factor income approach**(要素所得アプローチ)は GDP を『生産で生まれた所得』の側から足し上げる方法で『**Y = Employee Compensation + Rent + Interest + Profit**』です。\n\n--- 考え方 ---\n• 消費者の支出は、労働者・地主・資本所有者・企業の所得になる。\n• だから受け取った所得をすべて足せば GDP になる。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• **sales taxes**(売上税)などの調整が必要。\n• 支出側(spending)= 受取側(income)で同じ GDP になる。", "example": "Y = Employee compensation + Rent + Interest + Profit. Because every dollar a consumer spends becomes someone's income (a worker's wage, a landlord's rent, a lender's interest, or a firm's profit), summing these incomes (after adjusting for sales taxes) yields the same GDP as the spending approach.", "whyNeeded": "GDP を支出と所得の両面から測れることを理解する鍵。national spending approach との対比で出題されやすい。", "mistakes": ["**factor income approach** と **national spending approach** の式を取り違える誤り。所得側は Wages + Rent + Interest + Profit。", "**sales taxes** の調整を忘れる誤り。"], "memorize": "Income side: Y = Wages + Rent + Interest + Profit"}, {"id": "c26_problems_with_gdp", "ch": 26, "week": 5, "name": "Problems with GDP as a Measure of Welfare", "star": false, "scene": "GDP は生産の優れた推計だが、人々の幸福(welfare)をそのまま測れるわけではない。GDP に含まれないものが何かを理解したい状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "GDP omits non-priced production, leisure, the underground economy, and income distribution.", "defEN": "GDP is an estimate of the economic output of a nation over a year, but it has limits as a measure of welfare:\n\n- GDP does not count **non-priced production**, when valuable goods and services are produced but no monetary payment is made.\n- GDP does not count **leisure**, economic \"bads\", and **illegal or underground-market transactions**.\n- GDP does not measure the **distribution of income**.\n\nGDP does, however, account for priced market activity such as medical services.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**GDP** は生産の良い推計だけど、幸福(welfare)の指標としては抜けがある、という話です。\n\n--- GDP に含まれないもの ---\n• **non-priced production**(値段のつかない生産)。\n• **leisure**(余暇)や economic \"bads\"。\n• **underground economy / illegal transactions**(地下経済・違法取引)。\n• **distribution of income**(所得分配)は測らない。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• 地下経済の規模は毎年ほぼ一定なので、『景気の変化』を見るには問題になりにくい(温度計の単位やシューズを履いたまま体重計に乗る比喩)。\n• 医療サービスのような有償の活動は GDP に含まれる。", "example": "GDP includes medical services (a priced activity) but excludes pollution, leisure, the underground economy, and the distribution of income. Because the underground economy stays about the same size year to year, it does not distort GDP as a measure of changes (like always wearing your shoes on the scale).", "whyNeeded": "GDP を『豊かさ・幸福』の完全な指標と誤解しないため。何が含まれ何が含まれないかの選択問題が頻出。", "mistakes": ["GDP が **leisure** や **distribution of income** を測ると勘違いする誤り。どちらも含まれない。", "地下経済の測定困難さが『景気変化の判定』を狂わせると思い込む誤り。規模が一定なら問題にならない。"], "memorize": "GDP misses: non-priced, leisure, underground, distribution"}, {"id": "c28_solow_production_function", "ch": 28, "week": 5, "name": "Solow Production Function Y = F(A, K, eL)", "star": true, "scene": "なぜ国の GDP が時間とともに成長する(しない)のか、成長の限界はどこかを理解したい状況。**Solow model** は生産関数から始め、産出 Y を3つの要素に結びつける。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The Solow model starts with Y = F(A, K, eL): output depends on ideas, physical capital, and education-augmented labor.", "defEN": "The **Solow model** begins with a **production function**. The total output of an economy (**Y**) depends on:\n\n- **Physical capital (K)**\n- **Human capital, or education × Labor (eL)**\n- **Ideas (A)**\n\nA production function expresses a relationship between output and the factors of production: **Y = F(A, K, eL)**. If we assume that A, e, and L are constant, output simplifies to **Y = F(K)**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**Solow model**(ソロー成長モデル)は『なぜ GDP が成長する/しないか、成長の限界はどこか』を理解する基本モデルで、生産関数 **Y = F(A, K, eL)** から始めます。\n\n--- 3つの生産要素 ---\n• **K**: physical capital(物的資本)。\n• **eL**: human capital(人的資本)= education × Labor。\n• **A**: ideas(アイデア・技術)。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• A, e, L を一定と仮定すると **Y = F(K)** に簡略化できる。\n• この簡略形が catching-up growth の分析の出発点。", "example": "Y = F(A, K, eL). Holding A, e, and L constant gives Y = F(K), e.g. the specific form Y = √K used to analyze how more capital raises output at a diminishing rate.", "whyNeeded": "経済成長の全分析の土台。産出が capital(K)・education×labor(eL)・ideas(A)に依存するという枠組みが試験で問われる。", "mistakes": ["**eL** を単なる労働量 L と混同する誤り。eL は education を掛けた human capital。", "A を物的資本と勘違いする誤り。A は ideas / 技術(productivity)。"], "memorize": "Y = F(A, K, eL): A=ideas, K=capital, eL=education×labor"}, {"id": "c28_diminishing_returns_capital", "ch": 28, "week": 5, "name": "Diminishing Returns to Capital (Marginal Product of Capital)", "star": true, "scene": "資本(K)を増やせば産出(Y)は増えるが、増え方はだんだん鈍る状況。なぜ豊かな国の成長が鈍り、資本の少ない国が急成長できるのかを説明する鍵。", "compare": null, "punchline": "More capital raises output but at a diminishing rate: the marginal product of capital falls as capital grows.", "defEN": "More capital (K) should produce more output (Y) but at a **diminishing rate**. The **marginal product of capital** is the increase in output caused by the addition of one more unit of capital, and it **diminishes** as more and more capital is added.\n\nThe MPK diminishes because the first unit of capital is applied where it is most productive, the second where it is slightly less productive, and so on. For the production function Y = F(K) = √K, output is the square root of capital.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**diminishing returns to capital**(資本の収穫逓減)は『資本 K を増やすと産出 Y は増えるが、増え方はだんだん小さくなる』ことです。\n\n--- 定義 ---\n• **marginal product of capital (MPK)**: 資本を1単位増やしたときの産出の増加分。資本が増えるほど MPK は **diminishes**(逓減)。\n• 最初の1単位は最も生産的な場所に、次は少し生産性の低い場所に…と使われるため。\n\n--- 例 (Y = √K) ---\n• K = 4 → Y = √4 = 2\n• K = 16 → Y = √16 = 4\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• 資本の少ない国(例: 改革初期の China)は MPK が高く急成長できる。\n• 資本が積み上がると MPK が下がり、成長率も下がる。", "example": "With Y = √K: if K = 4 then Y = 2; if K increases to 16 then Y = 4. China grew rapidly because it began with very little capital, so the marginal product of capital was very high; its growth rate will fall as the marginal product of capital falls.", "whyNeeded": "なぜ catching-up growth が永遠に続かず steady state で止まるのかの中心メカニズム。convergence の説明にも直結。", "mistakes": ["収穫逓減を『資本を増やすと産出が減る』と誤解する誤り。産出は増えるが『増え方』が鈍るだけ。", "**marginal product of capital** を平均生産性と混同する誤り。MPK は追加1単位の増分。"], "memorize": "MPK falls as K rises (Y = √K curve flattens)"}, {"id": "c28_capital_depreciation", "ch": 28, "week": 5, "name": "Capital, Investment and Depreciation", "star": true, "scene": "産出の一部は消費されず投資されて新しい資本になる。一方で既存の資本は摩耗(depreciate)する。資本がどう増減するかを決める2つの力を整理したい状況。", "compare": {"a": "Investment (γY)", "b": "Depreciation (δK)", "table": [{"dim": "What it does to capital", "a": "Adds new capital", "b": "Wears out / removes capital"}, {"dim": "Driven by", "a": "Fraction of output invested, gamma (γ)", "b": "Fraction of capital that wears out, delta (δ)"}, {"dim": "Shape vs capital stock", "a": "Increases at a diminishing rate", "b": "Increases at a linear (constant) rate"}, {"dim": "Example fraction", "a": "γ = 3/10 = 0.3", "b": "δ = 2/100 = 0.02"}]}, "punchline": "Investment (a fraction γ of output) adds capital; depreciation (a fraction δ of capital) wears it out.", "defEN": "**Capital** is output that is saved and invested rather than consumed. We write the fraction of output that is invested in new capital as **gamma (γ)**; e.g. out of 10 units produced, 7 are consumed and 3 are invested, so γ = 3/10 = 0.3. **Consumption** is the rest: (1 − γ) × Y.\n\nCapital also **depreciates** or wears out. We write the fraction of capital that wears out as **delta (δ)**; e.g. of 100 units of capital, 2 depreciate, so δ = 2/100 = 0.02. **Capital depreciation increases the greater the capital stock**, rising at a linear (constant) rate, while investment rises at a diminishing rate.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、資本は2つの力で増減します: **investment**(投資)で増え、**depreciation**(減耗)で減ります。\n\n--- 投資 ---\n• **Capital**(資本)は消費されず貯蓄・投資された産出。\n• 産出のうち投資に回る割合を **gamma (γ)** と書く(例: γ = 3/10 = 0.3)。\n• **consumption**(消費)= (1 − γ) × Y。\n\n--- 減耗 ---\n• 資本は摩耗する。摩耗する割合を **delta (δ)** と書く(例: δ = 2/100 = 0.02)。\n• depreciation は資本ストックが大きいほど大きくなり、**linear(一定)**な率で増える。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• investment は収穫逓減で『逓減的に』増える、depreciation は『線形に』増える。この差が steady state を生む。", "example": "Out of 10 units produced, consumption = (1 − 0.3) × 10 = 7 and investment = 0.3 × 10 = 3, so γ = 0.3. If there are 100 units of capital and 2 depreciate, δ = 2/100 = 0.02, leaving 98 for the next period.", "whyNeeded": "steady state を理解するための2要素。investment が逓減的、depreciation が線形に増えるという非対称性が交点(steady state)を生む。", "mistakes": ["**investment** と **depreciation** の増え方を逆にする誤り。investment は逓減、depreciation は線形。", "**gamma (γ, 投資率)** と **delta (δ, 減耗率)** の記号を取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "Investment = γY (diminishing); Depreciation = δK (linear)"}, {"id": "c28_steady_state", "ch": 28, "week": 5, "name": "Steady-State Level of Capital", "star": true, "scene": "資本が積み上がると、ある時点で『毎期の投資がちょうど減耗分を補うだけ』になる。すると資本も産出も成長を止める。その均衡点が **steady state**。", "compare": null, "punchline": "At the steady state, investment equals depreciation, so capital and output stop growing.", "defEN": "At some point, the capital stock reaches a level such that every unit of investment is needed just to replace the capital that depreciates that period. The **steady-state level of capital** is where the capital stock is neither increasing nor decreasing.\n\n- **Investment > Depreciation** → capital stock grows, output next period is bigger.\n- **Investment = Depreciation** → capital and output are constant (the **steady state**).\n- **Investment < Depreciation** → capital stock shrinks, output next period is smaller.\n\nBecause investment increases at a diminishing rate while depreciation increases at a constant rate, at some point they are equal; there is no new (net) investment and economic growth stops.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**steady state**(定常状態)は『**investment = depreciation**(投資=減耗)になって資本も産出も増えも減りもしない点』です。\n\n--- 3つのケース ---\n• Investment > Depreciation → 資本が増え、来期の産出は大きくなる。\n• Investment = Depreciation → 資本も産出も一定(**steady state**)。\n• Investment < Depreciation → 資本が減り、来期の産出は小さくなる。\n\n--- なぜ起きるか ---\n• investment は収穫逓減で逓減的に増えるが、depreciation は線形に増える。\n• だからどこかで両者が一致し、net investment がゼロになって成長が止まる。", "example": "With investment = 0.3Y and depreciation = 0.02K: at K = 100, investment > depreciation so K increases; at K = 300, investment < depreciation so K decreases; the steady-state capital stock is around K = 225, where investment = depreciation.", "whyNeeded": "単純な Solow モデルが『長期の成長率はゼロ』と予測する核心。投資率を上げれば steady-state の GDP 水準は上がるが、長期の成長率は上がらない点が頻出。", "mistakes": ["steady state を『産出がゼロの状態』と誤解する誤り。産出は一定(成長がゼロ)なだけ。", "投資率を上げれば『長期の成長率』が上がると誤解する誤り。上がるのは steady-state の『水準』であって成長率ではない。"], "memorize": "Steady state: Investment (γY) = Depreciation (δK) → growth stops"}, {"id": "c28_catching_up_vs_cutting_edge", "ch": 28, "week": 5, "name": "Catching-Up Growth vs. Cutting-Edge Growth", "star": true, "scene": "貧しい国が資本を積み上げて急成長する『追いつき型』と、すでに先端にいる国がアイデアで成長し続ける『先端型』。長期の持続的成長の源泉はどちらかを問う状況。", "compare": {"a": "Catching-Up Growth", "b": "Cutting-Edge Growth", "table": [{"dim": "Source of growth", "a": "Capital accumulation (K)", "b": "Better ideas / technology (A)"}, {"dim": "Long-run sustainability", "a": "Stops at the steady state (diminishing returns)", "b": "Can keep the economy growing even in the long run"}, {"dim": "Effect on production function", "a": "Move along Y = √K", "b": "Shifts Y = A√K upward"}, {"dim": "Model prediction", "a": "Simplest Solow model predicts zero long-run growth", "b": "New growth theory: growth from technological innovation"}]}, "punchline": "Catching-up growth from capital eventually stops; cutting-edge growth from ideas can continue forever.", "defEN": "**Catching-up growth** comes from **capital accumulation**, but long-run economic growth cannot be due to capital accumulation: diminishing returns mean that eventually capital and output cease growing at the steady state. The logic of diminishing returns applies to human capital as well.\n\nThe simplest form of the Solow model predicts **zero economic growth in the long run**, BUT modern economies have grown for more than 200 years. **Cutting-edge growth** comes from **better ideas**, which can keep the economy growing even in the long run. This is called **new growth theory**, in which growth stems from technological innovation.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**catching-up growth**(追いつき成長)は資本蓄積による成長、**cutting-edge growth**(先端成長)はアイデアによる成長です。\n\n--- catching-up growth ---\n• **capital accumulation**(資本蓄積)が源泉。\n• だが収穫逓減のため steady state で止まる。human capital にも同じ理屈が効く。\n• 最も単純な Solow モデルは『長期の成長率はゼロ』と予測する。\n\n--- cutting-edge growth ---\n• **better ideas**(より良いアイデア)が源泉。\n• 近代経済は200年以上成長し続けている → アイデアなら長期でも成長を続けられる。\n• これを **new growth theory**(新成長理論)と呼ぶ。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• 長期の持続的成長を説明できるのは catching-up ではなく cutting-edge(ideas)。", "example": "China's rapid growth is catching-up growth: it began with little capital, so the marginal product of capital was high; this growth will slow as the marginal product of capital falls. NVIDIA's development of advanced GPUs and AI chips illustrates cutting-edge growth, where innovation keeps raising productivity.", "whyNeeded": "週テストでも『長期では catching-up growth は steady state で止まる』が出題。持続的成長の源泉(ideas/A)の理解が核心。", "mistakes": ["**catching-up growth** が長期の成長を説明できると誤解する誤り。長期成長を説明するのは **cutting-edge growth**(ideas)。", "資本蓄積(catching-up)とアイデア(cutting-edge)の役割を取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "Catching-up = capital (stops); Cutting-edge = ideas (continues)"}, {"id": "c28_role_of_ideas", "ch": 28, "week": 5, "name": "Role of Ideas / Technology (A) and New Growth Theory", "star": true, "scene": "資本蓄積だけでは長期成長が止まるなら、近代経済が200年以上成長してきた理由は何か。答えは生産性を高めるアイデア(A)。production function を上にシフトさせる力を理解したい状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Ideas (A) raise productivity and shift the production function up, sustaining growth even with constant capital.", "defEN": "In **new growth theory**, growth stems from **technological innovation**. Letting **A** stand for ideas that increase productivity, the production function becomes **Y = A√K**.\n\nBetter ideas or technological knowledge—represented by increases in **A**—increase output even while holding K constant; an increase in A represents an increase in **productivity**. On the Solow diagram, better ideas shift output upward (from Output_old to Output_new), and more capital then produces more output.\n\nIdeas are **non-rivalrous**: one person's consumption of a good does not limit another person's consumption. Because of **spillovers**, ideas tend to be **underprovided**, which gives a role for patents, government subsidies, and larger market size in fostering ideas.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**A (ideas/technology)** は生産性を高めるアイデアで、production function を上にシフトさせ、資本が一定でも産出を増やします。\n\n--- モデル ---\n• production function は **Y = A√K**。\n• **A** が増える = **productivity**(生産性)が上がる → K を一定にしても Y が増える。\n• Solow 図では『better ideas』が産出曲線を上にシフト(Output_old → Output_new)。\n\n--- アイデアの性質 ---\n• **non-rivalrous**(非競合的): ある人の消費が他人の消費を妨げない。\n• **spillovers**(波及)があるため、アイデアは **underprovided**(過少供給)になりがち。\n• だから patents(特許)、政府の補助金、大きな market size がアイデア促進に役立つ。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• production function を上にシフトさせる要因は **technological advancement**(技術進歩)。資本ストックの増加は曲線上の移動にすぎない。", "example": "With Y = A√K, an increase in A shifts the whole production curve up (from Output_old to Output_new) even at constant K. An upward shift of the production function is caused by technological advancement, not by an increase in the capital stock. NVIDIA's AI chips raise total factor productivity across the economy.", "whyNeeded": "長期の持続的成長を説明できる唯一の源泉。週テストの『生産関数を上にシフトさせるのは何か』という問いの答えが technological advancement。", "mistakes": ["生産関数の上方シフトの原因を『資本ストックの増加』とする誤り。それは曲線上の移動。上方シフトは **technological advancement (A)**。", "ideas を **rivalrous**(競合的)と勘違いする誤り。ideas は **non-rivalrous**。"], "memorize": "Y = A√K; higher A shifts the curve UP (productivity)"}, {"id": "c28_investment_rate_steady_state", "ch": 28, "week": 5, "name": "Investment Rate and Steady-State GDP", "star": false, "scene": "なぜ投資率の高い国ほど豊かなのか。投資率を上げると steady-state の資本も産出も上がる。ただし上がるのは『水準』であって『長期の成長率』ではない点を区別したい状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A higher investment rate raises a country's steady-state level of GDP, but not its long-run growth rate.", "defEN": "In the Solow model, a greater **investment rate** means more capital, which means more output. This increases a country's **steady-state level of GDP**. Thus the Solow model predicts that countries with higher rates of investment will be wealthier.\n\nHowever, the level of the capital stock determines the **output level but not its growth rate**, at least not in the very long run. Increased investment raises steady-state output (e.g., shifting from Investment = 0.3Y to Investment = 0.4Y).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**investment rate**(投資率)が高いほど資本が多く、産出も多く、**steady-state の GDP 水準**が上がります。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• 投資率が高い国ほど豊か(wealthier)になる、と Solow モデルは予測する。\n• ただし資本ストックの水準が決めるのは『産出の水準』であって、(超長期の)『成長率』ではない。\n\n--- 試験で聞かれるポイント ---\n• 投資率↑ → steady-state output↑(例: 0.3Y から 0.4Y へ投資曲線が上がる)。\n• これは『水準効果』であり、長期成長率を恒久的に上げるわけではない。", "example": "Raising the investment rate from Investment = 0.3Y to Investment = 0.4Y shifts the investment curve up, so it intersects the depreciation line (δK) at a higher capital stock, raising steady-state output. Countries with higher investment rates have higher GDP per capita.", "whyNeeded": "なぜ投資率の違いが国の豊かさの差を生むかを説明。『水準』と『成長率』への効果を区別する点が試験で問われる。", "mistakes": ["投資率を上げれば『長期の成長率』が恒久的に上がると誤解する誤り。上がるのは steady-state の『水準』。", "saving / investment rate を上げると長期成長が下がると勘違いする誤り(Solow の予測は逆)。"], "memorize": "Higher investment rate → higher steady-state LEVEL (not growth rate)"}, {"id": "c30_aggregate_demand_curve", "ch": 30, "week": 6, "name": "Aggregate Demand Curve", "star": true, "scene": "支出の伸び **M + v** が5%に固定されているとき、インフレ率と実質成長率の組み合わせはどうなるかを考える状況。**aggregate demand curve**(総需要曲線)はその全組み合わせを示す。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The aggregate demand curve shows all combinations of inflation and real growth consistent with a specified rate of spending growth, M + v.", "defEN": "The **aggregate demand curve** shows all the combinations of **inflation** and **real growth** that are consistent with a specified rate of spending growth, **M + v**. It is derived from the quantity theory of money in dynamic form: **M + v = P + YR**. Because the spending total M + v is fixed along a single AD curve, higher real growth implies lower inflation and vice versa, so the curve slopes **downward**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**aggregate demand curve**(総需要曲線)は『支出の伸び **M + v** を一定にしたときの、インフレ率と実質成長率のあらゆる組み合わせ』です。\n\n--- 導出 ---\n動学版の貨幣数量説 **M + v = P + YR** から導く。\n• **M** = マネーサプライの成長率\n• **v** = 流通速度(velocity)の成長率\n• **P** = 物価の成長率(インフレ率)\n• **YR** = 実質GDPの成長率\n\n--- ポイント ---\nM + v が一定なので、実質成長が上がればインフレは下がる → 右下がりの曲線。例: M + v = 5% なら、実質成長2.5% のときインフレは 2.5%。", "example": "If money growth plus velocity growth = 5%, and real growth = 2.5%, then inflation = 5% - 2.5% = 2.5%. Another point on the same AD curve: real growth = 5% gives inflation = 0%.", "whyNeeded": "**inflation**(インフレ)を理解し、経済政策を比較し、長期の価格安定をモデル化するために不可欠。試験では **M + v = P + YR** を使った計算と、AD曲線上の点の読み取りが頻出。", "mistakes": ["**AD curve**(右下がり)と **SRAS curve**(右上がり)を取り違える誤り。", "AD曲線『上の移動(shift along)』と曲線『自体のシフト(shift of)』を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "AD: M + v = P + YR (spending fixed, so P up <=> YR down)"}, {"id": "c30_dynamic_quantity_theory_ad", "ch": 30, "week": 6, "name": "Dynamic Quantity Theory (M + v = P + YR)", "star": true, "scene": "貨幣数量説 **Mv = PYR** を成長率(伸び)の形に書き直すと、足し算の式 **M + v = P + YR** になる状況。これが AD 曲線の基礎になる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "In dynamic form the quantity theory becomes M + v = P + YR, treated as an always-true identity in this model.", "defEN": "The dynamic form of the quantity theory of money is **M + v = P + YR**, where **M** is the growth rate of the money supply, **v** is the growth in velocity, **P** is the growth rate of prices (**inflation**), and **YR** is the growth rate of real GDP. In this course the quantity theory is treated as an **identity**: it is always true in our toy-model world. It can also be written as **M + v = Inflation + Real Growth**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、水準の式 **Mv = PYR** を『成長率(変化率)』に直すと、掛け算が足し算になって **M + v = P + YR** になります。\n\n--- 式の読み方 ---\n• **M + v** = 支出の伸び(spending growth)\n• **P + YR** = インフレ + 実質成長\n\nこの講義では数量説を **identity**(恒等式=常に成立)として扱います。だから『M + v = Inflation + Real Growth』と書き換え可能。", "example": "If M + v = 10% and real growth YR = 3%, then inflation P = 10% - 3% = 7%.", "whyNeeded": "この式が AD 曲線・LRAS 均衡・潜在成長率の計算すべての土台。試験では『M + v が分かっていて成長率を与えられ、インフレを求める』タイプが頻出。", "mistakes": ["水準の式 **Mv = PYR**(掛け算)と成長率の式 **M + v = P + YR**(足し算)を混同する誤り。", "**v**(velocity の伸び)を物価 P と取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "Levels multiply (Mv=PY); growth rates ADD (M+v=P+YR)"}, {"id": "c30_lras_solow_growth_rate", "ch": 30, "week": 6, "name": "Long-Run Aggregate Supply (LRAS)", "star": true, "scene": "長期では貨幣は中立(**money is neutral**)で、M を増やしても物価が上がるだけで実質GDPは増えない状況。**LRAS** は **Solow growth rate** の所に立つ垂直線になる。", "compare": {"a": "SRAS (Short Run)", "b": "LRAS (Long Run)", "table": [{"dim": "Slope", "a": "Upward sloping", "b": "Vertical"}, {"dim": "Is money neutral?", "a": "No (money is not neutral)", "b": "Yes (money is neutral)"}, {"dim": "Why", "a": "Wages and prices are sticky", "b": "Prices and wages fully adjust"}, {"dim": "AD shock affects", "a": "Both inflation and real growth", "b": "Only inflation"}, {"dim": "Located at", "a": "Expected inflation E(pi)", "b": "Solow growth rate"}]}, "punchline": "The long-run aggregate supply curve is a vertical line at the Solow growth rate, independent of the inflation rate.", "defEN": "The **long-run aggregate supply curve (LRAS)** is a vertical line at the **Solow growth rate**, independent of the inflation rate. It is vertical for two reasons: (1) **QTM** says money is neutral in the long run, so increases in M only raise P, not Y; and (2) the **Solow model** says the causes of growth (accumulation of labor and physical capital, and technological change) are unrelated to the rate of inflation. LRAS represents **potential output** or **full-employment output**: the maximum sustainable real GDP when all resources are fully employed and prices and wages have fully adjusted.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**LRAS**(長期総供給曲線)は **Solow growth rate** の所に立つ『垂直線』です。インフレ率がいくらでも、長期の成長率は変わりません。\n\n--- なぜ垂直? ---\n• **QTM**: 長期では **money is neutral**(貨幣は中立)。M を増やしても P が上がるだけで Y は増えない。\n• **Solow model**: 成長の原因(労働・資本の蓄積、技術進歩)はインフレ率と無関係。\n\n--- LRAS が表すもの ---\n**potential output**(潜在産出 / 完全雇用産出)。全資源がフル稼働し、賃金・物価が完全に調整された状態の最大持続産出。", "example": "If the Solow growth rate is 3%, the LRAS is a vertical line at 3% real growth. Whether inflation is 2% or 7%, long-run real growth stays at 3%.", "whyNeeded": "AD と LRAS の交点で長期の均衡インフレ率と成長率が決まる。試験では『real shock が LRAS をシフトさせる』『money neutrality で M 増は P だけ上げる』が頻出。", "mistakes": ["**LRAS**(垂直)を **SRAS**(右上がり)と取り違える誤り。", "長期で M を増やせば実質成長が上がると思う誤り。実際は **money neutrality** でインフレだけ上がる。"], "memorize": "LRAS = vertical at Solow rate; long run money is NEUTRAL"}, {"id": "c30_solow_growth_rate", "ch": 30, "week": 6, "name": "Solow Growth Rate", "star": false, "scene": "物価が伸縮的で、既存の生産要素(資本・労働)が与えられたときに実現する経済の成長率を考える状況。それが **Solow growth rate**。", "compare": {"a": "Solow Growth Model", "b": "LRAS Curve", "table": [{"dim": "What it shows", "a": "How potential output changes over time", "b": "The level of potential output at a point in time"}, {"dim": "Determined by", "a": "Growth in K, L, A", "b": "Current K, L, A"}, {"dim": "Key implication", "a": "Explains why LRAS shifts", "b": "Shows where the economy produces in the long run"}]}, "punchline": "The Solow growth rate is the economy's growth rate that would occur given flexible prices and the existing real factors of production.", "defEN": "The **Solow growth rate** is an economy's growth rate: the rate of economic growth that would occur given **flexible prices** and the existing real factors of production. The **Solow Growth Model** explains how potential output grows over time through changes in **capital accumulation**, **labour growth**, and **technological progress**, which determine the steady-state level of output per worker. In the steady state, investment and depreciation offset, so the growth rate is driven by productivity and ideas.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**Solow growth rate** は『物価が伸縮的で、今ある資本・労働などの実質要因が与えられたときに実現する経済の成長率』です。\n\n--- Solow Growth Model が説明するもの ---\n潜在産出が時間とともにどう成長するか。決める要因は:\n• **capital accumulation**(資本蓄積)\n• **labour growth**(労働の伸び)\n• **technological progress**(技術進歩)\nこれらが労働者1人あたり産出の steady-state(定常状態)水準を決める。", "example": "If the past 60 years show real GDP growing at an average of 2-3% per year, that average trend rate is the Solow growth rate around which actual growth fluctuates.", "whyNeeded": "LRAS の位置を決めるのが Solow growth rate。**business fluctuations** は実際の成長がこのトレンド率の周りで揺れること。試験では LRAS と結びつけて問われる。", "mistakes": ["**Solow growth model**(時間を通じた変化を説明)と **LRAS curve**(ある時点の水準)を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Solow rate = trend growth from K, L, A under flexible prices"}, {"id": "c30_money_neutrality", "ch": 30, "week": 6, "name": "Money Neutrality", "star": true, "scene": "長期にマネーサプライ M を増やしたとき、実質GDPは増えず物価だけが上がる状況。これが **money neutrality**(貨幣の中立性)。", "compare": null, "punchline": "In the long run money is neutral: an increase in M only leads to higher inflation, not higher real output.", "defEN": "**Money is neutral** in the long run: an increase in the money supply **M** only leads to higher **inflation (P)**, not to higher real output **(Y)**. This is why the LRAS curve is vertical. The quantity theory also implies that the growth rate of the money supply will be approximately equal to the inflation rate, because money is neutral in the long run. Money is **not** neutral in the short run, because wages and prices are sticky ('you can be fouled once, but...').", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**money neutrality**(貨幣の中立性)は『長期では M を増やしても物価が上がるだけで、実質GDPは増えない』ことです。\n\n--- 帰結 ---\n• LRAS が垂直になる理由。\n• 数量説より、マネーサプライの成長率 ≒ インフレ率(長期)。\n\n--- 注意 ---\n短期では **money is NOT neutral**。賃金・物価が **sticky**(粘着的)だから(『一度はだまされる』)。週テストでも『money is neutral only in the long run』が正解として出た。", "example": "In the long run, if money growth rises by 10 percentage points, the inflation rate rises by about 10 percentage points, with no lasting change in real GDP growth.", "whyNeeded": "long-run price stability とインフレの原因を理解する核心。週テスト Q2 で『money is neutral only in the long run』が正答。短期と長期の区別が頻出。", "mistakes": ["『short run でも貨幣は中立』と思う誤り。中立は **long run のみ**。", "**neutrality**(実質に影響なし)と **velocity** の概念を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Long run: M up -> P up only (neutral); Short run: M up -> Y up too"}, {"id": "c30_real_shock_lras_shift", "ch": 30, "week": 6, "name": "Real (Supply) Shock", "star": true, "scene": "新技術・戦争・石油供給の変化など、資本・労働の生産性やアイデアの流れを大きく変える出来事が起きる状況。これが **real shock** で **LRAS** をシフトさせる。", "compare": {"a": "Real (Supply) Shock", "b": "Aggregate Demand Shock", "table": [{"dim": "Shifts which curve", "a": "LRAS (and we move along AD)", "b": "AD curve"}, {"dim": "Duration of impact", "a": "Lasting impact", "b": "Short-term impact on GDP, lasting on prices"}, {"dim": "Positive shock effect", "a": "Higher real growth, lower inflation", "b": "Higher inflation and/or higher real growth (short run)"}, {"dim": "Negative shock effect", "a": "Lower real growth, higher inflation (stagflation)", "b": "Recession, then return to Solow rate"}, {"dim": "Examples", "a": "New technology, war, oil supply fall", "b": "Change in M (permanent), change in v (temporary)"}]}, "punchline": "Real shocks shift the LRAS curve; we move along the AD curve, changing both inflation and growth.", "defEN": "**Real shocks** are rapid changes in economic conditions that increase or diminish the productivity of capital and labor or the flow of ideas. Examples: wars, terrorist attacks, new regulations, tax rate changes, mass strikes, new technologies. A **positive real shock** (e.g. new technology) raises the real growth rate and lowers inflation. A **negative real shock** (e.g. war, an oil supply fall like the 1973 OPEC shock) lowers the real growth rate and raises inflation. Real shocks **shift the LRAS curve**, but we move along the AD curve with changing inflation and growth rates.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**real shock**(実質/供給ショック)は『資本・労働の生産性やアイデアの流れを急に変える出来事』です。\n\n--- 例 ---\n戦争、テロ、新規制、税率変更、大規模ストライキ、新技術、石油供給の減少(1973年の第一次OPECショックで原油価格が2年で3倍超)。\n\n--- 効果 ---\n• **positive shock**(新技術): 成長↑・インフレ↓\n• **negative shock**(戦争・石油不足): 成長↓・インフレ↑ → **stagflation**\nLRAS をシフトさせ、AD 曲線上を移動する。", "example": "A negative real shock (war reducing oil supply) shifts LRAS left: real growth falls (e.g. from 3% to -1%) and inflation rises (e.g. from 7% to 11%). This combination of recession plus high inflation is stagflation.", "whyNeeded": "business fluctuations が real shock で起きる仕組みを理解するため。演習 Ch32 Q7 で『**stagflation** を引き起こすのは negative real shock』が正答。", "mistakes": ["**real shock**(LRAS をシフト)と **AD shock**(AD をシフト)を取り違える誤り。", "positive real shock がインフレを上げると思う誤り。実際は **下げる**。"], "memorize": "Real shock -> shifts LRAS; positive: growth up/inflation down; negative: stagflation"}, {"id": "c30_short_run_aggregate_supply", "ch": 30, "week": 6, "name": "Short-Run Aggregate Supply (SRAS)", "star": true, "scene": "短期では賃金や一部の投入価格が **sticky**(粘着的)で、物価が上がると企業の収入がコストより速く増え、生産を増やす状況。だから **SRAS** は右上がり。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The SRAS curve is upward sloping because in the short run nominal wages and some prices are sticky, so money is not neutral.", "defEN": "The **short-run aggregate supply curve (SRAS)** shows how much output firms are willing to produce in the short run at different price levels. It is **upward sloping** because, in the short run, nominal wages and some input prices are **sticky** (they don't adjust immediately when the price level changes). When the general price level rises, firms' revenues increase faster than their costs, so they increase production. Each SRAS curve is associated with a particular rate of **expected inflation E(pi)**. Three reasons for short-run rigidity: **sticky wages**, **sticky prices (menu costs)**, and the **misperception theory**. Once wages and prices fully adjust, the economy returns to the vertical LRAS.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**SRAS**(短期総供給曲線)は『短期に企業がどれだけ生産するか』を示し、**右上がり**です。\n\n--- なぜ右上がり? ---\n短期は賃金や一部投入価格が **sticky**(粘着的)。物価が上がっても賃金が据え置きだと、企業の実質労働コストが下がり、増産が儲かる。\n\n--- 3つの理由 ---\n• **sticky wages**(粘着賃金): 契約・慣習で賃金が固定\n• **sticky prices / menu costs**(メニューコスト): 値札変更が面倒\n• **misperception theory**(誤認理論): 全体の物価上昇を自社製品の相対価格上昇と誤認\n\n各 SRAS は予想インフレ **E(pi)** に対応。賃金・物価が完全調整すれば LRAS に戻る。", "example": "If prices rise by 5% but wages stay the same for a few months, firms sell goods at higher prices without paying higher wages, so they produce more. This is why a positive AD shock raises both inflation and real growth in the short run (point a to b).", "whyNeeded": "短期で AD ショックがインフレと実質成長の両方を動かす理由を説明する。演習 Ch32 Q2 で『SRAS の定義(II)は誤り』、Q6 で『実際のインフレが予想を上回ると成長は Solow 率より高くなる』が正答。", "mistakes": ["**SRAS**(右上がり、E(pi) ごと)と **AD**(右下がり、M+v ごと)を混同する誤り。", "Ch32 Q2: 『spending growth の組み合わせ=SRAS』は誤り。それは **AD** の定義。"], "memorize": "SRAS up-sloping: sticky wages, menu costs, misperception; one per E(pi)"}, {"id": "c30_ad_shock", "ch": 30, "week": 6, "name": "Aggregate Demand Shock", "star": true, "scene": "予想外に M が増える(または v が変わる)ことで AD 曲線が外側にシフトし、短期にインフレと実質成長が両方上がる状況。長期には成長は Solow 率に戻る。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A positive AD shock raises both inflation and real growth in the short run, but in the long run raises only inflation.", "defEN": "An **aggregate demand shock** shifts the AD curve. A **positive AD shock** (outward shift, from higher M and/or v) increases inflation and/or the real growth rate. In the short run, the increase in spending is split between higher inflation and higher real growth (because SRAS is upward sloping; point a to b). In the long run, the real growth rate returns to the **Solow rate** because money is neutral, so the shock ends up increasing **only the inflation rate** (point b to c, as expected inflation adjusts). A **negative AD shock** (e.g. a fall in money growth) can induce a lengthy recession because prices and wages are especially sticky downward, before the economy reaches a new long-run equilibrium.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**AD shock**(総需要ショック)は AD 曲線を動かすショックです。\n\n--- positive AD shock(M や v の増加で外側シフト) ---\n1. 短期: 支出増がインフレ増と実質成長増に『分かれる』(SRAS 右上がりのため; a→b)\n2. 長期: 成長率は **Solow rate** に戻る(money neutrality)\n3. 結局: インフレ率だけが上がる(b→c, 予想インフレが調整)\n\n--- negative AD shock(M の伸び低下など) ---\n下方向は特に賃金・物価が sticky なので、長く続く **recession**(不況)を招きうる。やがて賃金が unstuck になり新均衡へ。", "example": "An unexpected rise in M shifting AD from (M+v=5%) to (M+v=10%): short run, both inflation and growth rise (a to b, growth 3% to 6%); long run, growth returns to 3% and inflation rises to 7% (b to c).", "whyNeeded": "金融政策の効果と recession を理解する核心。演習 Ch32 Q5 で『M 成長率の予想外の低下は AD を左にシフト→その後 SRAS を右にシフト』が正答。", "mistakes": ["positive AD shock が長期に実質成長を恒久的に上げると思う誤り。長期は **インフレだけ**。", "AD shock(temporary な v 変化と permanent な M 変化)の持続性を取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "Positive AD shock: short run both up; long run inflation only (Solow rate)"}, {"id": "c31_quantity_theory_of_money", "ch": 31, "week": 6, "name": "Quantity Theory of Money (Mv = PYR)", "star": true, "scene": "総支出 **Mv** が、物価×実質GDP **PYR** に等しいという関係を考える状況。実質GDPと流通速度がほぼ一定なら、M を増やすと P が上がる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The quantity theory of money states Mv = PYR; with v and Y fixed, an increase in M must cause an increase in P.", "defEN": "The **quantity theory of money** states **Mv = PYR**, where **M** = money supply, **v** = velocity of money, **P** = price level, and **YR** = real GDP. **Mv** is the total amount spent on final goods and services; **PYR** is the price level times real GDP. The assumptions hold because real GDP is fixed in the steady state by the Solow model, and **v** changes only slowly. The key consequence: increases in **M** must cause increases in **P**. In other words, inflation is caused by an increase in the supply of money. The growth rate of the money supply will be approximately equal to the inflation rate, because money is neutral in the long run.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**quantity theory of money**(貨幣数量説)は **Mv = PYR** という関係式です。\n\n--- 各記号 ---\n• **M** = マネーサプライ、**v** = 流通速度\n• **P** = 物価水準、**YR** = 実質GDP\n• **Mv** = 最終財・サービスへの総支出\n• **PYR** = 物価 × 実質GDP\n\n--- なぜ成り立つ? ---\n実質GDP は Solow model で steady state に固定、**v** はゆっくりしか変わらない。\n\n--- 帰結 ---\nM が増えれば P が増える。つまり『インフレは貨幣供給の増加が原因』(Friedman: 'Inflation is always and everywhere a monetary phenomenon')。", "example": "In a small economy, money = $2.5 million, real GDP = $5 million, price level = 2. Velocity v = PY/M = (2 x 5)/2.5 = 10/2.5 = 4.", "whyNeeded": "インフレの原因と AD 曲線の土台。演習 Ch31 Q6 で v = PY/M = 4 を計算、Q10 で P = Mv/Y を埋める問題が出る。", "mistakes": ["**v = PY/M** の式変形を間違える誤り(M で割るのを忘れる等)。", "**P**(物価水準)と **inflation**(物価の成長率)を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Mv = PYR; so v = PY/M and P = Mv/Y"}, {"id": "c31_inflation_monetary", "ch": 31, "week": 6, "name": "Inflation", "star": true, "scene": "マネーサプライが急速に伸びる国は高インフレ、ゆっくり伸びる国は低インフレという関係がほぼ完全に直線になる状況。インフレは貨幣現象。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Inflation is always and everywhere a monetary phenomenon: in the long run inflation is caused by money supply growth.", "defEN": "**Inflation** is an increase in the price level over time; **P** in the quantity theory is the growth rate of prices. In this model, inflation is caused by an increase in the supply of money. Nations with rapidly growing money supplies had high inflation rates; nations with slowly growing money supplies had low inflation rates. The relationship is almost perfectly linear: a 10 percentage point increase in the money growth rate leads to a 10 percentage point increase in the inflation rate. An unexpected increase in the money supply can boost the economy in the short run (SRAS is upward sloping), but in the long run money is neutral and output grows no faster than normal.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**inflation**(インフレ)は『物価が時間とともに上がること』で、数量説の **P** は物価の成長率です。\n\n--- 原因 ---\nこのモデルでは『マネーサプライの増加』。マネーが速く伸びる国は高インフレ、遅い国は低インフレ。関係はほぼ完全に直線で、マネー成長率が10%ポイント上がるとインフレ率も約10%ポイント上がる。\n\n--- 短期 vs 長期 ---\n予想外の M 増は短期に景気を押し上げる(SRAS 右上がり)が、長期は **money neutral** で通常の成長率に戻る。", "example": "If money growth rises by 10 percentage points, inflation rises by about 10 percentage points (an almost perfectly linear relationship).", "whyNeeded": "Cost of inflation、Fisher 効果、金融政策の理解の前提。演習 Ch31 のインフレ率計算(CPI 表)で頻出。", "mistakes": ["短期の M 増が長期に実質GDPを押し上げ続けると思う誤り。長期は **neutral**。", "**inflation**(物価の伸び)と **price level P**(物価の水準)を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Inflation = monetary phenomenon; 10pp money growth -> ~10pp inflation"}, {"id": "c31_cpi_inflation_disinflation", "ch": 31, "week": 6, "name": "CPI, Inflation Rate & Disinflation", "star": true, "scene": "消費者物価指数 **CPI** の表からインフレ率を計算し、インフレ率が下がった(まだプラスだが鈍化した)年を探す状況。それが **disinflation**。", "compare": {"a": "Disinflation", "b": "Deflation", "table": [{"dim": "What happens", "a": "Inflation rate falls but stays positive", "b": "Price level actually falls (negative inflation)"}, {"dim": "Sign of inflation rate", "a": "Still positive (e.g. 5% then 3%)", "b": "Negative"}, {"dim": "Prices", "a": "Still rising, but slower", "b": "Falling"}]}, "punchline": "The inflation rate is the percentage change in the CPI; disinflation is a fall in the inflation rate that remains positive.", "defEN": "The **Consumer Price Index (CPI)** measures the average price level. The **inflation rate** between two years is the percentage change in the CPI: (CPI_new - CPI_old) / CPI_old x 100. A **real price** is a price that has been corrected for inflation. **Disinflation** occurs when the inflation rate falls but remains positive (prices still rise, just more slowly). This is different from **deflation**, where the price level actually falls.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**CPI**(消費者物価指数)は平均的な物価水準を測る指標です。\n\n--- インフレ率の計算 ---\n2年間の **inflation rate** = (新CPI − 旧CPI) ÷ 旧CPI × 100\n\n--- 用語の区別 ---\n• **real price**(実質価格): インフレ調整済みの価格\n• **disinflation**(ディスインフレ): インフレ率が下がるが **まだプラス**(物価は上がり続けるがペースが鈍化)\n• **deflation**(デフレ): 物価水準が実際に **下がる**(インフレ率がマイナス)", "example": "Refer to a CPI table for 2005-2010: the approximate inflation rate over 2007 to 2008 is about 3.86% (answer c). Disinflation occurred in both 2007 and 2009 (the inflation rate fell but stayed positive).", "whyNeeded": "インフレを数値で測り、政策議論の土台にするため。演習 Ch31 Q4(インフレ率 3.86%)、Q5(disinflation は 2007 と 2009 両方)で頻出。", "mistakes": ["**disinflation**(インフレ率↓だが正)と **deflation**(物価が下落=負のインフレ)を混同する誤り。", "**real price**(インフレ調整済み価格)を velocity の定義と取り違える誤り(Ch31 Q3)。"], "memorize": "Disinflation = inflation slows but stays +; deflation = prices fall (-)"}, {"id": "c31_real_vs_nominal_interest", "ch": 31, "week": 6, "name": "Real vs Nominal Interest Rate", "star": true, "scene": "貸し手の実質収益は、名目利子率からインフレ率を引いたものになる状況。インフレと利子率が予想外に上がると、富が借り手から貸し手へ(または逆へ)再分配される。", "compare": {"a": "Nominal Interest Rate (i)", "b": "Real Interest Rate (rreal)", "table": [{"dim": "Definition", "a": "Stated rate of return", "b": "Return corrected for inflation"}, {"dim": "Formula", "a": "i = rreal + pi", "b": "rreal = i - pi"}, {"dim": "Adjusts for inflation?", "a": "No", "b": "Yes"}, {"dim": "Unexpected inflation rises", "a": "Fixed (already set)", "b": "Falls (lenders lose)"}]}, "punchline": "The real rate of return equals the nominal rate minus the inflation rate: rreal = i - pi.", "defEN": "The relationship between the lender's **real rate of return (rreal)**, the **nominal rate of return (i)**, and the **inflation rate (pi)** is **rreal = i - pi**. The real rate of return equals the nominal rate of return minus the inflation rate. In the short run, inflation reduces the real return lenders receive, transferring wealth from **lenders to borrowers**. When inflation and interest rates rise **unexpectedly**, wealth is redistributed from **borrowers** (paying higher rates) to **lenders**. This is one channel by which inflation redistributes wealth.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**real interest rate**(実質利子率)は名目からインフレを引いたものです。\n\n--- 関係式 ---\n**rreal = i − pi**\n• **rreal** = 実質収益率\n• **i** = 名目利子率\n• **pi** = インフレ率\n\n--- 富の再分配 ---\n• 短期に予想外のインフレ → 貸し手の実質収益↓ → 富が **lender → borrower**(貸し手から借り手)へ移転\n• インフレと利子率が予想外に上がると → 富が **borrower → lender** へ\n(政府は巨額債務があると、予想外インフレで債務を目減りさせる誘因を持つ)", "example": "If the nominal interest rate i = 7% and inflation pi = 4%, then the real rate of return rreal = 7% - 4% = 3%.", "whyNeeded": "インフレによる富の再分配と Fisher 効果を理解する核心。Fisher 計算(i, E(pi), r のうち2つから3つ目)で頻出。", "mistakes": ["**rreal = i - pi** の符号を逆にする誤り。", "**nominal**(名目=未調整)と **real**(実質=インフレ調整済み)を取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "rreal = i - pi (real = nominal minus inflation)"}, {"id": "c31_fisher_effect", "ch": 31, "week": 6, "name": "Fisher Effect", "star": true, "scene": "貸し手がインフレ上昇を予想すると、より高い名目利子率を要求する状況。名目利子率は予想インフレ率＋均衡実質利子率に等しい。これが **Fisher effect**。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The Fisher effect: the nominal interest rate equals expected inflation plus the equilibrium real rate, i = E(pi) + r_equilibrium.", "defEN": "The **Fisher effect** is the tendency of **nominal interest rates** to rise with **expected inflation** rates. When lenders expect inflation to increase, they demand a higher nominal interest rate. The Fisher effect says the nominal interest rate equals the expected inflation rate plus the equilibrium real interest rate: **i = E(pi) + r_equilibrium**, where i = nominal rate of interest, E(pi) = expected rate of inflation, and r_equilibrium = equilibrium real rate of return. Because there are three items, if any two are known the third can be calculated. The 'Friedman rule' is a special case used in a later chapter.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**Fisher effect**(フィッシャー効果)は『名目利子率は予想インフレ率に応じて上がる傾向』です。\n\n--- 式 ---\n**i = E(pi) + r_equilibrium**\n• **i** = 名目利子率\n• **E(pi)** = 予想インフレ率\n• **r_equilibrium** = 均衡実質利子率\n\n--- 使い方 ---\n3つの項のうち **2つが分かれば3つ目を計算**できる。エコノミストはこれを使って、観測しにくい予想インフレや均衡実質利子率を推定する。最後の例は『Friedman rule』(後の章で扱う)。", "example": "If expected inflation E(pi) = 3% and the equilibrium real rate r_equilibrium = 2%, then the nominal interest rate i = 3% + 2% = 5%. Conversely, if i = 5% and E(pi) = 3%, then r_equilibrium = 5% - 3% = 2%.", "whyNeeded": "観測困難な経済変数(予想インフレ・均衡実質利子率)を推定する実務ツール。演習 Ch31 Q16/Q26 で『2つから3つ目を求める』計算が頻出。", "mistakes": ["**Fisher effect**(i = E(pi) + r)と単なる実質利子率の式(rreal = i - pi)を混同する誤り。前者は **予想インフレ**、後者は **実現インフレ**。", "i, E(pi), r のどれを求めるか取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "Fisher: i = E(pi) + r_equilibrium (nominal = expected inflation + real)"}, {"id": "c31_costs_of_inflation", "ch": 31, "week": 6, "name": "Costs of Inflation", "star": false, "scene": "インフレが価格シグナルを読みにくくし、富を再分配し、他の税と相互作用し、止めるのが苦痛、という4つの問題を考える状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Inflation has four costs: price confusion, wealth redistribution, interaction with taxes, and being painful to stop.", "defEN": "There are four problems associated with inflation: (1) **Price confusion and money illusion** - inflation makes price signals harder to interpret, so resources are wasted in activities that appear profitable but are not; (2) **Inflation redistributes wealth** - between lenders and borrowers via real interest rates; (3) **Inflation interacts with other taxes**; (4) **Inflation is painful to stop** - the tools used to reduce it (raising interest rates or cutting government spending) slow the entire economy, not just prices. Disinflation often works with a lag of 12-24 months, so 'the medicine hurts as much as the disease' and short-term pain precedes long-term gains.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、インフレには4つのコストがあります。\n\n1. **Price confusion and money illusion**(価格混乱・貨幣錯覚): 価格シグナルが読みにくくなり、儲かるように見えて実は儲からない活動に資源が浪費される。\n2. **Inflation redistributes wealth**(富の再分配): 実質利子率を通じて貸し手⇔借り手で。\n3. **Inflation interacts with other taxes**(他の税との相互作用)。\n4. **Inflation is painful to stop**(止めるのが苦痛): 利上げや歳出削減は物価だけでなく経済全体を冷やす。効果は12〜24か月のラグ。『medicine hurts as much as the disease』。", "example": "After inflation surged in 2021-2022 in Europe, the ECB raised its policy rate sharply in ten steps between summer 2022 and September 2023; growth slowed and the pain was felt before inflation fully cooled (a 12-24 month lag).", "whyNeeded": "なぜインフレが望ましくなく、止めるのに不況リスクが伴うかを理解するため。disinflation の現実的コストの理解に直結。", "mistakes": ["『インフレを止めるのは簡単』と思う誤り。実際は **painful to stop**(ラグと景気後退を伴う)。", "**price confusion**(シグナル混乱)と単なる **redistribution**(再分配)を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "4 costs: confusion, redistribution, taxes, painful-to-stop"}, {"id": "c32_unemployment_rate", "ch": 32, "week": 6, "name": "Unemployment Rate", "star": true, "scene": "労働力(働いている人＋仕事を探している失業者)のうち、失業者が占める割合を計算する状況。求職をあきらめた人や学生・退職者は労働力に含まれない。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The unemployment rate is the number of unemployed divided by the labor force (employed plus those looking for work).", "defEN": "The **labor force** consists of **employed workers and adults who do not have jobs but who are looking for work**. The **unemployment rate** is the number of unemployed divided by the labor force, times 100. People who are not looking for work (homemakers, full-time students, retirees, and those who have **given up looking** - discouraged workers) are **not** in the labor force. **Underemployed** workers (e.g. part-timers who want full-time work) are counted as **employed**, so an increase in underemployment does **not** raise the unemployment rate.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**unemployment rate**(失業率)は『労働力のうち失業者が占める割合』です。\n\n--- 計算 ---\n失業率 = 失業者 ÷ **labor force**(労働力)× 100\n**labor force** = 就業者 + 仕事を探している成人\n\n--- 労働力に含まれない人 ---\n専業主婦/主夫、フルタイム学生、退職者、**求職をあきらめた人(discouraged workers)**。\n\n--- 注意 ---\n**underemployed**(フルタイム希望のパート等)は『**employed**』に数える。だから underemployment が増えても失業率は上がらない(演習 Ch32 Q7 で False が正答)。", "example": "Adult population 200 million, 100 million employed, 10 million unemployed. Labor force = 100 + 10 = 110 million. Unemployment rate = 10 / 110 = 9.1% (Weekly Test 6, answer B).", "whyNeeded": "労働市場の健全性を測る基本指標。週テスト Q1(9.1%)、演習 Ch32 Q4(25%)、Q6($10 最低賃金で 50%)など計算が頻出。", "mistakes": ["分母を **adult population**(成人人口)にしてしまう誤り。正しくは **labor force**。", "**discouraged workers**(求職放棄者)を失業者に数える誤り。彼らは労働力に **含まれない**。", "**underemployed** を失業に数える誤り。彼らは employed。"], "memorize": "U-rate = unemployed / (employed + job-seekers); discouraged & students OUT"}, {"id": "c32_labor_force_participation", "ch": 32, "week": 6, "name": "Labor Force & Participation", "star": true, "scene": "成人人口のうち、誰が労働力に入り誰が入らないかを区別する状況。求職中の人は労働力だが、専業主婦・学生・退職者・求職放棄者は入らない。", "compare": {"a": "In the Labor Force", "b": "NOT in the Labor Force", "table": [{"dim": "Employed full-time", "a": "Yes", "b": "-"}, {"dim": "Underemployed (part-time wanting full)", "a": "Yes (counted as employed)", "b": "-"}, {"dim": "Laid off and looking for work", "a": "Yes (unemployed)", "b": "-"}, {"dim": "Given up looking (discouraged)", "a": "-", "b": "Yes (out)"}, {"dim": "Homemaker / full-time student / retiree", "a": "-", "b": "Yes (out)"}]}, "punchline": "The labor force is employed workers plus adults without jobs who are looking for work; everyone else is out.", "defEN": "The **labor force** consists of **employed workers and adults who do not have jobs but who are looking for work**. A person who was laid off and is now looking for work **is** part of the labor force. A **homemaker**, a **full-time student**, and a **retiree** are **not** part of the labor force. Adults who are interested in working but have **given up looking** (discouraged workers) are also out of the labor force, which is why they are excluded when computing the unemployment rate.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**labor force**(労働力)は『就業者 + 仕事を探している成人(失業者)』です。\n\n--- 含まれる ---\n• フルタイム就業者\n• **underemployed**(フルタイム希望のパート→ employed 扱い)\n• 解雇され求職中の人(=失業者)\n\n--- 含まれない ---\n• 専業主婦/主夫(homemaker)\n• フルタイム学生(full-time student)\n• 退職者(retiree)\n• **求職をあきらめた人(discouraged / given up looking)**\n\n演習 Ch32 Q3・Q5 で『労働力=就業者＋求職中の成人』『laid off で求職中の人は労働力』が正答。", "example": "Of 30 million adults: 5M not interested in working (out), 5M gave up looking (out), 5M still looking (unemployed), 5M part-time wanting full-time (employed), 10M full-time (employed). Labor force = 5 + 5 + 10 = 20M; unemployment rate = 5 / 20 = 25% (Ch32 Q4, answer c).", "whyNeeded": "失業率の分母を正しく決めるために必須。誰が労働力に入るかの判定が計算問題の前提として頻出。", "mistakes": ["**discouraged workers**(あきらめた人)を労働力に入れる誤り。入らない。", "**full-time student** や **homemaker** を労働力に数える誤り。入らない。"], "memorize": "Labor force = employed + actively looking; gave-up/students/retirees OUT"}, {"id": "c32_types_of_unemployment", "ch": 32, "week": 6, "name": "Frictional, Structural & Cyclical Unemployment", "star": true, "scene": "失業を、転職に伴う一時的なもの(frictional)、産業構造の変化によるもの(structural)、景気後退によるもの(cyclical)に分類する状況。", "compare": {"a": "Frictional / Structural / Cyclical", "b": "Cause", "table": [{"dim": "Frictional", "a": "Short-term job search (moving, switching jobs)", "b": "Normal job-matching process"}, {"dim": "Structural", "a": "Skills/industry mismatch (e.g. replaced by robots)", "b": "Changes in industry structure or technology"}, {"dim": "Cyclical", "a": "Driven by the business cycle / recessions", "b": "Bad aggregate demand, downturns"}]}, "punchline": "Frictional = job search; structural = skills/industry mismatch; cyclical = caused by recessions.", "defEN": "Unemployment is classified into three types. **Frictional unemployment** arises from the normal short-term process of searching for a job (e.g. workers who quit to move to another town and search for work there). **Structural unemployment** arises from a mismatch between workers' skills and available jobs, often due to changes in industry or technology (e.g. workers laid off and replaced by robots who must look for jobs outside their industry). **Cyclical unemployment** is caused by the business cycle - downturns and recessions (e.g. a factory shut down for four months because the economy gets worse).", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、失業は3種類に分けられます。\n\n1. **frictional unemployment**(摩擦的失業): 転職・引っ越しに伴う **短期の求職**。例: 別の町に住みたくて辞め、新しい町で職探しを始める労働者。\n2. **structural unemployment**(構造的失業): スキルと求人の **ミスマッチ**(産業構造・技術変化)。例: ロボットに置き換えられ、別産業で職探しをする労働者。\n3. **cyclical unemployment**(循環的失業): **景気循環・不況** が原因。例: 景気悪化で工場が4か月閉鎖され解雇。", "example": "(Ch30 Q4) a. Factory shut for four months because the economy worsens = cyclical. b. Workers replaced by robots, look outside the auto industry = structural. c. Workers quit to live in another town and search there = frictional.", "whyNeeded": "失業の原因に応じた政策(景気刺激 vs 職業訓練)を考えるため。演習 Ch30 Q4 で3例の分類が頻出。", "mistakes": ["**structural**(ミスマッチ)と **frictional**(普通の求職)を取り違える誤り。ロボット置換は structural。", "**cyclical**(景気)と他の2つを取り違える誤り。一時的な景気悪化による解雇は cyclical。"], "memorize": "Frictional=search, Structural=mismatch, Cyclical=recession"}, {"id": "c32_minimum_wage_unemployment", "ch": 32, "week": 6, "name": "Minimum Wage & Unemployment", "star": false, "scene": "均衡賃金より高い最低賃金($10)が課されると、労働供給量が需要量を上回り、失業が生まれる状況。同じ論理は『高い職質(job quality)』の強制でも成り立つ。", "compare": null, "punchline": "A minimum wage set above equilibrium creates unemployment because quantity of labor supplied exceeds quantity demanded.", "defEN": "When a **minimum wage** is set above the equilibrium wage, the quantity of labor **supplied** exceeds the quantity **demanded**, creating unemployment. The same logic applies when a union negotiates a higher-than-equilibrium **job quality** while holding wages constant: the number of workers looking for work (Qs) exceeds the number of jobs (Q_mandate), so unemployment equals (Qs - Q_mandate). Jobs become higher quality, but there are fewer of them.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、均衡より高い **minimum wage**(最低賃金)を課すと、労働の **供給量が需要量を上回り** 失業が生まれます。\n\n--- 仕組み ---\n高い賃金 → 働きたい人が増える(供給↑)が、雇いたい企業は減る(需要↓)→ その差が失業。\n\n--- 応用: 職質(job quality) ---\n賃金を一定にして、組合が均衡より高い職質を勝ち取ると、求職者数 Qs が求人数 Q_mandate を上回り、失業 = Qs − Q_mandate。仕事の質は上がるが数は減る(演習 Ch30 Q27)。", "example": "(Ch30 Q6) With the implementation of a $10 minimum wage in the labor-market figure, the resulting unemployment rate is 50% (answer c): the gap between labor supplied and labor demanded at $10 is half of those who want to work.", "whyNeeded": "価格下限(price floor)が労働市場に失業を生む仕組みを理解するため。演習 Ch30 Q6(失業率50%)で頻出。", "mistakes": ["最低賃金が常に労働者を助けると思う誤り。均衡超なら **失業** を生む。", "職質(job quality)の上昇が無条件に良いと思う誤り。均衡超なら雇用数が減る。"], "memorize": "Min wage > equilibrium -> Qs > Qd -> unemployment = Qs - Qd"}, {"id": "c33_transmission_amplification", "ch": 33, "week": 6, "name": "Transmission & Amplification", "star": true, "scene": "小さな初期ショックが、なぜ産出・雇用・投資に大きな影響を与えるのかを考える状況。**transmission** はショックの広がり方、**amplification** は小さなショックが大きく増幅される理由。", "compare": {"a": "Transmission", "b": "Amplification", "table": [{"dim": "What it refers to", "a": "How a shock spreads across sectors/decisions", "b": "Why a small shock causes a large effect"}, {"dim": "Focus", "a": "Spreading through sectors and time", "b": "Magnification of output/employment/investment effects"}, {"dim": "Direction", "a": "Both up and down", "b": "Booms bigger, busts deeper"}]}, "punchline": "Transmission is how a shock spreads; amplification is why a small shock causes a large effect.", "defEN": "**Transmission** refers to how an initial economic shock **spreads** through different sectors or decisions. **Amplification** refers to why a small initial shock can cause a **large** overall effect on output, employment, or investment. A **transmission mechanism amplifies shocks** by spreading them across time and through sectors of the economy. Real shocks and aggregate demand shocks can interact, with one leading to the other; a mild negative shock can be transformed into a serious reduction in output, and a positive shock into a boom. Five mechanisms: **intertemporal substitution**, **uncertainty and irreversible investments**, **labor adjustment costs**, **time bunching**, and **collateral damage**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**transmission**(伝播)は『ショックが部門や意思決定を通じてどう広がるか』、**amplification**(増幅)は『小さなショックがなぜ大きな効果を生むか』です。\n\n--- 関係 ---\n**transmission mechanism** はショックを時間・部門を通じて広げ、**増幅** する(演習 Ch33 Q1: 答えは b)。real shock と AD shock は相互作用し、片方がもう片方を引き起こす。軽い負のショックが深刻な産出減に、正のショックがブームに転じうる。\n\n--- 5つのメカニズム ---\n1. intertemporal substitution\n2. uncertainty & irreversible investments\n3. labor adjustment costs\n4. time bunching\n5. collateral damage", "example": "A mild negative shock can be transformed into a serious reduction in output through transmission mechanisms; for example, rising rates lead households to postpone car and home purchases, so investment and production fall and unemployment rises.", "whyNeeded": "なぜ経済が小さな政策変化やショックに強く反応するかを説明する核心。演習 Ch33 Q1 で『transmission mechanism は時間・部門を通じてショックを増幅する』が正答。", "mistakes": ["**transmission mechanism** がショックを『緩和する(mitigate)』と思う誤り。実際は **amplify**(増幅)。", "transmission(広がり)と amplification(増幅)の役割を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Transmission = spread; Amplification = magnify (booms bigger, busts deeper)"}, {"id": "c33_intertemporal_substitution", "ch": 33, "week": 6, "name": "Intertemporal Substitution", "star": true, "scene": "人は頑張りの見返りが最も大きいときに最も働く。試験前に猛勉強し、終われば遊ぶように、努力を時間を通じて配分する状況。これが **intertemporal substitution**。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Intertemporal substitution amplifies cycles: people work and invest more in booms and less in recessions.", "defEN": "**Intertemporal substitution** is substituting effort (or consumption/investment) across time. People are most likely to work hard when hard work brings the greatest return - just as you study harder as a test approaches and less afterward. **Transmission role**: when real interest rates rise, people save more and consume less now, planning to consume later; firms delay investment when the cost of capital rises. **Amplification**: if many agents respond the same way, a small rate hike can significantly reduce current demand. Because the **returns to work are higher in booms than in recessions**, people work more during booms and less during recessions, which amplifies business cycles.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**intertemporal substitution**(異時点間の代替)は『努力・消費・投資を時間を通じて配分すること』です。試験前は猛勉強し、終われば遊ぶのと同じ。\n\n--- transmission role ---\n実質利子率が上がると、人は今より貯蓄し消費を減らし、後で消費しようとする。企業も資本コスト上昇で投資を遅らせる。\n\n--- amplification ---\n多くの人が同じように反応すると、わずかな利上げが現在の需要を大きく減らす。\n\n--- なぜ景気を増幅? ---\n働く見返りはブーム時に高く不況時に低いので、人はブームで多く働き不況で少なく働く(演習 Ch33 Q2: 答えは b)。", "example": "If the central bank raises rates, households postpone buying cars or homes, so investment and production fall and unemployment rises - a small rate hike is amplified into a larger slowdown.", "whyNeeded": "なぜ金利や見返りの変化が景気循環を増幅するかを説明する。演習 Ch33 Q2 で『ブームは働く見返りが高いので人は多く働く』が正答。", "mistakes": ["intertemporal substitution の理由を『投資の見返りが他者と連動するから(=time bunching/collateral)』と取り違える誤り。正しくは **働く見返りが好不況で変わる** から。"], "memorize": "Work/invest more when returns are highest -> amplifies booms & busts"}, {"id": "c33_irreversible_investment_uncertainty", "ch": 33, "week": 6, "name": "Uncertainty & Irreversible Investment", "star": true, "scene": "多くの投資は **sunk cost**(埋没費用)を伴い元に戻せない。世界が不確実なほど、企業は『様子見(wait-and-see)』で投資を遅らせる状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Uncertainty makes firms delay irreversible investments, freezing spending and deepening recessions.", "defEN": "Many investments involve **sunk costs** - they are **irreversible investments**, or very costly to reverse. The more uncertain the world appears, the harder it is for investors to read signals about where and when to invest; uncertainty usually slows investment and keeps resources in less productive uses. **Transmission role**: a rise in uncertainty (about demand, policy, or geopolitics) leads firms to delay investment, reducing short-run spending and employment. **Amplification**: this 'wait-and-see' behavior can make recessions deeper - uncertainty freezes investment, which lowers output and creates more uncertainty. Note: once an investment opportunity is identified, execution should **not** automatically follow immediately - it is rational to seek out the truth when new information casts suspicion.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、多くの投資は **sunk cost**(埋没費用)を伴う **irreversible investment**(不可逆投資)で、元に戻すのが非常に高くつきます。\n\n--- transmission role ---\n不確実性(需要・政策・地政学)が高まると、企業は投資を遅らせ、短期の支出と雇用が減る。\n\n--- amplification ---\nこの『wait-and-see(様子見)』が不況を深くする。不確実性が投資を凍結→産出↓→さらに不確実性↑の悪循環。\n\n--- 注意(Ch33 Q3) ---\n『投資機会を見つけたら直ちに実行すべき』は **誤り**。新情報が疑念を生むなら、真偽を確かめてから進めるのが合理的。", "example": "During a financial crisis, firms delay big projects because future profits are unclear, so aggregate investment collapses - a 'wait-and-see' response that deepens the downturn.", "whyNeeded": "不確実性が投資を凍結し不況を深める仕組みを理解するため。演習 Ch33 Q3 で『機会を見つけたら直ちに実行すべき=NOT true』が正答。", "mistakes": ["『不可逆投資は機会があれば即実行すべき』と思う誤り。不確実なら **wait-and-see** が合理的。", "**sunk cost**(埋没費用=回収不能)を可変費用と混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Uncertainty + sunk costs -> wait-and-see -> investment freezes -> deeper recession"}, {"id": "c33_labor_adjustment_costs", "ch": 33, "week": 6, "name": "Labor Adjustment Costs", "star": true, "scene": "負のショック後、労働者は新しい職探し・転居・賃金期待の調整を強いられる。これらが高いと、企業は雇用調整を遅らせ、失業が増える状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "High labor adjustment costs delay employment changes, magnifying negative shocks and raising unemployment.", "defEN": "Once a negative shock hits, workers must look for new jobs, move to new areas, and sometimes change their wage expectations. This induces more search and thus more **search-related unemployment**; the high cost of reversing job decisions can lead to unemployment. **Transmission role**: because of these **labor adjustment costs**, firms don't immediately adjust employment to match shocks; they smooth output through other channels (hours worked, productivity). **Amplification**: adjustment costs delay recovery after shocks - in a boom, hiring lags; in a slump, firms may overcut labor to avoid future costs, deepening downturns. A negative AD shock leads to a higher unemployment rate when labor adjustment costs are **higher**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**labor adjustment costs**(労働調整コスト)は『雇用を増減させるのにかかるコスト』です。\n\n--- 仕組み ---\n負のショック後、労働者は新しい職探し・転居・賃金期待の調整を迫られ、**search-related unemployment**(求職に伴う失業)が増える。不確実なとき多くの労働者は『待つ』ので失業が増え、負の実質ショックが増幅される。\n\n--- transmission/amplification ---\n企業は雇用を即調整せず、労働時間や生産性で調整。調整コストは回復を遅らせる。ブームでは採用が遅れ、不況では企業が労働を過剰に削減し下降を深める。\n\n--- 週テスト Q3 ---\n『負の AD ショックは labor adjustment costs が **高い** ほど失業率を上げる』が正答(D)。", "example": "If demand falls, firms lay off workers slowly - but once layoffs begin, they may overshoot because rehiring is costly, deepening the downturn. (Weekly Test 6 Q3: a negative AD shock raises unemployment most when labor adjustment costs are higher.)", "whyNeeded": "なぜ雇用がショックにすぐ反応せず、回復が遅れるかを説明する。週テスト Q3 で labor adjustment costs が答えとして頻出。", "mistakes": ["『調整コストが低いほど失業が増える』と思う誤り。負の AD ショックで失業が増えるのはコストが **高い** とき。", "labor adjustment costs(雇用調整)と intertemporal substitution(時間配分)を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Higher labor adjustment costs -> slower adjustment -> more unemployment from shocks"}, {"id": "c33_time_bunching", "ch": 33, "week": 6, "name": "Time Bunching", "star": false, "scene": "人々は他者と行動を合わせると得なので、投資・生産・販売を同時に行う。この『時間的な集中』がショックを時間を通じて広げる状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Time bunching clusters activity into the same period, magnifying business cycles - peaks higher, troughs deeper.", "defEN": "**Time bunching**: many economic activities cluster in time because it pays to coordinate your economic actions with those of others - we want to invest, produce, and sell at the same time as others, which makes buying and selling more efficient. But it also causes shocks to spread through the economy and through time. **Transmission role**: policies or shocks that affect timing (tax changes, bonuses, expected inflation) can lead to synchronized spending or production. **Amplification**: when many agents bunch activity into the same period, it magnifies business cycles - peaks get higher and troughs deeper.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**time bunching**(時間的集中)は『他者と行動を合わせると得なので、経済活動が同じ時期に集中する』ことです。\n\n--- なぜ集中? ---\nみんなと同時に投資・生産・販売すると売買が効率的になる。でもその分、ショックが経済全体・時間を通じて広がる。\n\n--- transmission role ---\nタイミングに影響する政策・ショック(税変更、ボーナス、予想インフレ)が、支出や生産の意思決定を同期させる。\n\n--- amplification ---\n多くの人が同じ時期に活動を束ねると、景気循環が増幅される(山は高く、谷は深く)。", "example": "If firms expect taxes to rise next year, they rush investments into this year, causing a temporary boom followed by a slump next year.", "whyNeeded": "なぜ景気の山と谷が極端になるかを説明する。amplification メカニズムの一つとして週テストの選択肢に登場。", "mistakes": ["time bunching(同時行動)を collateral damage(担保・信用)と混同する誤り。", "time bunching がショックを平準化すると思う誤り。実際は **山谷を増幅**。"], "memorize": "Time bunching: coordinate timing -> synchronized booms/busts (peaks higher, troughs deeper)"}, {"id": "c33_collateral_damage", "ch": 33, "week": 6, "name": "Collateral Damage (Financial Accelerator)", "star": true, "scene": "銀行は下振れリスクを重視する。資産価格(住宅・株)が下がると企業・家計の信用が縮み、支出・投資が減り、さらに資産価格が下がる悪循環の状況。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Falling asset values cut access to credit, creating a feedback loop that amplifies downturns - the financial accelerator.", "defEN": "Banks are more concerned about **downside risk** because if a customer does poorly, the bank could lose the entire value of its loan, whereas if the firm does well the bank only gets its loan back plus interest. Banks don't often invest in startups or firms whose debts exceed assets because of a lack of **collateral**. For the economy as a whole this amplifies booms and busts. **Transmission role**: a fall in asset prices (housing or stocks) limits firms' and households' access to credit, so spending and investment fall. **Amplification**: the feedback loop - lower collateral leads to less borrowing, lower spending, and even lower asset prices - amplifies downturns. This is often called the **financial accelerator**. Collateral shocks amplify cycles because assets are worth more in booms than recessions, and asset values are positively correlated with firms' ability to obtain funding.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**collateral damage**(担保ショック)は『資産価格の下落が信用を縮め、不況を増幅する』メカニズムです。\n\n--- 銀行の行動 ---\n銀行は **downside risk**(下振れリスク)を重視。借り手が失敗すると融資全額を失いうるが、成功しても元本＋利子しか得られない。だから **collateral**(担保)が不足する企業には貸さない。\n\n--- transmission role ---\n住宅・株などの資産価格下落 → 企業・家計の信用アクセス低下 → 支出・投資↓。\n\n--- amplification(financial accelerator) ---\n担保↓ → 借入↓ → 支出↓ → 資産価格さらに↓ の悪循環。これを **financial accelerator** と呼ぶ。\n\n演習 Ch33 Q4: 『資産はブーム時に価値が高く、資産価値は企業の資金調達力と正に相関』が正答(a)。", "example": "In a housing bust, falling home prices reduce homeowners' equity, so consumption falls, demand weakens further, and prices fall again - the financial-accelerator feedback loop.", "whyNeeded": "金融市場がどう実体経済のショックを増幅するかを理解する核心。演習 Ch33 Q4 で『資産価値と資金調達力の正の相関』が正答。", "mistakes": ["collateral damage(信用・担保チャネル)を labor adjustment costs と混同する誤り。", "Ch33 Q4: 『働く見返り(intertemporal)』や『投資の連動(time bunching)』を選ぶ誤り。正しくは **資産価値と資金調達力の正の相関**。"], "memorize": "Collateral down -> borrow less -> spend less -> assets down (financial accelerator)"}, {"id": "c34_central_bank_role", "ch": 34, "week": 7, "name": "Central Bank and Its Policy Tools", "star": true, "scene": "**European Central Bank** や **Federal Reserve**、**De Nederlandsche Bank** といった中央銀行が、経済全体のお金の量をどうコントロールするかという状況。中央銀行は **money supply** の(成長率)を決め、それが **aggregate demand** を通じて景気とインフレに影響する。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Central banks determine and influence the growth rate of the money supply, affecting aggregate demand, real GDP growth in the short run, and inflation.", "defEN": "**Central banks** (like the European Central Bank, the Federal Reserve, or De Nederlandsche Bank) determine and influence the growth rate of the **money supply**. From the Quantity Theory of Money and the AD/AS framework, this influences **aggregate demand** and thereby **Real GDP growth** in the short run (via SRAS) and **inflation** in the short and long run.\n\nCentral banks use several instruments to influence the money supply and interest rates: **policy interest rates**, **open market operations**, **reserve requirements**, **forward guidance and communication**, and **quantitative easing**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**central bank**(中央銀行)は『お金の量(の成長率)を決めて景気とインフレを動かす存在』です。\n\n--- なぜ効くか ---\n• Quantity Theory of Money と AD/AS から、**money supply** は **aggregate demand** に影響する。\n• その結果、短期では **Real GDP growth**(SRAS経由)、短期・長期では **inflation** が動く。\n\n--- 5つの道具 ---\n• **policy interest rates**(政策金利)\n• **open market operations**(公開市場操作)\n• **reserve requirements**(準備率)\n• **forward guidance**(フォワードガイダンス)\n• **quantitative easing**(量的緩和)", "example": "In 2020, the ECB kept its main refinancing rate at 0% to stimulate demand during the pandemic. The Fed raised rates sharply in 2022-2023 to cool inflation, from near 0% to above 5%.", "whyNeeded": "中央銀行が **money supply** を通じて景気循環に介入する仕組みは Week 7 の中心。5つの道具と、それぞれが **aggregate demand** に与える効果は試験で頻出。", "mistakes": ["中央銀行が金利を『直接すべて』決めると誤解する誤り。中央銀行は **policy interest rate** を設定し、それが他の金利に波及する。", "**money supply** と **money demand** を混同する誤り。中央銀行が操作するのは供給側。"], "memorize": "5 tools: policy rates, OMO, reserve requirements, forward guidance, QE"}, {"id": "c34_policy_interest_rate", "ch": 34, "week": 7, "name": "Policy Interest Rate", "star": true, "scene": "中央銀行が商業銀行の借入コストを左右する『鍵となる金利』を設定する状況。**policy interest rate** は住宅ローンから企業融資、預金金利まで、経済の他のすべての金利に影響する。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The central bank sets a key interest rate that influences borrowing costs throughout the economy, raising AD when lowered and lowering AD when raised.", "defEN": "A **policy interest rate** is a key interest rate the central bank sets that influences how much it costs commercial banks to borrow money. These rates affect all other interest rates in the economy, from mortgages to business loans and savings accounts.\n\n**Lower rates** lead to cheaper borrowing, more spending and investment, and higher **aggregate demand**. **Higher rates** lead to more expensive borrowing, less spending, and lower **aggregate demand**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**policy interest rate**(政策金利)は『中央銀行が決める鍵となる金利』で、経済の他のすべての金利に波及します。\n\n--- 仕組み ---\n• **Lower rates** → 借入が安い → 支出・投資が増える → **aggregate demand** が増加。\n• **Higher rates** → 借入が高い → 支出が減る → **aggregate demand** が減少。\n\n--- COVID-19の例 ---\n• 2020年以前から ECB の金利は超低水準: main refinancing rate 0.00%、deposit facility rate −0.50%、marginal lending facility rate 0.25%。\n• 2016年以降ほぼゼロで、これ以上下げる余地がほとんどなかった。", "example": "In 2020, the ECB kept the main refinancing rate at 0% to keep borrowing costs stable for banks and firms during the panic and to avoid tightening financial conditions when liquidity was critical.", "whyNeeded": "金利の上下が **aggregate demand** をどう動かすかは monetary policy の出発点。利上げ・利下げの方向と効果を取り違えないことが試験で問われる。", "mistakes": ["利下げで AD が『減る』と取り違える誤り。lower rates → higher AD。", "**policy interest rate** を市場が決める金利と混同する誤り。これは中央銀行が設定する。"], "memorize": "Lower rates -> cheaper borrowing -> higher AD; higher rates -> lower AD"}, {"id": "c34_open_market_operations", "ch": 34, "week": 7, "name": "Open Market Operations", "star": true, "scene": "中央銀行が公開市場で **government bonds** を売買して、お金の量と短期金利をコントロールする状況。Week 7 のテストでも『Fed が国債を買って銀行口座に入金したらマネーサプライがいくら増えるか』が問われる。", "compare": {"a": "Central Bank Buys Bonds", "b": "Central Bank Sells Bonds", "table": [{"dim": "Demand for bonds", "a": "Increases", "b": "Decreases"}, {"dim": "Price of bonds", "a": "Rises", "b": "Falls"}, {"dim": "Interest rates", "a": "Fall", "b": "Rise"}, {"dim": "Liquidity in banks", "a": "Injected (increases)", "b": "Removed (decreases)"}, {"dim": "Aggregate demand", "a": "Increases", "b": "Decreases"}]}, "punchline": "Open market operations are buying or selling government bonds to control the money supply and influence short-term interest rates.", "defEN": "**Open market operations** are the buying or selling of **government bonds** in the open market to control the **money supply** and influence short-term interest rates.\n\n**Buying bonds** injects money into banks, increasing liquidity, so aggregate demand increases. **Selling bonds** takes money out of banks, reducing liquidity, so aggregate demand decreases.\n\nWhen the central bank buys bonds, demand for bonds rises, the price of bonds rises, and interest rates fall. When it sells bonds, demand falls, the price of bonds falls, and interest rates rise.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**open market operations**(公開市場操作、OMOs)は『中央銀行が **government bonds**(国債)を売買してマネーサプライと短期金利を動かすこと』です。\n\n--- 仕組み ---\n• **Buying bonds**(買いオペ)→ 銀行にお金を注入 → 流動性↑ → AD↑。\n• **Selling bonds**(売りオペ)→ 銀行からお金を吸収 → 流動性↓ → AD↓。\n\n--- 価格と金利 ---\n• 買い → 債券需要↑ → 債券価格↑ → 金利↓。\n• 売り → 債券需要↓ → 債券価格↓ → 金利↑。", "example": "During the 2008 financial crisis, the Fed bought large amounts of government securities to keep interest rates low and boost lending. The ECB does similar operations to maintain its target interest rates within the eurozone.", "whyNeeded": "OMO は中央銀行が日常的に金利を誘導する主力ツール。『買うと金利が下がる』『債券価格と金利は逆方向』の関係は試験で頻出。", "mistakes": ["債券価格と金利の方向を逆にする誤り。bond price↑ ⇔ interest rate↓。", "buying bonds でマネーサプライが減ると取り違える誤り。買いオペは流動性を『注入』する。"], "memorize": "Buy bonds = inject money, bond price up, rates down, AD up"}, {"id": "c34_reserve_requirement", "ch": 34, "week": 7, "name": "Reserve Requirement and Reserve Ratio", "star": true, "scene": "商業銀行が預金のうち何%を貸さずに手元(準備)に置かねばならないかを決める **reserve requirement** の状況。$10 の預金につき $1 を準備として持てば **reserve ratio** は 0.1。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The reserve requirement is the percentage of deposits banks must hold in reserve and not lend out; the reserve ratio is reserves divided by deposits.", "defEN": "The **reserve requirement** is the percentage of deposits that commercial banks must hold in reserve and not lend out. The level of reserves is defined by the **reserve ratio**, i.e., the ratio of reserves to deposits. If $1 in cash is held in reserve for every $10 of deposits, the reserve ratio is 0.1. The reserve ratio is determined primarily by the market and by the central bank.\n\nA **lower reserve ratio** lets banks lend more, so the money supply rises and aggregate demand increases. A **higher reserve ratio** means less lending, so aggregate demand decreases.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**reserve requirement**(準備率規制)は『銀行が預金のうち貸し出さずに準備として持たねばならない割合』です。実際の水準は **reserve ratio**(準備率 = reserves ÷ deposits)で測ります。\n\n--- 計算例 ---\n• 預金 $10 につき現金 $1 を準備 → reserve ratio = 0.1。\n\n--- AD への効果 ---\n• **lower reserve ratio** → 銀行が多く貸せる → money supply↑ → AD↑。\n• **higher reserve ratio** → 貸出が減る → AD↓。", "example": "The ECB currently sets a minimum reserve requirement of 1% of certain liabilities. For every euro 100 deposited, a bank must keep euro 1 as reserves at the ECB and can lend the other euro 99. The People's Bank of China cut its reserve requirement ratio several times in 2023 to encourage lending.", "whyNeeded": "**reserve ratio** は次に学ぶ **money multiplier** の逆数で、マネーサプライ計算の土台。準備率を上下させると貸出能力がどう変わるかは試験で頻出。", "mistakes": ["**reserve ratio** を上げると貸出が増えると取り違える誤り。ratio↑ → 貸出↓ → AD↓。", "reserve ratio(比率)と reserves(準備の額)を混同する誤り。"], "memorize": "Reserve ratio = reserves / deposits; $1 per $10 -> 0.1"}, {"id": "c34_money_multiplier", "ch": 34, "week": 7, "name": "Money Multiplier", "star": true, "scene": "中央銀行が銀行準備を $100,000 増やしたとき、銀行システム全体でマネーサプライが最終的にいくら増えるかを知りたい状況。鍵は **reserve ratio** の逆数である **money multiplier**。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The money multiplier is the inverse of the reserve ratio (1/RR) and tells how much deposits expand with increases in reserves.", "defEN": "The inverse of the **reserve ratio** (1/RR) is called the **money multiplier (MM)**, which is around 3 in reality (and 10 in a textbook example). The **money multiplier** tells us how much deposits expand with increases in reserves.\n\nTotal potential increase in the money supply = change in reserves x money multiplier = change in reserves / reserve ratio.\n\nFor the ECB, with a 1% reserve requirement, the money multiplier is 1 / 0.01 = 100 (theoretical maximum); in practice the actual multiplier is lower because banks often hold excess reserves and some deposits leak out as cash.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**money multiplier**(貨幣乗数、MM)は『**reserve ratio** の逆数 (1/RR)』で、『準備が増えると預金が何倍に膨らむか』を表します。\n\n--- 計算 ---\nマネーサプライの最大増加 = 準備の増加 × MM = 準備の増加 ÷ reserve ratio。\n\n--- 例 ---\n• RR = 20% → MM = 1/0.2 = 5。準備 $100,000 増 → 最大 $500,000 増。\n• ECB の RR = 1% → MM = 1/0.01 = 100(理論上の最大)。\n• 現実では銀行が **excess reserves**(超過準備)を持ち、現金として漏れるため実際の乗数は低い(現実で約3)。", "example": "If the average reserve ratio is 20% and the Fed increases bank reserves by $100,000, the total potential increase in the money supply is $100,000 / 0.20 = $500,000.", "whyNeeded": "Week 7 の演習・週テストの計算問題そのもの。reserve ratio から乗数を出し、マネーサプライの増加を求める手順は必出。", "mistakes": ["準備の増加に乗数を『掛ける』のに『足す』誤り。Increase = reserves x (1/RR)。", "理論上の乗数(1/RR)と現実の乗数を同一視する誤り。現実は excess reserves と現金漏れで小さい。"], "memorize": "MM = 1 / reserve ratio; money supply rise = reserves / RR"}, {"id": "c34_quantitative_easing", "ch": 34, "week": 7, "name": "Quantitative Easing (QE)", "star": true, "scene": "金利がすでにゼロ近辺で『これ以上下げられない』状況。中央銀行は **government or corporate bonds** を大量に買ってお金を直接注入し、長期金利を下げる **quantitative easing** を使う。Week 7 演習では『QE の例はどれか』も問われる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Quantitative easing is a non-traditional tool used when interest rates are near zero: the central bank buys large quantities of financial assets to inject money and lower long-term interest rates.", "defEN": "**Quantitative Easing (QE)** is a non-traditional tool used when interest rates are already near zero. The central bank buys large quantities of financial assets (like government or corporate bonds) to inject money directly into the economy and lower **long-term interest rates**.\n\nIt influences aggregate demand by increasing liquidity and lowering borrowing costs, and by raising asset prices, which increases wealth and boosts consumption and investment.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**quantitative easing**(量的緩和、QE)は『金利がゼロ近辺で下げられないときに、中央銀行が大量の金融資産(国債や社債)を買ってお金を直接注入する手法』です。\n\n--- AD への効果 ---\n• 流動性を増やし借入コストを下げる。\n• **asset prices**(資産価格)を押し上げ → wealth↑ → 消費・投資↑。\n\n--- ポイント(演習) ---\n• QE の典型例は『**long-term** government bonds の購入』。短期国債の購入は通常の OMO に近い。", "example": "The Fed's QE programs (2009-2014) involved trillions of dollars of bond purchases to revive lending after the financial crisis. In an exercise, the Fed purchasing $50,000 of long-term government bonds is the example of QE (not short-term bonds).", "whyNeeded": "金利がゼロ下限に達した後の非伝統的手段として重要。QE と通常の OMO の違い(長期資産・資産価格チャネル)は試験で問われる。", "mistakes": ["短期国債の購入を QE と取り違える誤り。QE は主に **long-term** 資産を買う。", "QE と単なる利下げを同一視する誤り。QE は金利がゼロ近辺で使う非伝統的ツール。"], "memorize": "QE = buy long-term assets when rates near zero; inject money, raise asset prices"}, {"id": "c34_forward_guidance", "ch": 34, "week": 7, "name": "Forward Guidance", "star": false, "scene": "中央銀行が『今後も金利を低く保つ』と将来の政策意図を伝えることで、人々の期待を動かす状況。金利がまだ変わっていなくても、期待だけで投資や支出が増える。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Forward guidance is when central banks communicate future policy intentions to shape expectations about interest rates, inflation, and economic conditions.", "defEN": "**Forward guidance** is when central banks communicate their future policy intentions to shape **expectations** about interest rates, inflation, and economic conditions. If businesses and households expect rates to stay low, they are more likely to borrow and invest now.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**forward guidance**(フォワードガイダンス)は『中央銀行が将来の政策方針を予め伝えて、人々の **expectations**(期待)を動かす手法』です。\n\n--- なぜ効くか ---\n• 企業や家計が『金利は当面低いまま』と期待すれば、今のうちに借りて投資・支出する。\n• 金利が実際に変わる前から **aggregate demand** を押し上げられる。", "example": "In 2020, the ECB and the Fed both promised to keep rates low 'for as long as necessary' to support the recovery after COVID-19. This signaled stability, boosted confidence, and increased aggregate demand even before rates changed.", "whyNeeded": "期待(**expectations channel**)を通じて、政策金利を実際に動かさずに AD を動かせる点が重要。5つの政策ツールの一つとして区別が問われる。", "mistakes": ["forward guidance を実際の利下げと混同する誤り。これは『コミュニケーション』であり期待に働きかける。", "期待が変わっても効果はないと考える誤り。期待だけで支出が動く。"], "memorize": "Forward guidance = communicate future policy to shape expectations"}, {"id": "c34_monetary_policy_difficulty", "ch": 34, "week": 7, "name": "Limits and Lags of Monetary Policy", "star": true, "scene": "中央銀行が景気を安定させたくても、リアルタイムでデータが揃わず、マネーサプライの制御も不完全でラグがある状況。3つの実務的な問いに答えねばならない。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Monetary policy is difficult because the central bank must act in real time with unknown data and has incomplete, lagged control over the money supply.", "defEN": "Monetary policy is difficult because: (1) the central bank must operate in **real time** when much of the data about the state of the economy is unknown; and (2) the central bank's control of the **money supply** is incomplete and subject to **uncertain lags**.\n\nThree key practical questions are: When should the central bank try to influence AD? When will it be able to influence AD? When will the influence on AD result in higher GDP growth rates?\n\nTo predict effects, the central bank must monitor whether banks will lend out all new reserves or hold **excess reserves**, how quickly increases in the **monetary base (MB)** translate into new loans and larger M1 and M2, whether businesses want to borrow, and whether they will hire or just hold the money.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、monetary policy が難しいのは『リアルタイムでデータが分からず、マネーサプライの制御も不完全でラグがあるから』です。\n\n--- 2つの難しさ ---\n• 経済の状態が分からないまま **real time** で動かねばならない。\n• **money supply** の制御は不完全で **uncertain lags**(不確実なラグ)を伴う。\n\n--- 3つの実務的な問い ---\n1. いつ AD に影響を与えるべきか。\n2. いつ AD に影響を与えられるか。\n3. その影響がいつ GDP 成長率の上昇につながるか。\n\n--- 監視すべき変数 ---\n• 銀行は新しい準備を全部貸すか、**excess reserves**(超過準備)を持つか。\n• **monetary base (MB)** の増加がどれだけ速く M1・M2 の増加に変わるか。\n• 企業は借りたいか、借りても雇用・投資するか。", "example": "Banks may lend out only a portion of new reserves, holding the rest as excess reserves, so an increase in the monetary base (MB) may translate only slowly and uncertainly into larger M1 and M2.", "whyNeeded": "政策が『効くまで時間がかかり、効果が読めない』ことは、なぜ中央銀行が間違えうるか(Great Depression や Great Recession への批判)の理解に不可欠。", "mistakes": ["中央銀行がマネーサプライを完全に制御できると考える誤り。制御は incomplete で lags がある。", "**monetary base (MB)** と M1/M2 を同一視する誤り。MB が増えても貸出を通じてしか M1/M2 は増えない。"], "memorize": "Hard because: real-time data unknown + incomplete control + uncertain lags"}, {"id": "c35_best_case_demand_shock", "ch": 35, "week": 7, "name": "Monetary Policy Response to a Spending (AD) Shock", "star": true, "scene": "民間の支出減で **aggregate demand** が下がり、インフレも成長も落ちた『ベストケース』の状況。Fed がマネーサプライを増やせば AD を元に戻し、リセッションの長さと深さを和らげられる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "When a negative spending shock lowers AD, the Fed can increase the money supply to push AD back, restoring growth with little long-run cost.", "defEN": "When the rate of growth of the **money supply** falls, this causes a fall in **aggregate demand** and a decline in the growth rate of output. Because wages are **sticky**, the adjustment takes time and considerable unemployment before the economy adjusts.\n\nThis is the **best case** for monetary policy: a negative shock to AD lowers inflation and growth, and the **Fed response** is to increase M, which raises AD, increasing both inflation and growth back toward the Solow rate. The central bank can use monetary policy to reduce the length and severity of a recession.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、これは『民間支出の減少で AD が下がったとき、Fed が M を増やして AD を元に戻す』ベストケースです。\n\n--- 流れ ---\n• 民間支出減 → **negative shock to AD**: ↓M → ↓AD → ↓π, ↓growth。\n• **wages are sticky**(賃金が硬直的)なので調整に時間がかかり失業も出る。\n• **Fed Response**: ↑M → ↑AD → ↑π, ↑growth で Solow 成長率に戻す。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• AD ショックは『best case』。中央銀行はリセッションの長さと severity(深刻さ)を減らせる。", "example": "A private decrease in spending shifts AD from (M + v) = 10% to (M + v) = 5%, lowering inflation from 7% to 6% and growth to -1%. The Fed responds by increasing M to shift AD back, raising inflation and growth (back toward 3% growth).", "whyNeeded": "AD ショックは『中央銀行が AD を動かすだけで対処できる』理想ケース。次の real shock(ジレンマ)との対比が試験で最重要。", "mistakes": ["AD ショックと real shock を同一視する誤り。AD ショックは best case で完全に相殺できる。", "**sticky wages** を無視して即座に調整すると考える誤り。硬直性ゆえにリセッションが長引く。"], "memorize": "AD shock = best case: Fed offsets by changing M, restores growth"}, {"id": "c35_real_shock_dilemma", "ch": 35, "week": 7, "name": "Monetary Policy Dilemma (Real Shock)", "star": true, "scene": "**negative real shock** が **LRAS** を左にシフトさせ、インフレ上昇かつ成長低下を招く厳しい状況。Fed は AD を増やせるが、経済の生産性が落ちているため増分の多くはインフレに化ける。", "compare": {"a": "Spending (AD) Shock", "b": "Real Shock", "table": [{"dim": "Which curve shifts", "a": "AD curve", "b": "LRAS curve shifts left"}, {"dim": "Effect on inflation and growth", "a": "Both fall together (negative AD shock)", "b": "Inflation rises, growth falls"}, {"dim": "Can the Fed fully offset it?", "a": "Yes (best case)", "b": "No (dilemma)"}, {"dim": "If Fed increases M", "a": "Restores growth, little long-run cost", "b": "Some growth but much higher inflation"}, {"dim": "If Fed decreases M", "a": "Deepens recession", "b": "Lower inflation but even lower growth"}]}, "punchline": "A negative real shock shifts LRAS left, raising inflation and lowering growth, leaving the Fed with no fully good option.", "defEN": "A difficult case for monetary policy is when the economy is hit by a **negative real shock**: it shifts the **LRAS** curve to the left, increasing inflation and decreasing GDP growth (the economy moves from a to a recession at b).\n\nThe central bank faces a dilemma. If the Fed decreases M, this moves the economy to lower inflation but even lower growth (point c). If the Fed increases AD, the increase in M brings some growth but much higher inflation, because the economy is less productive than before, so most of the increase shows up in **inflation**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**real shock**(実物ショック)は monetary policy の『ジレンマ』です。\n\n--- 何が起きるか ---\n• **negative real shock** → **LRAS** が左にシフト → インフレ↑かつ成長↓(a → リセッションの b)。\n\n--- 2つの選択肢 ---\n• Fed が ↓M → インフレは下がるが成長はさらに下がる(c)。\n• Fed が ↑AD(↑M)→ 多少の成長は出るが、生産性が落ちているため増分の多くは **inflation** に化け、インフレが大きく上がる。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• AD ショックと違い、どちらを選んでも痛みが残る。", "example": "A real shock shifts LRAS left, moving the economy from a to b at 8% inflation. If the Fed increases AD (M + v from 5% to 12%), there is some growth but inflation jumps to 13%; if the Fed decreases M, inflation falls but growth drops even further (point c).", "whyNeeded": "real shock では中央銀行が『インフレ vs 成長』のトレードオフに直面する。AD ショック(best case)との違いは試験で必出。", "mistakes": ["real shock を AD を増やすだけで完全に治せると考える誤り。生産性が落ちているので多くはインフレになる。", "**LRAS** シフト(real shock)と AD シフト(spending shock)を取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "Real shock shifts LRAS left -> inflation up, growth down; no good Fed option"}, {"id": "c35_inflation_targeting_real_shock", "ch": 35, "week": 7, "name": "Inflation Targeting and a Negative Real Shock", "star": true, "scene": "中央銀行が『一定のインフレ率』を目標(target)にしている状況で、**negative real shock** が起きてインフレが上がる場面。インフレ目標を守るには、Fed はマネーサプライ成長を抑えて AD を左にシフトさせる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "If a central bank targets a fixed inflation rate and a negative real shock raises inflation, it shifts the AD curve to the left.", "defEN": "Suppose a central bank **targets a fixed rate of inflation**. A negative real shock shifts the **LRAS** curve left, which raises inflation and lowers growth. To keep inflation at its target, the central bank uses monetary policy to shift the **AD curve to the left** (by reducing money supply growth).\n\nThis keeps inflation on target but, because the real shock has reduced productivity, real growth falls even further. It illustrates the cost of strict inflation targeting in the face of real shocks.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、中央銀行が **inflation target**(インフレ目標)を一定に保とうとするとき、**negative real shock** が来たら『AD を左にシフト』させます。\n\n--- なぜ左シフトか ---\n• real shock で **LRAS** が左へ → インフレ↑、成長↓。\n• 目標インフレを守るには AD を下げる(マネーサプライ成長を抑える)。\n\n--- コスト ---\n• インフレは目標に戻るが、成長はさらに下がる。\n• 厳格なインフレ目標は real shock のとき景気を犠牲にする。", "example": "If a central bank targets a fixed rate of inflation and a negative real shock occurs, it uses monetary policy to shift the AD curve to the left.", "whyNeeded": "インフレ目標と real shock の組み合わせは演習問題の定番。『目標固定なら AD を左に』という方向判断が問われる。", "mistakes": ["インフレ目標固定で real shock のとき AD を『右』に動かすと取り違える誤り。インフレを抑えるには左シフト。", "real shock のとき SRAS を動かせると考える誤り。中央銀行が直接動かせるのは AD。"], "memorize": "Inflation target + negative real shock -> shift AD curve LEFT"}, {"id": "c35_real_shock_inflation_bias", "ch": 35, "week": 7, "name": "Combating a Real Shock: Growth vs Inflation", "star": true, "scene": "Fed が **negative real shock** に対してマネーサプライ成長を増やして対抗するとき、結果として real GDP 成長率とインフレ率がどう動くかを比べる状況。生産性が落ちているため、効果の多くはインフレに偏る。", "compare": null, "punchline": "When the Fed raises money growth to combat a negative real shock, real GDP growth increases less than the inflation rate.", "defEN": "When the Federal Reserve increases the growth rate of the **money supply** to combat a **negative real shock**, the growth rate of real GDP will increase **less than the inflation rate**.\n\nThis is because a real shock has reduced the economy's productive capacity (LRAS shifted left), so most of any increase in aggregate demand shows up as **inflation** rather than as higher real output. The same logic explains why monetary policy cannot fully cure a real shock.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、Fed が **negative real shock** に対抗してマネーサプライ成長を増やすと、『real GDP 成長率の増加 < インフレ率の増加』になります。\n\n--- なぜか ---\n• real shock で経済の生産能力(LRAS)が落ちている。\n• だから AD を増やしても、その多くは **inflation** になり、real output はあまり増えない。\n\n--- ポイント ---\n• これが『real shock は金融政策で完全には治せない』理由。", "example": "When the Fed increases money growth by 3 percentage points after a negative supply shock takes the economy from A to Y, the economy moves to an intermediate point (point X), with real GDP growth rising less than inflation.", "whyNeeded": "real shock のときの『成長 < インフレ』という非対称性は演習・週テストで問われる。AD ショックとの違いを定量的に理解する必要がある。", "mistakes": ["real shock のとき成長とインフレが同じだけ上がると考える誤り。成長の増加はインフレより小さい。", "AD ショックと混同して『M を増やせば成長だけ戻る』と考える誤り。"], "memorize": "Real shock + more M -> real GDP grows LESS than inflation rises"}, {"id": "c35_policy_effectiveness_confidence", "ch": 35, "week": 7, "name": "Conditions for Effective Monetary Policy", "star": true, "scene": "Fed がマネーサプライ成長を上げて real GDP 成長を引き上げたいとき、どんな条件なら政策がよく効くかを問う状況。逆に、不確実性で現金需要が増えたり、人々が政策を信じなければ効果は弱まる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Monetary policy raises real GDP growth more effectively when prices remain very sticky.", "defEN": "If the Fed wants to raise real GDP growth by raising money supply growth, the condition that makes monetary policy **more effective** in raising real GDP growth is that **prices continue to remain very sticky**. With sticky prices, an increase in money growth raises real output rather than just prices.\n\nMonetary policy is **less effective** when uncertainty causes people to increase their demand for cash, when people lose confidence and reduce investment spending, or when people believe the Fed will abandon its policy (expectations matter). Increased uncertainty shifts the AD curve inward.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、Fed がマネーサプライ成長で real GDP 成長を上げたいとき、『**prices** がとても sticky(硬直的)なら』政策はよく効きます。\n\n--- なぜ sticky だと効くか ---\n• 価格が動かなければ、M の増加は価格ではなく real output を押し上げる。\n\n--- 効きにくい条件 ---\n• 不確実性で人々が現金需要を増やす。\n• 人々が信頼を失い投資支出を減らす。\n• 人々が『Fed は政策をやめる』と信じる(expectations)。\n• increased uncertainty は AD 曲線を内側(inward)にシフトさせる。", "example": "Among the options, prices remaining very sticky makes monetary policy more effective at raising real GDP growth; rising cash demand, falling confidence, or expecting the Fed to abandon its policy all make it less effective.", "whyNeeded": "金融政策の有効性が『価格の硬直性・信頼・期待』に依存することは演習で問われる。**sticky prices** が効果を高める仕組みの理解が必要。", "mistakes": ["不確実性や信頼喪失が政策を『強める』と取り違える誤り。これらは効果を弱める。", "価格が伸縮的(flexible)なほど real GDP が動くと考える誤り。逆で、sticky なほど real output が動く。"], "memorize": "Policy most effective when prices stay very sticky; uncertainty shifts AD inward"}, {"id": "c38_trade_deficit_surplus", "ch": 38, "week": 7, "name": "Trade Deficit and Trade Surplus", "star": true, "scene": "ある国の輸入額が輸出額を上回るか下回るかで貿易収支が決まる状況。輸入 > 輸出なら **trade deficit**、輸出 > 輸入なら **trade surplus**。", "compare": {"a": "Trade Deficit", "b": "Trade Surplus", "table": [{"dim": "Definition", "a": "Imports exceed exports", "b": "Exports exceed imports"}, {"dim": "Spending vs income", "a": "Spending exceeds earning", "b": "Earning exceeds spending"}, {"dim": "Matched by", "a": "Capital inflow / capital surplus (a loan)", "b": "Capital outflow / lending abroad"}, {"dim": "Optimistic view", "a": "Country is a great place to invest", "b": "n/a"}, {"dim": "Pessimistic view", "a": "Country is consuming too much, saving too little", "b": "n/a"}]}, "punchline": "A trade deficit occurs when imports exceed exports; a trade surplus occurs when exports exceed imports.", "defEN": "A **trade deficit** occurs when the value of a country's **imports** exceeds the value of its **exports**. A **trade surplus** occurs when the value of a country's **exports** exceeds the value of its **imports**.\n\nWith no borrowing, a person's trade deficits (purchases) must be matched with other trade surpluses (income). If you take out a loan, you are spending but not earning equivalent goods and services, so you run a trade deficit balanced by a **capital inflow** or **capital surplus**.\n\nThere are two views on whether a trade deficit is a problem: the **optimistic** view (the country is a great place to invest) and the **pessimistic** view (people are consuming too much and saving too little). Consensus: a mild trade deficit is not a problem, but it may indicate low savings.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**trade deficit**(貿易赤字)は『輸入 > 輸出』、**trade surplus**(貿易黒字)は『輸出 > 輸入』です。\n\n--- 借入との関係 ---\n• 借入がなければ、赤字(購入)は黒字(所得)で相殺されねばならない。\n• ローンを組むと、支出はするが同額を『輸出(稼ぐ)』しないので赤字になり、それは **capital inflow / capital surplus** で相殺される。\n\n--- 2つの見方 ---\n• **optimistic**(楽観):外国が投資したがる『良い投資先』だから赤字。\n• **pessimistic**(悲観):消費しすぎ・貯蓄不足。\n• consensus:軽度の赤字は問題ではないが、低貯蓄のサインかもしれない。", "example": "Goofus uses his student loan to buy a flat-screen TV (foolishly saving too little); Gallant uses his loan to buy textbooks and coffee for studying (a great place to invest). Both run a trade deficit, but only one builds future wealth.", "whyNeeded": "貿易赤字・黒字の定義と、それが capital flows でどう相殺されるかは international finance の基礎。optimistic/pessimistic の2つの物語は演習で問われる。", "mistakes": ["**trade deficit** を必ず『悪いこと』と決めつける誤り。良い投資先のサインのこともある。", "**imports** と **exports** の大小関係を逆にする誤り。deficit は imports > exports。"], "memorize": "Deficit: imports > exports; Surplus: exports > imports"}, {"id": "c38_balance_of_payments", "ch": 38, "week": 7, "name": "Balance of Payments", "star": true, "scene": "ある国の住民と『世界の残り』との間の経済取引を1年分まとめて記録したい状況。これが **balance of payments**。Week 7 週テストでも定義が問われる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "The balance of payments is a yearly summary of all economic transactions between residents of one country and the rest of the world.", "defEN": "The **balance of payments** is a yearly summary of all the economic transactions between residents of one country and residents of the rest of the world. It is a summary record of a country's economic transactions with the rest of the world.\n\nA key identity is: **Current account + Capital account = Change in official reserves**. A trade deficit plus a capital surplus means the balance of payments nets out to zero. You can finance a trade deficit with current income (a job), a loan, selling assets, or drawing on savings. If earning < spending: Earning - Spending = change in debt + change in assets + change in cash reserves.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**balance of payments**(国際収支)は『その国の住民と世界の残りとの間の、1年間のすべての経済取引のまとめ』です。\n\n--- 基本恒等式 ---\n**Current account + Capital account = Change in official reserves**(公的準備の変化)。\n• trade deficit + capital surplus → 国際収支はゼロにネットアウトする。\n\n--- 赤字のファイナンス手段 ---\n• 現在の所得(仕事)、ローン、資産の売却、過去の貯蓄の取り崩し。\n• earning < spending のとき: Earning − Spending = Δdebt + Δassets + Δcash reserves。", "example": "If the current account = -$10 and the capital account = +$15, then the change in reserves = +$5. If college expenses = $12,000 and barista income = $4,000, the current account = -$8,000 and the capital account = +$8,000 (the balance of payments must balance).", "whyNeeded": "国際収支の定義と『current + capital = change in reserves』の恒等式は週テスト・演習の計算で必出。どこからお金を得たかを必ず帳尻合わせする発想が要る。", "mistakes": ["**balance of payments** を『輸出入の差』だけと誤解する誤り。実際は世界とのすべての取引の記録。", "恒等式で符号(赤字は負、黒字は正)を取り違える誤り。"], "memorize": "BoP = yearly record of all transactions; Current + Capital = change in reserves"}, {"id": "c38_current_vs_capital_account", "ch": 38, "week": 7, "name": "Current Account vs Capital Account", "star": true, "scene": "国際収支を2つの口座に分けて理解する状況。**current account** は今期完了した取引(貿易・利子・送金)、**capital account** は外国による国内資産の所有変化を測る。", "compare": {"a": "Current Account", "b": "Capital Account", "table": [{"dim": "What it measures", "a": "Transactions completed in the current period", "b": "Changes in foreign ownership of domestic assets"}, {"dim": "Component 1", "a": "Balance of trade (exports minus imports of goods and services)", "b": "Financial assets (stocks and bonds)"}, {"dim": "Component 2", "a": "Net income on capital held abroad (interest and dividends)", "b": "Physical assets"}, {"dim": "Component 3", "a": "Net transfer payments (e.g., foreign aid)", "b": "n/a"}, {"dim": "Surplus means", "a": "Earning more than spending abroad", "b": "More investment coming in than going out"}]}, "punchline": "The current account sums trade, net foreign income, and transfers; the capital account measures changes in foreign ownership of domestic assets.", "defEN": "The **current account** is the sum of: (1) the **balance of trade** (exports minus imports of goods and services), (2) **net income on capital held abroad**, including interest and dividends, and (3) **net transfer payments**, such as foreign aid. Items in the current account measure transactions completed in a current period.\n\nThe **capital account** measures changes in foreign ownership of domestic assets. It includes financial assets like stocks and bonds as well as physical assets. When there is more investment going into a country than out, that country is running a **capital account surplus**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**current account**(経常収支)は『今期完了した取引』、**capital account**(資本収支)は『外国による国内資産の所有変化』です。\n\n--- current account の3要素 ---\n1. **balance of trade**(財・サービスの輸出 − 輸入)。\n2. 海外保有資本からの純所得(利子・配当)。\n3. 純移転(foreign aid など)。\n\n--- capital account ---\n• 株・債券などの financial assets と physical assets を含む。\n• 流入 > 流出 なら **capital account surplus**(資本収支黒字)。", "example": "When more investment goes into a country than out, it runs a capital account surplus. A trade deficit (in the current account) is often matched by a capital account surplus that finances it.", "whyNeeded": "国際収支の2つの口座の中身と、互いに相殺し合う関係は international finance の核心。current と capital の混同は試験で減点ポイント。", "mistakes": ["**current account** と **capital account** の中身を入れ替える誤り。貿易や利子・配当は current、資産所有の変化は capital。", "capital account surplus を『輸出超過』と勘違いする誤り。これは投資の流入超過のこと。"], "memorize": "Current = trade + foreign income + transfers; Capital = foreign ownership of assets"}, {"id": "c38_exchange_rate_appreciation_depreciation", "ch": 38, "week": 7, "name": "Exchange Rate, Appreciation, and Depreciation", "star": true, "scene": "ある通貨を別の通貨で買うときの『価格』が **exchange rate** で、円やドルの市場で supply と demand によって決まる状況。価格が上がれば **appreciation**、下がれば **depreciation**。", "compare": {"a": "Appreciation", "b": "Depreciation", "table": [{"dim": "Definition", "a": "Increase in the price of one currency in terms of another", "b": "Decrease in the price of one currency in terms of another"}, {"dim": "Caused by (currency itself)", "a": "Decrease in supply of the currency", "b": "Increase in supply of the currency"}, {"dim": "Caused by (demand side)", "a": "Increase in demand for exports / investment", "b": "Decrease in demand for exports / investment"}, {"dim": "Effect on exports", "a": "Exports become more expensive abroad", "b": "Exports become cheaper (exports rise)"}, {"dim": "Fed increases money supply", "a": "n/a", "b": "Currency depreciates"}]}, "punchline": "An exchange rate is the price of one currency in another; appreciation is a rise in that price and depreciation is a fall.", "defEN": "An **exchange rate** is the price of one currency in another currency, determined by **supply and demand**. The exchange rate is the number of, say, dollars it takes to buy 1 yen.\n\n**Appreciation** is an increase in the price of one currency in terms of another. **Depreciation** is a decrease in the price of one currency in terms of another.\n\nAn increase in the supply of a currency causes it to **depreciate**; a decrease in supply causes it to **appreciate**. An increase in demand for a country's exports, or its desirability for foreign investment, increases the value of its currency.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**exchange rate**(為替レート)は『ある通貨を別の通貨で買う価格』で、**supply and demand** で決まります。\n\n--- 2つの動き ---\n• **appreciation**(増価):ある通貨の価格が上がること。\n• **depreciation**(減価):ある通貨の価格が下がること。\n\n--- 供給・需要 ---\n• 通貨の供給↑ → その通貨は **depreciate**。供給↓ → **appreciate**。\n• 輸出需要↑、または投資先としての魅力↑ → その通貨の価値↑。\n• Fed が money supply を増やす → ドルの supply↑ → ドルは depreciate。", "example": "If the ECB increases the supply of euros, the euro depreciates relative to other currencies. With a floating exchange rate, when the Fed increases the U.S. money supply, the dollar depreciates (e.g., from $0.79 to $0.86 per dollar means appreciation; the reverse is depreciation).", "whyNeeded": "為替レートが supply/demand でどう決まり、増価・減価がどちらの方向かは international finance とマネタリーの橋渡し。floating rate でマネーサプライ増→減価という連鎖が試験で問われる。", "mistakes": ["**appreciation** と **depreciation** を逆にする誤り。価格が上がるのが appreciation。", "通貨の供給を増やすと appreciate すると取り違える誤り。供給↑ → depreciate。"], "memorize": "Appreciation = price up; Depreciation = price down; more supply -> depreciate"}, {"id": "c38_ppp_law_of_one_price", "ch": 38, "week": 7, "name": "Purchasing Power Parity and the Law of One Price", "star": true, "scene": "通貨の価値は『それで何が買えるか』から最終的に決まる、という長期の為替の状況。同じ財は世界中でほぼ同じ価格になるはずという **law of one price** と、その応用である **purchasing power parity** が登場する。", "compare": {"a": "Nominal Exchange Rate", "b": "Real Exchange Rate", "table": [{"dim": "Definition", "a": "The rate at which you can exchange one currency for another", "b": "The rate at which you can exchange the goods and services of one country for those of another"}, {"dim": "Long-run behavior (PPP)", "a": "Adjusts so real purchasing power is equal", "b": "Returns to its fundamental value set by approximate PPP"}, {"dim": "After a permanent increase in M (long run)", "a": "Falls (currency depreciates)", "b": "Unchanged"}, {"dim": "Holds more tightly", "a": "n/a", "b": "In the long run than in the short run"}]}, "punchline": "PPP says the real purchasing power of money should be the same at home or abroad; it is an application of the law of one price.", "defEN": "The **nominal exchange rate** is the rate at which you can exchange one currency for another. The **real exchange rate** is the rate at which you can exchange the goods and services of one country for the goods and services of another.\n\nThe **Purchasing Power Parity (PPP) theorem** says that the real purchasing power of a money should be the same, whether it is spent at home or converted into another currency and spent abroad. The quantity of goods and services obtainable for a given currency should be the same everywhere.\n\nPPP is an application of the **law of one price**: if trade were free, identical goods should sell for about the same price throughout the world. PPP is limited by transportation costs, non-shippable personal services and goods, and tariffs or quotas, and it holds more tightly in the long run than in the short run.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、**purchasing power parity (PPP)**(購買力平価)は『お金の実質購買力は、自国で使っても外貨に換えて外国で使っても同じはず』という定理です。\n\n--- 関連定義 ---\n• **nominal exchange rate**(名目為替レート):通貨どうしを交換するレート。\n• **real exchange rate**(実質為替レート):財・サービスどうしを交換するレート。\n• **law of one price**(一物一価):自由貿易なら同一の財は世界中でほぼ同じ価格になる。PPP はその応用。\n\n--- 限界 ---\n• 輸送費、運べない personal services や財、tariffs/quotas。\n• PPP は短期より **long run** でより強く成立する。\n\n--- 長期の中立性 ---\n• M を恒久的に増やすと、長期では nominal exchange rate は下がるが real exchange rate は不変。", "example": "According to PPP, if Toyotas are cheaper in the U.S., they will be shipped to Japan (or a plant set up in the U.S.), and exchange rates and prices adjust to equalize returns. In the long run the real exchange rate returns to its fundamental value as determined by approximate PPP.", "whyNeeded": "長期の為替決定理論として PPP と law of one price は必須。nominal と real の区別、長期で real rate が PPP に戻る点は試験で頻出。", "mistakes": ["**nominal exchange rate** と **real exchange rate** を混同する誤り。real は財どうしの交換レート。", "PPP が短期でも厳密に成立すると考える誤り。輸送費・関税で制約され、long run でより強く成立。"], "memorize": "PPP: same real purchasing power home or abroad; an application of law of one price"}, {"id": "c38_monetary_policy_open_economy", "ch": 38, "week": 7, "name": "Monetary Policy in an Open Economy", "star": true, "scene": "Fed が M を増やしたとき、為替を通じて輸出と AD がどう動くかを短期・長期で追う状況。短期はドル安→輸出増→AD増、長期はマネーの中立性でインフレだけが上がる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "When the Fed increases M, the dollar depreciates and exports rise in the short run, but in the long run only inflation rises because money is neutral.", "defEN": "Suppose the Fed increases **M**. In the **short run**: the supply curve for dollars shifts to the right, the dollar **depreciates**, a depreciation raises **exports**, and higher exports raise **aggregate demand** and the real GDP growth rate.\n\nIn the **long run**: because **money is neutral**, the only thing that happens is that inflation rises (remember the Quantity Theory of Money). Domestic prices rise, the **nominal exchange rate** falls, and the **real exchange rate** has not changed. This is what causes the real growth rate to return to its long-run level after the money supply is increased: **inflation**.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、Fed が **M** を増やすと、短期はドル安で輸出が増え AD が上がりますが、長期はマネーの中立性でインフレだけが上がります。\n\n--- 短期 ---\n• ドルの供給曲線が右にシフト → ドルが **depreciate**。\n• ドル安 → **exports**↑ → **aggregate demand**↑ → real GDP 成長率↑。\n\n--- 長期 ---\n• **money is neutral**(貨幣の中立性)なので、起きるのは π(インフレ)上昇だけ。\n• 国内物価↑、**nominal exchange rate**↓、**real exchange rate** は不変。\n• マネー増加後に成長率が長期水準へ戻る原因は **inflation**。", "example": "Suppose the Fed increases M: in the short run the economy moves from a to b (4% inflation, 6% growth). In the long run, domestic prices rise, the nominal exchange rate falls, the real exchange rate is unchanged, and inflation rises to 7% while growth returns to 3%.", "whyNeeded": "monetary policy と international finance を結ぶ最重要リンク。短期の為替チャネル(ドル安→輸出増)と長期の中立性(インフレだけ)の区別が試験で問われる。", "mistakes": ["M 増加で長期も real GDP が高いままと考える誤り。long run は money neutral でインフレだけ上がる。", "Fed が M を増やすとドルが appreciate すると取り違える誤り。supply↑ → depreciate。"], "memorize": "More M: short run dollar depreciates, exports & AD up; long run only inflation up"}, {"id": "c38_budget_deficit_trade_deficit", "ch": 38, "week": 7, "name": "Twin Deficits: Budget Deficit to Trade Deficit", "star": true, "scene": "政府が予算赤字をファイナンスするために借入を増やすと、金利・資本フロー・為替を通じて貿易赤字につながる状況。Week 7 演習の連鎖問題で問われる。", "compare": null, "punchline": "Budget deficits raise interest rates, attract net capital inflow, cause currency appreciation, and thereby reduce net exports.", "defEN": "When the U.S. government borrows to finance its budget deficits, the dollar will **appreciate** and U.S. imports will increase.\n\nThe mechanism: **budget deficits** lead to higher interest rates, which lead to **net capital inflow**, which leads to **currency appreciation**, thus reducing **net exports** (a trade deficit). A stronger currency makes imports cheaper (imports increase) and exports more expensive.", "defJA": "めちゃくちゃ簡単に言うと、政府が予算赤字を借入でまかなうと、最終的に貿易赤字につながります(twin deficits)。\n\n--- 連鎖メカニズム ---\n1. **budget deficits**(予算赤字)→ 金利↑(higher interest rates)。\n2. 金利↑ → **net capital inflow**(純資本流入)。\n3. 資本流入 → **currency appreciation**(通貨増価)。\n4. 増価 → **net exports**↓(輸出は割高、輸入は割安で増加)→ 貿易赤字。\n\n--- 結論 ---\n• ドルは appreciate し、U.S. imports は increase する。", "example": "If the U.S. government borrows to finance its budget deficits, the dollar appreciates and U.S. imports increase. Budget deficits raise interest rates, which cause net capital inflow, currency appreciation, and reduced net exports.", "whyNeeded": "財政赤字→貿易赤字の連鎖(higher rates → capital inflow → appreciation → lower net exports)は演習の定番チェーン。各ステップの向きを正確に追う必要がある。", "mistakes": ["budget deficit が金利を『下げる』と取り違える誤り。借入増で金利は上がる。", "資本流入で通貨が depreciate すると取り違える誤り。資本流入は appreciation を招く。"], "memorize": "Budget deficit -> higher rates -> capital inflow -> appreciation -> lower net exports"}];
window.TB_GLOSSARY=[{"term": "Ability Risk", "def": "他人の能力という本人が制御できないリスク。tournament が追加する。"}, {"term": "Adverse Selection", "def": "売り手の申し出自体が商品の負の情報を伝えること(hidden characteristics)。lemons market が代表。"}, {"term": "Aggregate Demand (AD)", "def": "総需要。money supply の変化が影響する。M↑→AD↑。"}, {"term": "Aggregate Demand Curve", "def": "総需要曲線。支出の伸び M + v を一定にしたときのインフレ率と実質成長率の全組み合わせ。右下がり。"}, {"term": "Aggregate Demand Shock", "def": "総需要ショック。AD 曲線をシフト。正なら短期に成長とインフレ両方↑、長期はインフレのみ↑。"}, {"term": "Amplification", "def": "増幅。小さな初期ショックが産出・雇用・投資に大きな効果を生む理由。"}, {"term": "Antitrust Law", "def": "独占禁止法。カルテル摘発・合併阻止・巨大企業分割に使われる。"}, {"term": "Appreciation", "def": "増価。ある通貨の価格が他通貨で見て上がること。供給↓や輸出需要↑で起きる。"}, {"term": "Arguments Against Free Trade", "def": "自由貿易への反対論。saving domestic jobs・child labor・national security・key industries。利益は集中しコストは分散するため保護が残る。"}, {"term": "Asymmetric Information", "def": "取引の一方が相手より多く・良い情報を持つ状態。情報の少ない side が取引を危険と感じ撤退しうる。"}, {"term": "Backward-Bending Labor Supply", "def": "income effect が substitution effect を上回ると、賃上げで労働時間が減る後方屈曲の労働供給曲線。"}, {"term": "Balance of Payments", "def": "国際収支。ある国の住民と世界の残りとの1年間の全経済取引の記録。Current+Capital=Change in reserves。"}, {"term": "Budget Constraint", "def": "所得と価格のもとで買える消費バンドル全体。Px·X + Py·Y ≤ I。"}, {"term": "Budget Line", "def": "予算制約の境界線。例: 10X + 2Y = 100。所得増で平行シフト、価格低下で回転。"}, {"term": "Capital Account", "def": "資本収支。外国による国内資産(株・債券・実物資産)所有の変化。流入超過なら capital account surplus。"}, {"term": "Capital Surplus", "def": "資本黒字。外国資本の流入が国内資本の流出を上回る状態。trade deficit を相殺する capital inflow。"}, {"term": "Cartel", "def": "カルテル。供給を絞り価格と利潤を上げて独占を真似る寡占の集団。崩壊しやすい。"}, {"term": "Catching-up growth", "def": "追いつき成長。capital accumulation による成長。収穫逓減のため steady state で止まる。"}, {"term": "Central Bank", "def": "中央銀行。money supply(の成長率)を決め、aggregate demand を通じて景気とインフレに影響する機関(ECB, Fed, De Nederlandsche Bank など)。"}, {"term": "Choice Architecture", "def": "選択肢の提示・設計の仕方。framing 次第で行動が大きく変わる。"}, {"term": "Coase Theorem", "def": "コースの定理。transaction costs が低く property rights が明確なら、外部性があっても私的交渉で効率的な均衡に至る。"}, {"term": "Collateral Damage", "def": "担保ショック。資産価格下落→信用縮小→支出減→さらに資産価格下落の悪循環(financial accelerator)。"}, {"term": "Commodity Tax", "def": "物品税。燃料・タバコ・酒などの財にかかる税。売り手・買い手どちらに課しても効果は同じ。"}, {"term": "Comparative Advantage", "def": "比較優位。専門化を通じ生産性を高め貿易の利益を生む原理。"}, {"term": "Compensating Differential", "def": "補償賃金差。労働条件の差を埋め合わせる賃金差。危険な仕事ほど高給。"}, {"term": "Competition for the Market", "def": "市場を取るための競争。ネットワーク財では市場の中でなく市場そのものを巡って競う。"}, {"term": "Consumer Price Index (CPI)", "def": "消費者物価指数。平均的な物価水準を測る指標。インフレ率は CPI の変化率。"}, {"term": "Consumption (C)", "def": "消費。最終財・サービスへの民間支出。"}, {"term": "Contestable Market", "def": "コンテスタブル市場。潜在的参入の脅威だけで市場が競争的に振る舞う市場。"}, {"term": "Coordination Game", "def": "調整ゲーム。同じ戦略を選ぶほうが互いに得だが、合わせる先が複数あるゲーム。"}, {"term": "Cross-Price Elasticity of Demand", "def": "需要の交差価格弾力性。財 x の需要量が財 y の価格変化にどれだけ反応するか。(ΔQxd/Qxd)÷(ΔPy/Py)。"}, {"term": "Current Account", "def": "経常収支。balance of trade + 海外資本からの純所得(利子・配当)+ 純移転(foreign aid)。"}, {"term": "Cutting-edge growth", "def": "先端成長。better ideas による成長。長期でも経済を成長させ続けられる。"}, {"term": "Cyclical Unemployment", "def": "循環的失業。景気循環・不況が原因の失業。"}, {"term": "Deadweight Loss (DWL)", "def": "死荷重。税・補助金・価格統制で失われる gains from trade。需要・供給が more elastic なほど大きい。"}, {"term": "Deflation", "def": "デフレ。物価水準が実際に下がること(インフレ率がマイナス)。"}, {"term": "Delta (δ)", "def": "資本のうち摩耗・減耗する割合(減耗率)。例: δ = 2/100 = 0.02。"}, {"term": "Depreciation", "def": "減耗。資本の摩耗。δK。資本ストックが大きいほど大きくなり、linear(線形)に増える。"}, {"term": "Determinants of Elasticity", "def": "弾力性の決定要因。substitutes が多い・long run・specific brands・luxuries・予算割合が大きいほど more elastic。"}, {"term": "Diminishing returns", "def": "収穫逓減。資本を増やすと産出は増えるが、その増え方はだんだん小さくなる。"}, {"term": "Discouraged Workers", "def": "求職をあきらめた人。働く意欲はあるが探すのをやめた人。労働力に含まれない。"}, {"term": "Disinflation", "def": "ディスインフレ。インフレ率が下がるがまだプラス(物価は上昇継続だが鈍化)。"}, {"term": "Dominant Strategy", "def": "支配戦略。相手が何を選んでも最善となる戦略(例: Cheat, Talk)。"}, {"term": "Double counting", "def": "二重計上。中間財と最終財を両方数えてしまう誤り。final goods のみ数えることで回避する。"}, {"term": "Economies of Scale", "def": "規模の経済。生産量が増えるほど平均費用が下がる大規模生産の利点。"}, {"term": "Elastic Demand", "def": "弾力的需要。|E|>1。価格変化に需要量が大きく反応し、価格と total revenue は逆方向に動く。"}, {"term": "Elasticity of Demand", "def": "需要の弾力性。非弾力的(inelastic)なほど独占の markup が大きい。"}, {"term": "Environment Risk", "def": "景気やガソリン価格など、全員に共通で本人が制御できない外部リスク。tournament が隔離する。"}, {"term": "Excess Reserves", "def": "超過準備。銀行が required を超えて保有する準備。多いと money multiplier は下がる。"}, {"term": "Exchange Rate", "def": "為替レート。ある通貨を別の通貨で買う価格。supply と demand で決まる。"}, {"term": "External Benefit (Positive Externality)", "def": "外部便益(正の外部性)。当事者以外が得る便益。例: ワクチンの underuse。Social benefit = private benefit + external benefit。"}, {"term": "External Cost (Negative Externality)", "def": "外部費用(負の外部性)。当事者以外が払う費用。例: 抗生物質の overuse。Social cost = private cost + external cost。"}, {"term": "Externality", "def": "外部性。取引の当事者でない bystanders にかかる費用・便益。市場価格が真の費用便益を示さず非効率になる。"}, {"term": "Factor income approach", "def": "要素所得アプローチ。GDP を所得の側から積み上げる Y = Employee Compensation + Rent + Interest + Profit。sales taxes の調整が必要。"}, {"term": "Final goods", "def": "最終財。最終利用者に売られ消費・在庫保有される財。GDP に含めるのはこれだけ(double counting 回避のため)。"}, {"term": "Financial Accelerator", "def": "金融加速器。担保価値の低下が借入・支出を減らし下降を増幅するフィードバック。"}, {"term": "Fisher Effect", "def": "フィッシャー効果。名目利子率は予想インフレに応じて上がる。i = E(pi) + r_equilibrium。"}, {"term": "Forward Guidance", "def": "フォワードガイダンス。将来の政策方針を伝えて expectations を動かす手法。"}, {"term": "Frictional Unemployment", "def": "摩擦的失業。転職・引っ越しに伴う短期の求職による失業。"}, {"term": "Friedman Rule", "def": "フリードマン・ルール。Fisher 効果の特殊例として演習に登場(後の章で詳述)。"}, {"term": "Gamma (γ)", "def": "産出のうち新規資本に投資される割合(投資率)。例: γ = 3/10 = 0.3。"}, {"term": "GDP Deflator", "def": "GDPデフレーター。(Nominal GDP ÷ Real GDP) × 100 で求める price index。inflation を測る。100 を超えた分が基準年からのインフレ率。"}, {"term": "GDP growth rate", "def": "GDP成長率。(GDP今年 − GDP前年) ÷ GDP前年 × 100。生産の増減の速さを示す。"}, {"term": "GDP per capita", "def": "一人当たりGDP。GDP ÷ population。生活水準(standard of living)のざっくりした目安。"}, {"term": "Government purchases (G)", "def": "政府購入。各レベルの政府の最終財・サービス支出。transfers(移転支出)は含まない。"}, {"term": "Gross Domestic Product (GDP)", "def": "国内総生産。1年間に一国内で生産されたすべての final goods and services の market value(市場価値)の合計。"}, {"term": "Hidden Action", "def": "moral hazard の別名。行動が相手に見えないことに起因する情報問題。"}, {"term": "Hidden Characteristics", "def": "adverse selection の別名。商品/相手の隠れた特性に起因する情報問題。"}, {"term": "Human Capital", "def": "人的資本。生産性を高める『頭の中の道具』。education・training・experience への投資。"}, {"term": "Human capital (eL)", "def": "人的資本。education(e)× Labor(L)。教育で増強された労働。"}, {"term": "Ideas (A)", "def": "アイデア・技術。生産性(productivity)を高め、K 一定でも産出を増やす。Y = A√K で上方シフトを生む。"}, {"term": "Import Tariff", "def": "輸入関税。輸入品への税。国内価格↑・国内生産↑・国内消費↓・輸入↓・政府収入(tariff rate×import quantity)・DWL を生む。"}, {"term": "Income Effect", "def": "価格変化による purchasing power(購買力)の変化が引き起こす消費の変化。"}, {"term": "Income Elasticity of Demand", "def": "需要の所得弾力性。(ΔQd/Qd)÷(ΔI/I)。所得変化に対する需要量の反応度。"}, {"term": "Indifference Curve", "def": "同じ utility を与える消費バンドルを結んだ曲線。"}, {"term": "Inelastic Demand", "def": "非弾力的需要。|E|<1。需要量の反応が小さく、価格と total revenue は同方向に動く。食料が典型。"}, {"term": "Inflation", "def": "インフレ。物価水準の上昇。GDP deflator − 100 で基準年からのインフレ率を計算できる。"}, {"term": "Inflation Targeting", "def": "インフレ目標。固定インフレ目標下で negative real shock が来ると AD を左にシフトさせる。"}, {"term": "Intermediate goods", "def": "中間財。企業に売られ後工程で加工・bundle される財。GDP に二重計上しないため別個には含めない。"}, {"term": "Internalizing Externalities", "def": "外部性の内部化。私的+社会的な費用便益を意思決定に織り込むよう誘因を調整すること。"}, {"term": "International Trade", "def": "国際貿易。国境を越える取引。preferences の差・specialization・comparative advantage で利益を生む。"}, {"term": "Intertemporal Substitution", "def": "異時点間の代替。努力・消費・投資を時間を通じて配分すること。ブームで多く働き不況で少なく働く。"}, {"term": "Intrinsic Motivation", "def": "内発的動機。金銭報酬がこれを crowd out(締め出す)ことがある(子どもの家事の例)。"}, {"term": "Investment (I)", "def": "投資。将来の産出を生む道具・工場・設備への民間支出。"}, {"term": "Investment rate", "def": "投資率。高いほど資本・産出が多く、steady-state の GDP 水準が上がる(ただし長期成長率は上げない)。"}, {"term": "Irreversible Investment", "def": "不可逆投資。sunk cost を伴い元に戻せない投資。不確実だと wait-and-see で凍結。"}, {"term": "Labor Adjustment Costs", "def": "労働調整コスト。雇用を増減させるコスト。高いほど負のショックで失業が増える。"}, {"term": "Labor Force", "def": "労働力。就業者 + 仕事を探している成人。専業主婦・学生・退職者・求職放棄者は含まない。"}, {"term": "Law of One Price", "def": "一物一価。自由貿易なら同一の財は世界中でほぼ同じ価格になるはず。"}, {"term": "Lemons", "def": "中古車市場の低品質車。本文では value = $8,000。"}, {"term": "Lock-in", "def": "ロックイン。市場が劣った製品・ネットワークに固定されること(例: QWERTY)。"}, {"term": "Long-Run Aggregate Supply (LRAS)", "def": "長期総供給曲線。Solow growth rate の所に立つ垂直線。インフレ率と独立。potential output を表す。"}, {"term": "LRAS", "def": "長期総供給。real shock で左にシフトする。Solow 成長率に対応。"}, {"term": "Marginal Cost (MC)", "def": "限界費用。1単位多く売ったときの総費用の変化。利潤最大化条件は MR = MC。"}, {"term": "Marginal product of capital (MPK)", "def": "資本の限界生産物。資本を1単位追加したときの産出の増加。資本が増えるほど diminishes(逓減)する。"}, {"term": "Marginal Product of Labor (MPL)", "def": "労働の限界生産物。労働需要の基礎。雇用条件は MPL ≥ w、均衡で MPL = W。"}, {"term": "Marginal Rate of Substitution (MRS)", "def": "無差別なまま一方の財を他方とどれだけ交換するか。= 無差別曲線の傾きの絶対値。最適で = Pa/Pb。"}, {"term": "Marginal Revenue (MR)", "def": "限界収入。1単位多く売ったときの総収入の変化 ΔTR/ΔQ。独占では MR < P。"}, {"term": "Marginal Revenue Product of Labor (MRPL)", "def": "労働の限界収入生産物。追加労働者が生む収入増。金銭表示の MPL と同じ。"}, {"term": "Marginal Utility", "def": "限界効用。追加1単位の消費による utility の変化。MUa は財Aの限界効用。"}, {"term": "Market Failure", "def": "良質中古車が取引されない等、市場が効率的な結果を出せない状態。adverse selection の帰結。"}, {"term": "Market Power", "def": "市場支配力。他社の参入を恐れず価格を限界費用より上げられる力(P > MC)。"}, {"term": "Market value", "def": "市場価値。価値の異なる財を共通の尺度で合計するため、各財を市場価格で評価したもの。"}, {"term": "Markup", "def": "上乗せ幅。価格が限界費用を超える部分。需要が inelastic ほど大きい。"}, {"term": "Menu Costs", "def": "メニューコスト。値札変更・システム更新などのコスト。価格が即調整されない理由(sticky prices)。"}, {"term": "Minimum Wage", "def": "最低賃金。均衡賃金より高い labor market の price floor。労働の surplus(失業)と DWL を生む。"}, {"term": "Misallocation of Resources", "def": "資源の誤配分。価格統制下で資源が最高価値の用途に流れない状態。"}, {"term": "Misperception Theory", "def": "誤認理論。企業が全体の物価上昇を自社製品の相対価格上昇と誤認し増産すること。"}, {"term": "Monetary Base (MB)", "def": "マネタリーベース。これが増えても貸出を通じてしか M1・M2 は増えない。"}, {"term": "Money Multiplier (MM)", "def": "貨幣乗数。1/reserve ratio。準備の増加が預金を何倍に膨らませるか。現実で約3。"}, {"term": "Money Neutrality", "def": "貨幣の中立性。長期では M 増は P(インフレ)だけ上げ、実質GDPは増えない。短期は中立でない。"}, {"term": "Money Supply", "def": "マネーサプライ。経済に出回るお金の量。中央銀行が成長率に影響を与える。"}, {"term": "Monopolistic Competition", "def": "独占的競争。多数の売り手・自由参入・製品差別化を持つ市場。長期で P = AC。"}, {"term": "Monopoly", "def": "独占。market power を持つ単一企業。右下がりの需要曲線に直面する。"}, {"term": "Monopsony", "def": "需要独占(単一雇用主)。労働の唯一の買い手。最低賃金の失業効果が競争市場と異なる。"}, {"term": "Moral Hazard", "def": "契約成立後に agent が情報優位を不正・好ましくない形で悪用すること(hidden action)。保険加入者が不注意になる等。"}, {"term": "Nash Equilibrium", "def": "ナッシュ均衡。どのプレイヤーも単独(unilaterally)では戦略を変える誘因がない状態。"}, {"term": "National spending approach", "def": "支出アプローチ。GDP を支出の側から分解する Y = C + I + G + NX。"}, {"term": "Natural Monopoly", "def": "自然独占。1社が市場全体を2社以上より低コストで供給できる状態(水道・ガス等)。"}, {"term": "Net exports (NX)", "def": "純輸出。輸出の価値 − 輸入の価値。"}, {"term": "Network Effects", "def": "ネットワーク効果。利用者が増えるほど価値が高まる効果。独占の源泉の一つ。"}, {"term": "Network Good", "def": "ネットワーク財。使う人が増えるほど各人にとって価値が上がる財(Facebook, TikTok)。"}, {"term": "New growth theory", "def": "新成長理論。成長が technological innovation(技術革新)から生じるとする理論。"}, {"term": "Nominal Exchange Rate", "def": "名目為替レート。通貨どうしを交換するレート。長期で M 増→下がる。"}, {"term": "Nominal GDP", "def": "名目GDP。販売時点の価格(current prices)で計算した GDP。価格変化を調整していない。"}, {"term": "Nominal Interest Rate", "def": "名目利子率 i。インフレ調整前の利子率。i = E(pi) + r_equilibrium。"}, {"term": "Nominal variables", "def": "名目変数。GDP のように価格変化を調整していない変数。"}, {"term": "Non-rivalrous", "def": "非競合的。ある人の財の消費が他人の消費を妨げないこと。ideas はこの性質を持つ。"}, {"term": "Nudge", "def": "選択肢を禁止せず経済的誘因も大きく変えずに行動を予測可能に変える choice architecture の工夫。"}, {"term": "Oligopoly", "def": "寡占。少数の企業に支配される産業。価格は競争より高く独占より低い。"}, {"term": "Open Market Operations (OMOs)", "def": "公開市場操作。government bonds を売買して money supply と短期金利を調整する。buy→流動性注入・金利↓。"}, {"term": "Persuasive Advertising", "def": "説得的広告。ブランド差別化により市場支配力を生む広告。差別化企業が最も使う。"}, {"term": "Physical capital (K)", "def": "物的資本。生産に使う資本ストック。消費されず貯蓄・投資された産出。"}, {"term": "Piece Rate", "def": "出来高払い。output に直接支払う方式。output が測りやすいとき有効、品質が測りにくいとき不向き。"}, {"term": "Pigouvian Tax / Subsidy", "def": "ピグー税・補助金。負の外部性には Pigouvian tax、正の外部性には Pigouvian subsidy で外部性を内部化する。"}, {"term": "Plums", "def": "中古車市場の高品質車。本文では value = $12,000。期待価格$10,000では売られず取引が消える。"}, {"term": "Policy Interest Rate", "def": "政策金利。中央銀行が設定する鍵となる金利で、経済の他のすべての金利に波及する。lower rates→AD↑。"}, {"term": "Price Ceiling", "def": "価格上限(最高価格)。市場価格より下だと拘束的で Qd>Qs となり shortage を生む。品質低下・行列・賄賂も発生。"}, {"term": "Price Controls", "def": "価格統制。価格が最高(price ceiling)や最低(price floor)を越えるのを違法にする法律。市場シグナルに干渉する。"}, {"term": "Price Elasticity of Demand (Epd)", "def": "需要の価格弾力性。%ΔQd ÷ %ΔP で、価格変化に対する需要量の反応度。|E|>1 で elastic、|E|<1 で inelastic、|E|=1 で unit elastic。"}, {"term": "Price Elasticity of Supply (Eps)", "def": "供給の価格弾力性。(ΔQs/Qs)÷(ΔP/P)。toothpick は elastic、oil・gold は単位コスト急増で inelastic。"}, {"term": "Price Floor", "def": "価格下限(最低価格)。市場価格より上だと拘束的で Qs>Qd となり surplus を生む。過剰な品質競争も発生。"}, {"term": "Principal-Agent Problem", "def": "情報を持つ agent(代理人)を principal(依頼人)の利益のため働かせるにはどうするかという問題。患者と歯科医など。"}, {"term": "Prisoner's Dilemma", "def": "囚人のジレンマ。各自の自己利益追求が全員に望ましくない結果を招くゲーム。"}, {"term": "Product Differentiation", "def": "製品差別化。似ているが同一でない製品。味・スタイル・機能・立地で差別化。"}, {"term": "Production function", "def": "生産関数。産出と生産要素の関係を表す式。Y = F(A, K, eL)。"}, {"term": "Profit Maximization", "def": "利潤最大化。独占の条件は MR = MC。π = TR − TC = (P − AC)Q。"}, {"term": "Purchasing Power Parity (PPP)", "def": "購買力平価。お金の実質購買力は自国でも外国でも同じはず、という定理。law of one price の応用。"}, {"term": "Quantitative Easing (QE)", "def": "量的緩和。金利がゼロ近辺のとき、long-term bonds などを大量購入してお金を直接注入し長期金利を下げる。"}, {"term": "Quantity Theory of Money", "def": "貨幣数量説。Mv = PYR。v と Y がほぼ一定なら M 増は P 増を招く。動学版は M + v = P + YR。"}, {"term": "Real (Supply) Shock", "def": "実質/供給ショック。資本・労働の生産性やアイデアの流れを変える出来事(戦争・新技術・石油供給減)。LRAS をシフト。"}, {"term": "Real Exchange Rate", "def": "実質為替レート。財・サービスどうしを交換するレート。長期で PPP の値に戻る。"}, {"term": "Real GDP", "def": "実質GDP。すべての年で同じ(基準年の)価格を使って価格変化の影響を除いた GDP。"}, {"term": "Real Interest Rate", "def": "実質利子率 rreal。名目からインフレを引いたもの。rreal = i - pi。"}, {"term": "Real Price", "def": "実質価格。インフレ調整済みの価格。"}, {"term": "Real Shock", "def": "実物ショック。LRAS を左にシフトさせ、インフレ↑・成長↓を招く。金融政策のジレンマ。"}, {"term": "Real variables", "def": "実質変数。すべての期間で同じ価格を使って価格変化を調整した変数。"}, {"term": "Reserve Ratio", "def": "準備率。reserves ÷ deposits。$10の預金に$1なら0.1。money multiplier の逆数。"}, {"term": "Reserve Requirement", "def": "準備率規制。銀行が預金のうち貸さずに準備として持つべき割合。ECB は1%。"}, {"term": "Short-Run Aggregate Supply (SRAS)", "def": "短期総供給曲線。賃金・物価が sticky なため右上がり。各曲線は予想インフレ E(pi) に対応。"}, {"term": "Shortage", "def": "不足。price ceiling 下で Qd > Qs となる状態。"}, {"term": "Signal", "def": "情報を明らかにするためにとられる expensive action(高コストな行動)。嘘なら割に合わないため信頼できる。"}, {"term": "Signaling", "def": "情報を伝えるためにコストのかかる行動(signal)をとること。Hyundai の warranty、大学の学位など。"}, {"term": "Signaling Theory", "def": "シグナリング理論。学位はスキルでなく知性・誠実さを示すから高賃金になるとする説。"}, {"term": "Slope vs Elasticity", "def": "傾きと弾力性は別物。直線需要曲線では slope は一定でも elasticity は点ごとに変化し、flatter ほど more elastic。"}, {"term": "Solow Growth Rate", "def": "ソロー成長率。物価が伸縮的で既存の生産要素が与えられたときの経済の成長率。K, L, A で決まる。"}, {"term": "Solow model", "def": "ソロー成長モデル。なぜ GDP が成長する/しないか、成長の限界はどこかを説明する基本モデル。生産関数 Y = F(A, K, eL) から始める。"}, {"term": "Spillovers", "def": "波及効果。アイデアが他の企業・消費者に漏れ出すこと。発案者が便益を十分得られないと ideas は underprovided(過少供給)になる。"}, {"term": "SRAS", "def": "短期総供給。Inflation = Expected inflation + 1×(Real growth − Potential growth)。"}, {"term": "Stagflation", "def": "スタグフレーション。不況と高インフレの併存(1970年代半ば)。negative real shock が原因。"}, {"term": "Standard Wars", "def": "標準争い。ネットワーク財で支配的標準の座を巡る競争。"}, {"term": "Statistical Discrimination", "def": "統計的差別。集団平均の情報で個人を判断すること。完全情報下では消える。"}, {"term": "Steady-state level of capital", "def": "定常状態の資本。資本ストックが増えも減りもしない水準。investment = depreciation の点で net investment がゼロになり成長が止まる。"}, {"term": "Sticky Prices", "def": "価格の硬直性。価格が硬直的なほど M の増加が real output を押し上げ、金融政策が効きやすい。"}, {"term": "Sticky Wages", "def": "粘着賃金。契約・慣習で賃金がすぐ調整されないこと。SRAS が右上がりになる主因。"}, {"term": "Stock Options", "def": "株価が一定価格を超えたときだけ価値が出る報酬。CEO の努力を促す一方、決算操作の不正も誘発した。"}, {"term": "Strong Incentive Scheme", "def": "報酬を成果に強く連動させる制度。払う対象が正しければ良いが、間違うと weak より悪い。"}, {"term": "Structural Unemployment", "def": "構造的失業。スキルと求人のミスマッチ(技術・産業変化、例: ロボット置換)による失業。"}, {"term": "Subsidy", "def": "補助金。逆の税。政府が消費者・生産者に金を渡し取引量を増やすが、価値<費用の生産で waste(DWL)を生む。"}, {"term": "Substitution Effect", "def": "relative price(相対価格)の変化が引き起こす消費の変化。utility を一定に保って測る。"}, {"term": "Surplus", "def": "余剰(過剰供給)。price floor 下で Qs > Qd となる状態。"}, {"term": "Switching Costs", "def": "乗り換え費用。既存企業が上げて市場の contestability を下げようとする。"}, {"term": "Tacit Collusion", "def": "暗黙の共謀。明示的合意や連絡なしに企業が競争を制限すること。"}, {"term": "Taste-Based Discrimination", "def": "嗜好に基づく差別。特定集団への嫌悪。employers・customers・employees による。"}, {"term": "Tax Incidence", "def": "税の帰着。実際に税を負担するのは誰か。relative elasticities で決まり、less elastic な側が多く負担(Elastic = escape)。"}, {"term": "Tax Revenue", "def": "税収 = 税額 × 取引量。政府への transfer であり deadweight loss とは区別する。"}, {"term": "Tax Wedge", "def": "税のくさび。Tax = 買い手が払う価格 − 売り手が受け取る価格。需給曲線の縦の差として図で読む。"}, {"term": "Time Bunching", "def": "時間的集中。他者と行動を合わせ活動が同時期に集中。景気の山谷を増幅。"}, {"term": "Total Revenue (TR)", "def": "総収入 = Price × Quantity。elastic なら値下げで増え、inelastic なら値上げで増える。"}, {"term": "Total Surplus", "def": "総余剰。consumer surplus + producer surplus。独占はこれを減らす。"}, {"term": "Tournament", "def": "相対成績(relative performance)で報酬を決める方式。environment risk を除き ability risk を加える。"}, {"term": "Tradable Allowances", "def": "取引可能な排出枠。排出権を売買させ、最小総費用で汚染を削減する政府の解決策。"}, {"term": "Trade Deficit", "def": "貿易赤字。imports が exports を上回る状態。capital inflow で相殺される。"}, {"term": "Trade Surplus", "def": "貿易黒字。exports が imports を上回る状態。"}, {"term": "Transaction Costs", "def": "取引費用。合意に至るまでの全費用(相手探し・交渉・契約作成など)。多くの外部性では高くなりがち。"}, {"term": "Transmission Mechanism", "def": "伝播メカニズム。ショックを時間・部門を通じて広げ増幅する仕組み。"}, {"term": "Underemployed", "def": "不完全就業者。フルタイム希望のパート等。employed に数えるので失業率を上げない。"}, {"term": "Unemployment Rate", "def": "失業率。失業者 ÷ labor force × 100。discouraged workers や学生は除外。"}, {"term": "Unit Elastic", "def": "単位弾力的。|E|=1。価格が変わっても total revenue は変わらない。"}, {"term": "Utility Maximization Rule", "def": "効用最大化条件: MUa/Pa = MUb/Pb = … = MUz/Pz、かつ所得を全て使う。"}, {"term": "Velocity of Money", "def": "貨幣の流通速度 v。最終財・サービスに1ドルが1年に使われる平均回数。v = PY/M。"}, {"term": "Warranty", "def": "保証。adverse selection への対策であり、品質への本気度を伝える signal にもなる。"}, {"term": "World Price", "def": "世界価格。国が貿易を開いた際に直面する国際市場の価格。"}];
window.EXAM_PROBLEMS=[{"id": "ep_w1_1", "week": 1, "title": "Externality, Tax and Deadweight Loss (Bathroom Cleaners)", "badge": "Week 1 Practice 1", "scenario": "The market for bathroom cleaners is given by the demand and supply equations below, where P is the price in dollars and Q is quantity in thousands. When washed down the drain, the cleaners cause environmental poisoning, so each container carries an external cost of $3. The government considers a $3 tax on producers.", "transactions": ["Qd = 24 - 2P", "Qs = -4 + 2P", "External cost per container = $3", "Proposed Pigouvian tax on producers = $3, shifting supply to Qs = -4 + 2(P - 3)"], "questions": ["(a) What are the market price and market quantity in the bathroom cleaner market?", "(b) What is the social cost of this quantity of bathroom cleaner?", "(c) After the $3 tax, what is the efficient quantity traded?", "(e) What is the dollar amount of the deadweight loss removed from this market as a result of the tax?"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) Market equilibrium</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Set Qd = Qs:\n24 - 2P = -4 + 2P\n28 = 4P\nP = 7\nQ = 24 - 2(7) = 10\nMarket price = $7, market quantity = 10 (thousand) units.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b) Social cost</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Social cost = private cost + external cost\n= $7 + $3 = $10 per unit.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c) Efficient quantity after $3 tax</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">New supply: Qs = -4 + 2(P - 3)\nSet Qd = new Qs:\n24 - 2P = -4 + 2(P - 3)\n24 - 2P = -4 + 2P - 6\n34 = 4P\nP = 8.5\nEfficient price = $8.50, efficient quantity = 24 - 2(8.5) = 7.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(e) Deadweight loss removed</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">The tax removes the over-produced units (from Q = 10 down to Q = 7), where external cost exceeds value.\nDWL removed = (1/2) x base x height = (3 x 3)/2 = $4.50.</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w1_2", "week": 1, "title": "Elasticity Calculations: Demand and Supply", "badge": "Week 1 Practice 2", "scenario": "Two quick elasticity calculations drawn from the Chapter 5 exercises and Weekly Test 1. Use Elasticity = (% change in quantity) / (% change in price), and judge whether the result is elastic or inelastic.", "transactions": ["Baseball tickets: price rises 15%, quantity sold falls 5%.", "Cocoa: price rises 20%, quantity supplied rises 4%."], "questions": ["(a) What is the price elasticity of demand for Major League Baseball tickets, and is demand elastic or inelastic?", "(b) What is the price elasticity of supply for cocoa, and is supply elastic or inelastic?"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) Price elasticity of demand (baseball tickets)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Epd = %ΔQd / %ΔP = (-5%) / (15%) = -1/3 ≈ -0.33\n|E| = 0.33 < 1 -> demand is INELASTIC.\n(Matches Exercise Ch5 Q4, answer b: -1/3.)</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b) Price elasticity of supply (cocoa)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Eps = %ΔQs / %ΔP = (4%) / (20%) = 0.2\n|E| = 0.2 < 1 -> supply is INELASTIC.\n(Matches Weekly Test 1 Q1, answer c: 0.2.)</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">Common trap</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Do not invert the ratio: 20/4 = 5 is wrong. The cause (price, 20%) goes in the denominator, the effect (quantity, 4%) in the numerator: 4/20 = 0.2.</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w2_1", "week": 2, "title": "Monopoly Profit Maximization & Deadweight Loss", "badge": "Week 2 Practice ①", "scenario": "A monopolist's demand curve is P = 50 − 0.5Q, with marginal revenue MR = 50 − Q. Marginal cost is constant at MC = $5 and there are no fixed costs.", "transactions": ["Demand: P = 50 − 0.5Q", "Marginal revenue: MR = 50 − Q", "Marginal cost: MC = $5 (constant)", "No fixed costs"], "questions": ["(a) Find the profit-maximizing quantity and price.", "(b) Compute the monopolist's profit.", "(c) Compute the deadweight loss relative to the competitive (P = MC) outcome."], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) Profit-maximizing Q and P</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Profit max where MR = MC:\n50 − Q = 5  →  Q* = 45\nP* = 50 − 0.5(45) = 50 − 22.5 = 27.5</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b) Profit</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">TR = P × Q = 27.5 × 45 = 1237.5\nTC = MC × Q = 5 × 45 = 225  (no fixed costs)\nProfit = TR − TC = 1237.5 − 225 = 1012.5</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c) Deadweight loss</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Competitive outcome: P = MC = 5\n5 = 50 − 0.5Q  →  Q_comp = 90\nDWL triangle = ½ × (P_mono − MC) × (Q_comp − Q_mono)\n= ½ × (27.5 − 5) × (90 − 45)\n= ½ × 22.5 × 45 = 506.25</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Note: profit-max steps from solution Ch13 Q10 (Q=45, P=27.5, profit=1012.5). DWL uses the slide method DWL = (P−MC)×(ΔQ)/2 comparing with the P=MC optimum.</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w2_2", "week": 2, "title": "Cartel Cheating Incentive (Oil Market)", "badge": "Week 2 Practice ②", "scenario": "Oil is produced by 10 countries, each producing 10 million barrels a day (MBD), for a total of 100 MBD. At that quantity the world price is $36 per barrel, so each country earns $360 million a day. The countries form a cartel and each agrees to produce 8 MBD.", "transactions": ["10 countries, each 10 MBD → 100 MBD total", "World price at 100 MBD = $36/barrel → each earns $360M/day", "Cartel agreement: each produces 8 MBD", "Nine members cheat to 10 MBD; one keeps its promise at 8 MBD"], "questions": ["(a) If nine members cheat (produce 10 MBD) while one keeps 8 MBD, what does each cheater earn?", "(b) What does the loyal (non-cheating) country earn?", "(c) Why does a cartel member have a greater incentive to cheat than a monopolist has to expand output?"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) &amp; (b) Earnings after cheating</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Each cheater earns $375 million a day.\nThe non-cheating country earns $300 million a day.\n(Answer: choice a, exercise Ch15 Q6.)</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c) Why the incentive to cheat is greater</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">When a MONOPOLY raises quantity, it bears ALL of the loss from the lower price.\nWhen a CARTEL MEMBER raises quantity, the losses are SHARED with the other members.\n→ A cartel member has a greater incentive to cheat (overproduce).</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">This is why cartel agreements are hard to maintain: each firm has the incentive to INCREASE PRODUCTION to earn larger profits (Weekly Test 2, Q2: b). Cartels also collapse via new entrants and government prosecution.</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w3_1", "week": 3, "title": "Asymmetric Information: Moral Hazard vs Adverse Selection", "badge": "Week 3 Practice ①", "scenario": "Test your ability to classify real-world situations as moral hazard, adverse selection, signaling, or a principal-agent problem, using the definitions from Chapter 24.", "transactions": [], "questions": ["(a) A cab driver takes an out-of-town rider on a longer route to her destination. Which problem is this an example of?", "(b) Which of the following is an example of moral hazard: (A) a car dealership recommends a customer replace barely used tires; (B) a driver drives faster than the speed limit; (C) an unhealthy person purchases health insurance; (D) a driver purchases car insurance?", "(c) Sellers of good-quality used cars are not able to sell for a price they are willing to accept. Identify the concept and the broader outcome.", "(d) Obtaining a college education signals what about a potential employee?"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Moral hazard. The driver exploits an information advantage (the rider doesn't know the area) AFTER the ride begins. Detours were longest when the information advantage was greatest. Answer: moral hazard.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Answer: A. The dealership exploits its information advantage to recommend unnecessary work after the customer arrives — a hidden ACTION. Note (C) 'an unhealthy person purchases health insurance' is ADVERSE SELECTION, not moral hazard — a classic trap.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">This is adverse selection, and the broader outcome is a market failure. Buyers pay the expected value (½ x $8,000) + (½ x $12,000) = $10,000; the plum owner (car worth $12,000) won't sell at $10,000, so high-quality used cars don't trade. Answer: market failure.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(d)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">A college education signals that the employee 'has determination and a relatively high IQ.' The signal is credible because it is an expensive action. Answer: c.</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w3_2", "week": 3, "title": "Budget Constraint & Consumer Optimization", "badge": "Week 3 Practice ②", "scenario": "An individual chooses between good A and good B. The unit price of good A is $2 and the unit price of good B is $5. The consumer has an income of $30.", "transactions": ["Price of good A (Pa) = $2", "Price of good B (Pb) = $5", "Income (I) = $30"], "questions": ["(a) Which consumption bundle (good A, good B) lies exactly on the edge of the budget constraint: (5,5), (5,4), (6,4), or (6,5)?", "(b) Consumers maximize their utility when what condition holds?", "(c) If the budget line shifts inward in a parallel way, what could have caused it?"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">The budget line is Pa*A + Pb*B = I, i.e. 2A + 5B = 30. Test each bundle:</div><table class=\"exam-table\"><tr><th>Bundle (A,B)</th><th>2A + 5B</th><th>On edge ($30)?</th></tr><tr><td>(5,5)</td><td>10 + 25 = 35</td><td>No (over budget)</td></tr><tr><td>(5,4)</td><td>10 + 20 = 30</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>(6,4)</td><td>12 + 20 = 32</td><td>No (over budget)</td></tr><tr><td>(6,5)</td><td>12 + 25 = 37</td><td>No (over budget)</td></tr></table><div class=\"exam-entry\">Answer: B = (5,4), since 2(5) + 5(4) = 30 exactly spends the income.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Utility is maximized when the marginal utility per dollar is equal across all goods consumed and all income is spent: MUa/Pa = MUb/Pb = ... = MUz/Pz. Answer: b.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">A parallel inward shift is caused by a decrease in income (prices unchanged keep the slope constant). A price change would instead rotate the line. Answer: the consumer's income decreased.</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w5_1", "week": 5, "title": "Nominal GDP, Real GDP and the GDP Deflator (Pizza & Pretzels)", "badge": "Week 5 Practice ①", "scenario": "An economy produces only pizza and pretzels. In 2010, pizza costs $20 and pretzels cost $1; in 2011, pizza costs $22 and pretzels cost $1.10. Quantities: 100,000 pizzas and 1,000,000 pretzels in 2010; 110,000 pizzas and 1,100,000 pretzels in 2011. Use 2010 as the base year for real GDP.", "transactions": ["2010: price of pizza = $20, price of pretzels = $1", "2011: price of pizza = $22, price of pretzels = $1.10", "2010 quantities: 100,000 pizzas; 1,000,000 pretzels", "2011 quantities: 110,000 pizzas; 1,100,000 pretzels"], "questions": ["(a) What is nominal GDP for 2010 and 2011?", "(b) What is real GDP (using 2010 prices) for 2010 and 2011, and the growth rate of real GDP?", "(c) Why does the real GDP growth rate differ from the nominal GDP growth rate?", "(d) Use the GDP data to find the inflation rate from 2010 to 2011 via the GDP deflator."], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) Nominal GDP</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">2010: (100,000 × $20) + (1,000,000 × $1) = $3,000,000</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">2011: (110,000 × $22) + (1,100,000 × $1.10) = $3,630,000</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b) Real GDP (2010 prices) &amp; growth</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">2010 real GDP = (100,000 × $20) + (1,000,000 × $1) = $3,000,000</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">2011 real GDP = (110,000 × $20) + (1,100,000 × $1) = $3,300,000</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Real GDP growth = [(3,300,000 − 3,000,000) ÷ 3,000,000] × 100 = 10%</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c) Why they differ</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Nominal GDP growth = [(3,630,000 − 3,000,000) ÷ 3,000,000] × 100 = 21%. Nominal growth (21%) exceeds real growth (10%) because nominal GDP includes the increase in prices from 2010 to 2011 in addition to the increase in production captured by real GDP.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(d) Inflation via GDP deflator</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">GDP deflator(2011) = (nominal GDP(2011) ÷ real GDP(2011)) × 100 = (3,630,000 ÷ 3,300,000) × 100 = 110</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Inflation 2010→2011 = 110 − 100 = 10%</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w5_2", "week": 5, "title": "Solow Steady State and a Capital-Destroying Disaster", "badge": "Week 5 Practice ②", "scenario": "Use the Solow model. (1) A small country's production function per hour of labor is Y = K^(1/2), with depreciation rate δ = 1% and investment rate γ = 10%. (2) Separately, a country starts in a steady state Y_SS = √K_SS and a natural disaster destroys half of its steady-state capital stock, leaving K1 = (1/2)K_SS.", "transactions": ["Production function: Y = K^(1/2) = √K", "Depreciation rate δ = 1% = 0.01", "Investment rate γ = 10% = 0.10", "Disaster: K1 = (1/2) × K_SS"], "questions": ["(a) What is the steady-state level of output for the small country (a=1, b=10, c=100, d=1,000)?", "(b) After the disaster, if K1 = (1/2)K_SS, does output fall by half to Y1 = (1/2)Y_SS? Explain.", "(c) What happens to this country in the immediate future and in the long run?"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) Steady-state output</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">At the steady state, investment = depreciation: γY = δK, i.e. γ√K = δK.</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">0.10√K = 0.01K  →  √K = 0.01K / 0.10 = 0.1K  →  √K / K = 0.1  →  1/√K = 0.1  →  √K = 10</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">So K = 100 and Y = √K = √100 = 10. ANSWER: b (10).</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b) Does output halve?</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">No. With K1 = (1/2)K_SS, Y1 = √((1/2)K_SS) = √(1/2) × √K_SS ≈ 0.71√K_SS, which is greater than 0.5√K_SS.</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Output falls by less than half because of the diminishing marginal product of capital: the remaining capital is relatively more productive than the destroyed units.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c) Immediate future vs long run</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">The higher marginal product of capital raises the growth rate of output in the immediate future (investment now exceeds depreciation). In the long run the country returns to its original steady-state levels of capital and output (cf. Germany and Japan after WWII).</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w6_1", "week": 6, "title": "Unemployment Rate & Labor Force", "badge": "Week 6 Practice 1", "scenario": "Two related labor-market problems on computing the unemployment rate. The labor force = employed workers + adults without jobs who are looking for work. People not interested in working, those who have given up looking (discouraged), full-time students, homemakers, and retirees are NOT in the labor force. Underemployed part-timers are counted as employed.", "transactions": ["Weekly Test Q1: adult population 200 million; 100 million employed; 10 million unemployed.", "Exercises Ch32 Q4: 50 million people, 30 million adults; of the adults, 5M not interested in working, 5M interested but gave up looking, 5M still looking; of those with jobs, 5M part-time wanting full-time and 10M full-time."], "questions": ["(a) Compute the unemployment rate for the Weekly Test case.", "(b) Compute the unemployment rate for the Exercises Ch32 Q4 case.", "(c) Does an increase in the number of underemployed workers raise the unemployment rate? (Ch32 Q7)"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) Weekly Test Q1</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Labor force = employed + unemployed = 100M + 10M = 110M<br>Unemployment rate = 10M / 110M = 0.0909 = 9.1%</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Answer: B (9.1%). Note: the adult population (200M) includes people NOT in the labor force, so it is NOT the denominator.</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b) Exercises Ch32 Q4</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Employed = 5M (part-time, wanting full-time -> still employed) + 10M (full-time) = 15M<br>Unemployed = 5M (still looking)<br>NOT in labor force = 5M (not interested) + 5M (gave up looking / discouraged)<br>Labor force = employed + unemployed = 15M + 5M = 20M<br>Unemployment rate = 5M / 20M = 25%</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Answer: c (25%).</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c) Ch32 Q7</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">False. Underemployed workers (part-timers who want full-time work) are counted as EMPLOYED, so an increase in underemployment does not raise the unemployment rate.</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w6_2", "week": 6, "title": "Quantity Theory, Potential Growth & the Fisher Effect", "badge": "Week 6 Practice 2", "scenario": "Calculations using the quantity theory of money (Mv = PYR; dynamic form M + v = P + YR) and the Fisher effect (i = E(pi) + r_equilibrium). The quantity theory is treated as an identity. In the long run money is neutral, so a fall in money growth lowers inflation, not the potential (Solow) growth rate.", "transactions": ["Ch31 Q6: money = $2.5 million, real GDP = $5 million, price level = 2.", "Ch32 Q17: initial spending growth M + v = 9% and inflation = 5%; then money growth falls so spending growth = 4% per year, lasting many years.", "Fisher effect (Ch31 Q16/Q26): nominal rate i, expected inflation E(pi), equilibrium real rate r_equilibrium; given any two, find the third."], "questions": ["(a) Find the velocity of money. (Ch31 Q6)", "(b) Use the quantity theory to find the potential (real) growth rate before the shock, then the long-run growth rate and inflation after spending growth falls to 4%. (Ch32 Q17)", "(c) If expected inflation E(pi) = 3% and the equilibrium real rate r_equilibrium = 2%, find the nominal interest rate i; then if i = 5% and E(pi) = 3%, find r_equilibrium."], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) Velocity (Ch31 Q6)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Mv = PYR  =>  v = PYR / M<br>v = (2 x 5,000,000) / 2,500,000 = 10,000,000 / 2,500,000 = 4</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Answer: a (v = 4).</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b) Potential growth & long-run inflation (Ch32 Q17)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Dynamic identity: M + v = P + YR  =>  Real growth YR = (M + v) - P<br>Before shock: 9% = 5% + YR  =>  YR = 4% (potential / Solow growth rate)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">After spending growth falls to 4% (long run, money neutral):<br>Potential growth rate stays at 4% (unchanged by money).<br>4% = inflation + 4%  =>  long-run inflation = 0%</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c) Fisher effect (Ch31 Q16/Q26)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">i = E(pi) + r_equilibrium = 3% + 2% = 5%</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Solve for the real rate: r_equilibrium = i - E(pi) = 5% - 3% = 2%</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w7_1", "week": 7, "title": "Money Multiplier and Money Supply Expansion", "badge": "Week 7 Practice & Test", "scenario": "Use the money multiplier (MM = 1 / reserve ratio) to find the total potential increase in the money supply from an injection of new reserves. The total potential change equals the change in reserves divided by the reserve ratio.", "transactions": ["Case 1 (Exercise 2): reserve ratio = 20%, the Fed increases bank reserves by $100,000", "Case 2 (Weekly Test Q1): reserve ratio = 10%, the Fed's open market purchase credits a bank by $160,000"], "questions": ["(a) With a 20% reserve ratio and $100,000 of new reserves, what is the total potential increase in the money supply?", "(b) With a 10% reserve ratio and a $160,000 open market purchase, by how much is the money supply expected to change?", "(c) Why is the actual increase usually smaller than the theoretical maximum?"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a) Reserve ratio = 20%</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Money multiplier MM = 1 / 0.20 = 5</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Total potential increase = $100,000 / 0.20 = $100,000 x 5 = $500,000</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Answer: $500,000 (option c)</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b) Reserve ratio = 10%</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Money multiplier MM = 1 / 0.10 = 10</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Total potential increase = $160,000 / 0.10 = $160,000 x 10 = $1,600,000</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Answer: $1.6 million (option B)</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c) Why smaller in practice</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">The actual multiplier is lower because banks often hold excess reserves and some deposits leak out as cash, so M1 and M2 expand by less than the theoretical maximum.</div>"}, {"id": "ep_w7_2", "week": 7, "title": "Balance of Payments Practice (Current + Capital = Change in Reserves)", "badge": "Week 7 Practice", "scenario": "Use the balance of payments identity: Current account + Capital account = Change in official reserves. The balance of payments must always balance, so any spending in excess of earning must be financed from somewhere.", "transactions": ["(a) Current account = -$10, Capital account = +$15", "(b) Current account = -$10, Change in reserves = -$3", "(c) College expenses = $12,000, barista income = $4,000, no change in cash savings"], "questions": ["(a) What is the change in reserves?", "(b) What is the capital account?", "(c) What is your current account, and (if reserves are unchanged) what is the capital account?"], "solHtml": "<div class=\"exam-sol-label\">Identity</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Current account + Capital account = Change in official reserves</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(a)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Change in reserves = Current + Capital = (-$10) + (+$15) = +$5</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(b)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Capital account = Change in reserves - Current account = (-$3) - (-$10) = +$7</div><div class=\"exam-sol-label\">(c)</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Current account = Income - Spending = $4,000 - $12,000 = -$8,000</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">Reserves unchanged, so: Capital account = Change in reserves - Current account = 0 - (-$8,000) = +$8,000</div><div class=\"exam-entry\">You must have obtained the $8,000 of spending money from somewhere (borrowing from parents or a bank).</div>"}];
